P_HTM[885]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[886]="*5. Kasiṇasuttaṃ**Meditation on Universals*";
P_HTM[887]="*“Dasayimāni, bhikkhave, kasiṇāyatanāni.**“Mendicants, there are these ten universal dimensions of meditation.*";
P_HTM[888]="*Katamāni dasa?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[889]="*Pathavīkasiṇameko sañjānāti uddhaṃ adho tiriyaṃ advayaṃ appamāṇaṃ;**Someone perceives the meditation on universal earth above, below, across, non-dual and limitless.*";
P_HTM[890]="*āpokasiṇameko sañjānāti … pe …**They perceive the meditation on universal water …*";
P_HTM[891]="*tejokasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal fire …*";
P_HTM[892]="*vāyokasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal air …*";
P_HTM[893]="*nīlakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal blue …*";
P_HTM[894]="*pītakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal yellow …*";
P_HTM[895]="*lohitakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal red …*";
P_HTM[896]="*odātakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal white …*";
P_HTM[897]="*ākāsakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal space …*";
P_HTM[898]="*viññāṇakasiṇameko sañjānāti uddhaṃ adho tiriyaṃ advayaṃ appamāṇaṃ.**They perceive the meditation on universal consciousness above, below, across, non-dual and limitless.*";
P_HTM[899]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dasa kasiṇāyatanānī”ti.**These are the ten universal dimensions of meditation.”*";
P_HTM[900]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[901]="*6. Kāḷīsuttaṃ**With Kāḷī*";
P_HTM[902]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā mahākaccāno avantīsu viharati kuraraghare pavatte pabbate.**At one time Venerable Mahākaccāna was staying in the land of the Avantis near Kuraraghara on Steep Mountain.*";
P_HTM[903]="*Atha kho kāḷī upāsikā kuraragharikā yenāyasmā mahākaccāno tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ mahākaccānaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho kāḷī upāsikā kuraragharikā āyasmantaṃ mahākaccānaṃ etadavoca:**Then the laywoman Kāḷī of Kurughara went up to Venerable Mahākaccāna, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[904]="*“vuttamidaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā kumāripañhesu:**“Sir, this was said by the Buddha in ‘The Maidens’ Questions’:*";
P_HTM[905]="*‘Atthassa pattiṃ hadayassa santiṃ,**‘I’ve reached the goal, peace of heart.*";
P_HTM[906]="*Jetvāna senaṃ piyasātarūpaṃ;**Having conquered the army of the likable and pleasant,*";
P_HTM[907]="*Ekohaṃ jhāyaṃ sukhamanubodhiṃ,**alone, practicing absorption, I awakened to bliss.*";
P_HTM[908]="*Tasmā janena na karomi sakkhiṃ;**That’s why I don’t get too close to people,*";
P_HTM[909]="*Sakkhī na sampajjati kenaci me’ti.**and no-one gets too close to me.’*";
P_HTM[910]="*Imassa kho, bhante, bhagavatā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa kathaṃ vitthārena attho daṭṭhabbo”ti?**How should we see the detailed meaning of the Buddha’s brief statement?”*";
P_HTM[911]="*“Pathavīkasiṇasamāpattiparamā kho, bhagini, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā ‘attho’ti abhinibbattesuṃ.**“Sister, some ascetics and brahmins regard the attainment of the meditation on universal earth to be the ultimate. Thinking ‘this is the goal’, they are reborn.*";
P_HTM[912]="*Yāvatā kho, bhagini, pathavīkasiṇasamāpattiparamatā, tadabhiññāsi bhagavā.**The Buddha directly knew the extent to which the attainment of the meditation on universal earth was the ultimate.*";
P_HTM[913]="*Tadabhiññāya bhagavā assādamaddasa ādīnavamaddasa nissaraṇamaddasa maggāmaggañāṇadassanamaddasa.**Directly knowing this he saw the beginning, the drawback, and the escape. And he saw the knowledge and vision of the variety of paths.*";
P_HTM[914]="*Tassa assādadassanahetu ādīnavadassanahetu nissaraṇadassanahetu maggāmaggañāṇadassanahetu atthassa patti hadayassa santi viditā hoti.**Because he saw the beginning, the drawback, and the escape, and he saw the knowledge and vision of the variety of paths, he knew that he had reached the goal, peace of heart.*";
P_HTM[915]="*Āpokasiṇasamāpattiparamā kho, bhagini … pe …**Some ascetics and brahmins regard the attainment of the meditation on universal water to be the ultimate. Thinking ‘this is the goal’, they are reborn. …*";
P_HTM[916]="*tejokasiṇasamāpattiparamā kho, bhagini …**Some ascetics and brahmins regard the attainment of the meditation on universal fire …*";
P_HTM[917]="*vāyokasiṇasamāpattiparamā kho, bhagini …**universal air …*";
P_HTM[918]="*nīlakasiṇasamāpattiparamā kho, bhagini …**universal blue …*";
P_HTM[919]="*pītakasiṇasamāpattiparamā kho, bhagini …**universal yellow …*";
P_HTM[920]="*lohitakasiṇasamāpattiparamā kho, bhagini …**universal red …*";
P_HTM[921]="*odātakasiṇasamāpattiparamā kho, bhagini …**universal white …*";
P_HTM[922]="*ākāsakasiṇasamāpattiparamā kho, bhagini …**universal space …*";
P_HTM[923]="*viññāṇakasiṇasamāpattiparamā kho, bhagini, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā ‘attho’ti abhinibbattesuṃ.**universal consciousness to be the ultimate. Thinking ‘this is the goal’, they are reborn.*";
P_HTM[924]="*Yāvatā kho, bhagini, viññāṇakasiṇasamāpattiparamatā, tadabhiññāsi bhagavā.**The Buddha directly knew the extent to which the attainment of the meditation on universal consciousness was the ultimate.*";
P_HTM[925]="*Tadabhiññāya bhagavā assādamaddasa … ādīnavamaddasa … nissaraṇamaddasa … maggāmaggañāṇadassanamaddasa …**Directly knowing this he saw the beginning, the drawback, and the escape. And he saw the knowledge and vision of the variety of paths.*";
P_HTM[926]="*tassa assādadassanahetu ādīnavadassanahetu nissaraṇadassanahetu maggāmaggañāṇadassanahetu atthassa patti hadayassa santi viditā hoti.**Because he saw the beginning, the drawback, and the escape, and he saw the knowledge and vision of the variety of paths, he knew that he had reached the goal, peace of heart.*";
P_HTM[927]="*Iti kho, bhagini, yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā kumāripañhesu:**So, sister, that’s how to understand the detailed meaning of what the Buddha said in brief in ‘The Maiden’s Questions’:*";
P_HTM[928]="*‘Atthassa pattiṃ hadayassa santiṃ,**‘I’ve reached the goal, peace of heart.*";
P_HTM[929]="*Jetvāna senaṃ piyasātarūpaṃ;**Having conquered the army of the likable and pleasant,*";
P_HTM[930]="*Ekohaṃ jhāyaṃ sukhamanubodhiṃ,**alone, practicing absorption, I awakened to bliss.*";
P_HTM[931]="*Tasmā janena na karomi sakkhiṃ;**That’s why I don’t get too close to people,*";
P_HTM[932]="*Sakkhī na sampajjati kenaci me’ti.**and no-one gets too close to me.’”*";
P_HTM[933]="*Imassa kho, bhagini, bhagavatā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa evaṃ vitthārena attho daṭṭhabbo”ti.* **";
P_HTM[934]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[935]="*7. Paṭhamamahāpañhāsuttaṃ**The Great Questions (1st)*";
P_HTM[936]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[937]="*Atha kho sambahulā bhikkhū pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya sāvatthiṃ piṇḍāya pavisiṃsu.**Then several mendicants robed up in the morning and, taking their bowls and robes, entered Sāvatthī for alms.*";
P_HTM[938]="*Atha kho tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ etadahosi:**Then it occurred to him,*";
P_HTM[939]="*“atippago kho tāva sāvatthiyaṃ piṇḍāya carituṃ;**“It’s too early to wander for alms in Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[940]="*yannūna mayaṃ yena aññatitthiyānaṃ paribbājakānaṃ ārāmo tenupasaṅkameyyāmā”ti.**Why don’t we go to the monastery of the wanderers who follow other paths?”*";
P_HTM[941]="*Atha kho te bhikkhū yena aññatitthiyānaṃ paribbājakānaṃ ārāmo tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā tehi aññatitthiyehi paribbājakehi saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu.**Then they went to the monastery of the wanderers who follow other paths, and exchanged greetings with the wanderers there.*";
P_HTM[942]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinne kho te bhikkhū te aññatitthiyā paribbājakā etadavocuṃ:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, they sat down to one side. The wanderers said to them:*";
P_HTM[943]="*“Samaṇo, āvuso, gotamo sāvakānaṃ evaṃ dhammaṃ deseti:**“Reverends, the ascetic Gotama teaches his disciples like this:*";
P_HTM[944]="*‘etha tumhe, bhikkhave, sabbaṃ dhammaṃ abhijānātha, sabbaṃ dhammaṃ abhiññāya viharathā’ti;**‘Please, mendicants, directly know all things. Meditate having directly known all things.’*";
P_HTM[945]="*mayampi kho, āvuso, sāvakānaṃ evaṃ dhammaṃ desema:**We too teach our disciples:*";
P_HTM[946]="*‘etha tumhe, āvuso, sabbaṃ dhammaṃ abhijānātha, sabbaṃ dhammaṃ abhiññāya viharathā’ti.**‘Please, reverends, directly know all things. Live having directly known all things.’*";
P_HTM[947]="*Idha no, āvuso, ko viseso ko adhippayāso kiṃ nānākaraṇaṃ samaṇassa vā gotamassa amhākaṃ vā, yadidaṃ dhammadesanāya vā dhammadesanaṃ anusāsaniyā vā anusāsanin”ti?**What, then, is the difference between the ascetic Gotama’s teaching and instruction and ours?”*";
P_HTM[948]="*Atha kho te bhikkhū tesaṃ aññatitthiyānaṃ paribbājakānaṃ bhāsitaṃ neva abhinandiṃsu nappaṭikkosiṃsu.**Those mendicants neither approved nor dismissed that statement of the wanderers who follow other paths.*";
P_HTM[949]="*Anabhinanditvā appaṭikkositvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkamiṃsu:**They got up from their seat, thinking,*";
P_HTM[950]="*“bhagavato santike etassa bhāsitassa atthaṃ ājānissāmā”ti.**“We will learn the meaning of this statement from the Buddha himself.”*";
P_HTM[951]="*Atha kho te bhikkhū sāvatthiyaṃ piṇḍāya caritvā pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkantā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then, after the meal, when they returned from alms-round, they went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and told him what had happened.*";
P_HTM[952]="*“Idha mayaṃ, bhante, pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya sāvatthiṃ piṇḍāya pavisimhā.* **";
P_HTM[953]="*Tesaṃ no, bhante, amhākaṃ etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[954]="*‘atippago kho tāva sāvatthiyaṃ piṇḍāya carituṃ;* **";
P_HTM[955]="*yannūna mayaṃ yena aññatitthiyānaṃ paribbājakānaṃ ārāmo tenupasaṅkameyyāmā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[956]="*Atha kho mayaṃ, bhante, yena aññatitthiyānaṃ paribbājakānaṃ ārāmo tenupasaṅkamimhā; upasaṅkamitvā tehi aññatitthiyehi paribbājakehi saddhiṃ sammodimhā.* **";
P_HTM[957]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdimhā. Ekamantaṃ nisinne kho, bhante, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā amhe etadavocuṃ:* **";
P_HTM[958]="*‘Samaṇo, āvuso, gotamo sāvakānaṃ evaṃ dhammaṃ deseti—* **";
P_HTM[959]="*etha tumhe, bhikkhave, sabbaṃ dhammaṃ abhijānātha, sabbaṃ dhammaṃ abhiññāya viharathāti;* **";
P_HTM[960]="*mayampi kho, āvuso, sāvakānaṃ evaṃ dhammaṃ desema—* **";
P_HTM[961]="*etha tumhe, āvuso, sabbaṃ dhammaṃ abhijānātha, sabbaṃ dhammaṃ abhiññāya viharathāti.* **";
P_HTM[962]="*Idha no, āvuso, ko viseso ko adhippayāso kiṃ nānākaraṇaṃ samaṇassa vā gotamassa amhākaṃ vā, yadidaṃ dhammadesanāya vā dhammadesanaṃ anusāsaniyā vā anusāsanin’ti?* **";
P_HTM[963]="*Atha kho mayaṃ, bhante, tesaṃ aññatitthiyānaṃ paribbājakānaṃ bhāsitaṃ neva abhinandimhā nappaṭikkosimhā.* **";
P_HTM[964]="*Anabhinanditvā appaṭikkositvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkamimhā:* **";
P_HTM[965]="*‘bhagavato santike etassa bhāsitassa atthaṃ ājānissāmā’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[966]="*“Evaṃvādino, bhikkhave, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evamassu vacanīyā:**“Mendicants, when wanderers who follow other paths say this, you should say to them:*";
P_HTM[967]="*‘eko, āvuso, pañho eko uddeso ekaṃ veyyākaraṇaṃ, dve pañhā dve uddesā dve veyyākaraṇāni, tayo pañhā tayo uddesā tīṇi veyyākaraṇāni, cattāro pañhā cattāro uddesā cattāri veyyākaraṇāni, pañca pañhā pañcuddesā pañca veyyākaraṇāni, cha pañhā cha uddesā cha veyyākaraṇāni, satta pañhā sattuddesā satta veyyākaraṇāni, aṭṭha pañhā aṭṭhuddesā aṭṭha veyyākaraṇāni, nava pañhā navuddesā nava veyyākaraṇāni, dasa pañhā dasuddesā dasa veyyākaraṇānī’ti.**‘One thing: question, passage for recitation, and answer. Two … three … four … five … six … seven … eight … nine … ten things: question, passage for recitation, and answer.’*";
P_HTM[968]="*Evaṃ puṭṭhā, bhikkhave, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā na ceva sampāyissanti, uttari ca vighātaṃ āpajjissanti.**Questioned like this, the wanderers who follow other paths would be stumped, and, in addition, would get frustrated.*";
P_HTM[969]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[970]="*Yathā taṃ, bhikkhave, avisayasmiṃ.**Because they’re out of their element.*";
P_HTM[971]="*Nāhaṃ taṃ, bhikkhave, passāmi sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya yo imesaṃ pañhānaṃ veyyākaraṇena cittaṃ ārādheyya, aññatra tathāgatena vā tathāgatasāvakena vā ito vā pana sutvā.**I don’t see anyone in this world—with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans—who could provide a satisfying answer to these questions except for the Realized One or his disciple or someone who has heard it from them.*";
P_HTM[972]="*‘Eko pañho eko uddeso ekaṃ veyyākaraṇan’ti,**‘One thing: question, passage for recitation, and answer.’*";
P_HTM[973]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[974]="*Ekadhamme, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.**Becoming completely disillusioned, dispassionate, and freed regarding one thing, seeing its limits and fully comprehending its meaning, a mendicant makes an end of suffering in this very life.*";
P_HTM[975]="*Katamasmiṃ ekadhamme?**What one thing?*";
P_HTM[976]="*‘Sabbe sattā āhāraṭṭhitikā’—**‘All sentient beings are sustained by food.’*";
P_HTM[977]="*imasmiṃ kho, bhikkhave, ekadhamme bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.**Becoming completely disillusioned, dispassionate, and freed regarding this one thing, seeing its limits and fully comprehending its meaning, a mendicant makes an end of suffering in this very life.*";
P_HTM[978]="*‘Eko pañho eko uddeso ekaṃ veyyākaraṇan’ti,**‘One thing: question, passage for recitation, and answer.’*";
P_HTM[979]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ. (1)**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[980]="*‘Dve pañhā dve uddesā dve veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[981]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[982]="*Dvīsu, bhikkhave, dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[983]="*Katamesu dvīsu?**What two?*";
P_HTM[984]="*Nāme ca rūpe ca—**Name and form. …*";
P_HTM[985]="*imesu kho, bhikkhave, dvīsu dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[986]="*‘Dve pañhā dve uddesā dve veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ. (2)* **";
P_HTM[987]="*‘Tayo pañhā tayo uddesā tīṇi veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[988]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[989]="*Tīsu, bhikkhave, dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[990]="*Katamesu tīsu?**What three?*";
P_HTM[991]="*Tīsu vedanāsu—**Three feelings. …*";
P_HTM[992]="*imesu kho, bhikkhave, tīsu dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[993]="*‘Tayo pañhā tayo uddesā tīṇi veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ. (3)* **";
P_HTM[994]="*‘Cattāro pañhā cattāro uddesā cattāri veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[995]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[996]="*Catūsu, bhikkhave, dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[997]="*Katamesu catūsu?**What four?*";
P_HTM[998]="*Catūsu āhāresu—**The four foods. …*";
P_HTM[999]="*imesu kho, bhikkhave, catūsu dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1000]="*‘Cattāro pañhā cattāro uddesā cattāri veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ. (4)* **";
P_HTM[1001]="*‘Pañca pañhā pañcuddesā pañca veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1002]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[1003]="*Pañcasu, bhikkhave, dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1004]="*Katamesu pañcasu?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1005]="*Pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu—**The five grasping aggregates. …*";
P_HTM[1006]="*imesu kho, bhikkhave, pañcasu dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1007]="*‘Pañca pañhā pañcuddesā pañca veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ. (5)* **";
P_HTM[1008]="*‘Cha pañhā cha uddesā cha veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1009]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[1010]="*Chasu, bhikkhave, dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1011]="*Katamesu chasu?**What six?*";
P_HTM[1012]="*Chasu ajjhattikesu āyatanesu—**The six interior sense fields. …*";
P_HTM[1013]="*imesu kho, bhikkhave, chasu dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1014]="*‘Cha pañhā cha uddesā cha veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ. (6)* **";
P_HTM[1015]="*‘Satta pañhā sattuddesā satta veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1016]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[1017]="*Sattasu, bhikkhave, dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1018]="*Katamesu sattasu?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[1019]="*Sattasu viññāṇaṭṭhitīsu—**The seven planes of consciousness. …*";
P_HTM[1020]="*imesu kho, bhikkhave, sattasu dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1021]="*‘Satta pañhā sattuddesā satta veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ. (7)* **";
P_HTM[1022]="*‘Aṭṭha pañhā aṭṭhuddesā aṭṭha veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1023]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[1024]="*Aṭṭhasu, bhikkhave, dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1025]="*Katamesu aṭṭhasu?**What eight?*";
P_HTM[1026]="*Aṭṭhasu lokadhammesu—**The eight worldly conditions. …*";
P_HTM[1027]="*imesu kho, bhikkhave, aṭṭhasu dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno … pe … dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1028]="*‘Aṭṭha pañhā aṭṭhuddesā aṭṭha veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ. (8)* **";
P_HTM[1029]="*‘Nava pañhā navuddesā nava veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1030]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[1031]="*Navasu, bhikkhave, dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1032]="*Katamesu navasu?**What nine?*";
P_HTM[1033]="*Navasu sattāvāsesu—**The nine abodes of sentient beings. …*";
P_HTM[1034]="*imesu kho, bhikkhave, navasu dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1035]="*‘Nava pañhā navuddesā nava veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ. (9)* **";
P_HTM[1036]="*‘Dasa pañhā dasuddesā dasa veyyākaraṇānī’ti,**‘Ten things: question, passage for recitation, and answer.’*";
P_HTM[1037]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[1038]="*Dasasu, bhikkhave, dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.**Becoming completely disillusioned, dispassionate, and freed regarding ten things, seeing their limits and fully comprehending their meaning, a mendicant makes an end of suffering in this very life.*";
P_HTM[1039]="*Katamesu dasasu?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[1040]="*Dasasu akusalesu kammapathesu—**The ten ways of performing unskillful deeds.*";
P_HTM[1041]="*imesu kho, bhikkhave, dasasu dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.**Becoming completely disillusioned, dispassionate, and freed regarding these ten things, seeing their limits and fully comprehending their meaning, a mendicant makes an end of suffering in this very life.*";
P_HTM[1042]="*‘Dasa pañhā dasuddesā dasa veyyākaraṇānī’ti,**‘Ten things: question, passage for recitation, and answer.’*";
P_HTM[1043]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ idametaṃ paṭicca vuttan”ti. (10)**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.”*";
P_HTM[1044]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1045]="*8. Dutiyamahāpañhāsuttaṃ**The Great Questions (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1046]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā kajaṅgalāyaṃ viharati veḷuvane.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Kajaṅgalā in a bamboo grove.*";
P_HTM[1047]="*Atha kho sambahulā kajaṅgalakā upāsakā yena kajaṅgalikā bhikkhunī tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā kajaṅgalikaṃ bhikkhuniṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho kajaṅgalakā upāsakā kajaṅgalikaṃ bhikkhuniṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then several lay followers of Kajaṅgalā went to the nun Kajaṅgalikā, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to her:*";
P_HTM[1048]="*“Vuttamidaṃ, ayye, bhagavatā mahāpañhesu:**“Ma’am, this was said by the Buddha in ‘The Great Questions’:*";
P_HTM[1049]="*‘eko pañho eko uddeso ekaṃ veyyākaraṇaṃ, dve pañhā dve uddesā dve veyyākaraṇāni, tayo pañhā tayo uddesā tīṇi veyyākaraṇāni, cattāro pañhā cattāro uddesā cattāri veyyākaraṇāni, pañca pañhā pañcuddesā pañca veyyākaraṇāni, cha pañhā cha uddesā cha veyyākaraṇāni, satta pañhā sattuddesā satta veyyākaraṇāni, aṭṭha pañhā aṭṭhuddesā aṭṭha veyyākaraṇāni, nava pañhā navuddesā nava veyyākaraṇāni, dasa pañhā dasuddesā dasa veyyākaraṇānī’ti.**‘One thing: question, passage for recitation, and answer. Two … three … four … five … six … seven … eight … nine … ten things: question, passage for recitation, and answer.’*";
P_HTM[1050]="*Imassa nu kho, ayye, bhagavatā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa kathaṃ vitthārena attho daṭṭhabbo”ti?**How should we see the detailed meaning of the Buddha’s brief statement?”*";
P_HTM[1051]="*“Na kho panetaṃ, āvuso, bhagavato sammukhā sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ, napi manobhāvanīyānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ sammukhā sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ;**“Good people, I haven’t heard and learned this in the presence of the Buddha or from esteemed mendicants.*";
P_HTM[1052]="*api ca yathā mettha khāyati**But as to how it seems to me,*";
P_HTM[1053]="*taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[1054]="*“Evaṃ, ayye”ti, kho kajaṅgalakā upāsakā kajaṅgalikāya bhikkhuniyā paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, ma’am,” replied the lay followers.*";
P_HTM[1055]="*Kajaṅgalikā bhikkhunī etadavoca:**The nun Kajaṅgalikā said this:*";
P_HTM[1056]="*“‘Eko pañho eko uddeso ekaṃ veyyākaraṇan’ti, iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā.**‘One thing: question, passage for recitation, and answer.’ That’s what the Buddha said,*";
P_HTM[1057]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**but why did he say it?*";
P_HTM[1058]="*Ekadhamme, āvuso, bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.**Becoming completely disillusioned, dispassionate, and freed regarding one thing, seeing its limits and fully comprehending its meaning, a mendicant makes an end of suffering in this very life.*";
P_HTM[1059]="*Katamasmiṃ ekadhamme?**What one thing?*";
P_HTM[1060]="*Sabbe sattā āhāraṭṭhitikā—**‘All sentient beings are sustained by food.’*";
P_HTM[1061]="*imasmiṃ kho, āvuso, ekadhamme bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.**Becoming completely disillusioned, dispassionate, and freed regarding this one thing, seeing its limits and fully comprehending its meaning, a mendicant makes an end of suffering in this very life.*";
P_HTM[1062]="*‘Eko pañho eko uddeso ekaṃ veyyākaraṇan’ti, iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**‘One thing: question, passage for recitation, and answer.’ That’s what the Buddha said, and this is why he said it.*";
P_HTM[1063]="*‘Dve pañhā dve uddesā dve veyyākaraṇānī’ti iti, kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā.* **";
P_HTM[1064]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[1065]="*Dvīsu, āvuso, dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1066]="*Katamesu dvīsu?**What two?*";
P_HTM[1067]="*Nāme ca rūpe ca … pe …**Name and form. …*";
P_HTM[1068]="*katamesu tīsu?**What three?*";
P_HTM[1069]="*Tīsu vedanāsu—**Three feelings. …*";
P_HTM[1070]="*imesu kho, āvuso, tīsu dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1071]="*‘Tayo pañhā tayo uddesā tīṇi veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1072]="*‘Cattāro pañhā cattāro uddesā cattāri veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā.* **";
P_HTM[1073]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[1074]="*Catūsu, āvuso, dhammesu bhikkhu sammā subhāvitacitto sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.**With a mind well developed in four things—seeing their limits and fully comprehending their meaning—a mendicant makes an end of suffering in this very life.*";
P_HTM[1075]="*Katamesu catūsu?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1076]="*Catūsu satipaṭṭhānesu—**The four kinds of mindfulness meditation. …*";
P_HTM[1077]="*imesu kho, āvuso, catūsu dhammesu bhikkhu sammā subhāvitacitto sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.**With a mind well developed in these four things—seeing their limits and fully fathoming their meaning—a mendicant makes an end of suffering in this very life. …*";
P_HTM[1078]="*‘Cattāro pañhā cattāro uddesā cattāri veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1079]="*‘Pañca pañhā pañcuddesā pañca veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā.* **";
P_HTM[1080]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[1081]="*Pañcasu, āvuso, dhammesu bhikkhu sammā subhāvitacitto sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1082]="*Katamesu pañcasu?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1083]="*Pañcasu indriyesu … pe …**The five faculties. …*";
P_HTM[1084]="*katamesu chasu?**What six?*";
P_HTM[1085]="*Chasu nissaraṇīyāsu dhātūsu … pe …**The six elements of escape. …*";
P_HTM[1086]="*katamesu sattasu?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[1087]="*Sattasu bojjhaṅgesu … pe …**The seven awakening factors. …*";
P_HTM[1088]="*katamesu aṭṭhasu?**What eight?*";
P_HTM[1089]="*Aṭṭhasu ariyaaṭṭhaṅgikamaggesu—**The noble eightfold path. …*";
P_HTM[1090]="*imesu kho, āvuso, aṭṭhasu dhammesu bhikkhu sammā subhāvitacitto sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1091]="*‘Aṭṭha pañhā aṭṭhuddesā aṭṭha veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1092]="*‘Nava pañhā navuddesā nava veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā.* **";
P_HTM[1093]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[1094]="*Navasu, āvuso, dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.**Becoming completely disillusioned, dispassionate, and freed regarding nine things, seeing their limits and fully comprehending their meaning, a mendicant makes an end of suffering in this very life.*";
P_HTM[1095]="*Katamesu navasu?**What nine?*";
P_HTM[1096]="*Navasu sattāvāsesu—**The nine abodes of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[1097]="*imesu kho, āvuso, navasu dhammesu bhikkhu sammā nibbindamāno sammā virajjamāno sammā vimuccamāno sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.**Becoming completely disillusioned, dispassionate, and freed regarding these nine things, seeing their limits and fully comprehending their meaning, a mendicant makes an end of suffering in this very life.*";
P_HTM[1098]="*‘Nava pañhā navuddesā nava veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1099]="*‘Dasa pañhā dasuddesā dasa veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā.**‘Ten things: question, passage for recitation, and answer.’ That’s what the Buddha said,*";
P_HTM[1100]="*Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**but why did he say it?*";
P_HTM[1101]="*Dasasu, āvuso, dhammesu bhikkhu sammā subhāvitacitto sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.**Becoming well developed in ten things—seeing their limits and fully fathoming their meaning—a mendicant makes an end of suffering in this very life.*";
P_HTM[1102]="*Katamesu dasasu?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[1103]="*Dasasu kusalesu kammapathesu—**The ten ways of performing skillful deeds.*";
P_HTM[1104]="*imesu kho, āvuso, dasasu dhammesu bhikkhu sammā subhāvitacitto sammā pariyantadassāvī sammadatthaṃ abhisamecca diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhassantakaro hoti.**With a mind well developed in these ten things—seeing their limits and fully fathoming their meaning—a mendicant makes an end of suffering in this very life.*";
P_HTM[1105]="*‘Dasa pañhā dasuddesā dasa veyyākaraṇānī’ti, iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**‘Ten things: question, passage for recitation, and answer.’ That’s what the Buddha said, and this is why he said it.*";
P_HTM[1106]="*Iti kho, āvuso, yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā saṃkhittena bhāsitāsu mahāpañhāsu:**That’s how I understand the detailed meaning of what the Buddha said in brief in ‘The Great Questions’.*";
P_HTM[1107]="*‘eko pañho eko uddeso ekaṃ veyyākaraṇaṃ … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1108]="*dasa pañhā dasuddesā dasa veyyākaraṇānī’ti, imassa kho ahaṃ, āvuso, bhagavatā saṃkhittena bhāsitassa evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāmi.* **";
P_HTM[1109]="*Ākaṅkhamānā ca pana tumhe, āvuso, bhagavantaññeva upasaṅkamitvā etamatthaṃ paṭipuccheyyātha.**If you wish, you may go to the Buddha and ask him about this.*";
P_HTM[1110]="*Yathā vo bhagavā byākaroti tathā naṃ dhāreyyāthā”ti.**You should remember it in line with the Buddha’s answer.”*";
P_HTM[1111]="*“Evaṃ, ayye”ti kho kajaṅgalakā upāsakā kajaṅgalikāya kho bhikkhuniyā bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā kajaṅgalikaṃ bhikkhuniṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu.**“Yes, ma’am,” replied those lay followers, approving and agreeing with what the nun Kajaṅgalikā said. Then they got up from their seat, bowed, and respectfully circled her, keeping her on their right. Then they went to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side,*";
P_HTM[1112]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho kajaṅgalakā upāsakā yāvatako ahosi kajaṅgalikāya bhikkhuniyā saddhiṃ kathāsallāpo, taṃ sabbaṃ bhagavato ārocesuṃ.**and informed the Buddha of all they had discussed.*";
P_HTM[1113]="*“Sādhu sādhu, gahapatayo.**“Good, good, householders.*";
P_HTM[1114]="*Paṇḍitā, gahapatayo, kajaṅgalikā bhikkhunī. Mahāpaññā, gahapatayo, kajaṅgalikā bhikkhunī.**The nun Kajaṅgalikā is astute, she has great wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1115]="*Mañcepi tumhe, gahapatayo, upasaṅkamitvā etamatthaṃ paṭipuccheyyātha, ahampi cetaṃ evamevaṃ byākareyyaṃ yathā taṃ kajaṅgalikāya bhikkhuniyā byākataṃ.**If you came to me and asked this question, I would answer it in exactly the same way as the nun Kajaṅgalikā.*";
P_HTM[1116]="*Eso ceva tassa attho. Evañca naṃ dhāreyyāthā”ti.**That is what it means, and that’s how you should remember it.”*";
P_HTM[1117]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1118]="*9. Paṭhamakosalasuttaṃ**Kosala (1st)*";
P_HTM[1119]="*“Yāvatā, bhikkhave, kāsikosalā, yāvatā rañño pasenadissa kosalassa vijitaṃ, rājā tattha pasenadi kosalo aggamakkhāyati.**“As far as Kāsi and Kosala extend, and as far as the dominion of King Pasenadi of Kosala extends, King Pasenadi is said to be the foremost.*";
P_HTM[1120]="*Raññopi kho, bhikkhave, pasenadissa kosalassa attheva aññathattaṃ atthi vipariṇāmo.**But even King Pasenadi decays and perishes.*";
P_HTM[1121]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako tasmimpi nibbindati.**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with it.*";
P_HTM[1122]="*Tasmiṃ nibbindanto agge virajjati, pageva hīnasmiṃ. (1)**Their desire fades away even for the foremost, let alone the inferior.*";
P_HTM[1123]="*Yāvatā, bhikkhave, candimasūriyā pariharanti disā bhanti virocamānā, tāva sahassadhā loko.**A galaxy extends a thousand times as far as the moon and sun revolve and the shining ones light up the quarters.*";
P_HTM[1124]="*Tasmiṃ sahassadhā loke sahassaṃ candānaṃ sahassaṃ sūriyānaṃ sahassaṃ sinerupabbatarājānaṃ sahassaṃ jambudīpānaṃ sahassaṃ aparagoyānānaṃ sahassaṃ uttarakurūnaṃ sahassaṃ pubbavidehānaṃ cattāri mahāsamuddasahassāni cattāri mahārājasahassāni sahassaṃ cātumahārājikānaṃ sahassaṃ tāvatiṃsānaṃ sahassaṃ yāmānaṃ sahassaṃ tusitānaṃ sahassaṃ nimmānaratīnaṃ sahassaṃ paranimmitavasavattīnaṃ sahassaṃ brahmalokānaṃ.**In that galaxy there are a thousand moons, a thousand suns, a thousand Sinerus king of mountains, a thousand Indias, a thousand Western Continents, a thousand Northern Continents, a thousand Eastern Continents, four thousand oceans, four thousand Great Kings, a thousand realms of the Gods of the Four Great Kings, a thousand realms of the Gods of the Thirty-Three, of the Gods of Yama, of the Joyful Gods, of the Gods who Love to Create, of the Gods who Control the Creations of Others, and a thousand Brahmā realms.*";
P_HTM[1125]="*Yāvatā, bhikkhave, sahassī lokadhātu, mahābrahmā tattha aggamakkhāyati.**As far as the galaxy extends, the Great Brahmā is said to be the foremost.*";
P_HTM[1126]="*Mahābrahmunopi kho, bhikkhave, attheva aññathattaṃ atthi vipariṇāmo.**But even the Great Brahmā decays and perishes.*";
P_HTM[1127]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako tasmimpi nibbindati.**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with it.*";
P_HTM[1128]="*Tasmiṃ nibbindanto agge virajjati, pageva hīnasmiṃ. (2)**Their desire fades away even for the foremost, let alone the inferior.*";
P_HTM[1129]="*Hoti so, bhikkhave, samayo yaṃ ayaṃ loko saṃvaṭṭati.**There comes a time when this world contracts.*";
P_HTM[1130]="*Saṃvaṭṭamāne, bhikkhave, loke yebhuyyena sattā ābhassarasaṃvattanikā bhavanti.**As it contracts, most sentient beings migrate to the realm of streaming radiance.*";
P_HTM[1131]="*Te tattha honti manomayā pītibhakkhā sayaṃpabhā antalikkhecarā subhaṭṭhāyino ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ tiṭṭhanti.**There they are mind-made, feeding on rapture, self-luminous, moving through the sky, steadily glorious, and they remain like that for a very long time.*";
P_HTM[1132]="*Saṃvaṭṭamāne, bhikkhave, loke ābhassarā devā aggamakkhāyanti.**When the world is contracting, the gods of streaming radiance are said to be the foremost.*";
P_HTM[1133]="*Ābhassarānampi kho, bhikkhave, devānaṃ attheva aññathattaṃ atthi vipariṇāmo.**But even the gods of streaming radiance decay and perish.*";
P_HTM[1134]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako tasmimpi nibbindati.**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with it.*";
P_HTM[1135]="*Tasmiṃ nibbindanto agge virajjati, pageva hīnasmiṃ. (3)**Their desire fades away even for the foremost, let alone the inferior.*";
P_HTM[1136]="*Dasayimāni, bhikkhave, kasiṇāyatanāni.**There are these ten universal dimensions of meditation.*";
P_HTM[1137]="*Katamāni dasa?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[1138]="*Pathavīkasiṇameko sañjānāti uddhaṃ adho tiriyaṃ advayaṃ appamāṇaṃ;**Someone perceives the meditation on universal earth above, below, across, non-dual and limitless.*";
P_HTM[1139]="*āpokasiṇameko sañjānāti … pe …**They perceive the meditation on universal water …*";
P_HTM[1140]="*tejokasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal fire …*";
P_HTM[1141]="*vāyokasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal air …*";
P_HTM[1142]="*nīlakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal blue …*";
P_HTM[1143]="*pītakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal yellow …*";
P_HTM[1144]="*lohitakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal red …*";
P_HTM[1145]="*odātakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal white …*";
P_HTM[1146]="*ākāsakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal space …*";
P_HTM[1147]="*viññāṇakasiṇameko sañjānāti uddhaṃ adho tiriyaṃ advayaṃ appamāṇaṃ.**They perceive the meditation on universal consciousness above, below, across, non-dual and limitless.*";
P_HTM[1148]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dasa kasiṇāyatanāni.**These are the ten universal dimensions of meditation.*";
P_HTM[1149]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ dasannaṃ kasiṇāyatanānaṃ yadidaṃ viññāṇakasiṇaṃ eko sañjānāti uddhaṃ adho tiriyaṃ advayaṃ appamāṇaṃ.**The best of these ten universal dimensions of meditation is when someone perceives the meditation on universal consciousness above, below, across, non-dual and limitless.*";
P_HTM[1150]="*Evaṃsaññinopi kho, bhikkhave, santi sattā.**Some sentient beings perceive like this.*";
P_HTM[1151]="*Evaṃsaññīnampi kho, bhikkhave, sattānaṃ attheva aññathattaṃ atthi vipariṇāmo.**But even the sentient beings who perceive like this decay and perish.*";
P_HTM[1152]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako tasmimpi nibbindati.**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with it.*";
P_HTM[1153]="*Tasmiṃ nibbindanto agge virajjati, pageva hīnasmiṃ. (4)**Their desire fades away even for the foremost, let alone the inferior.*";
P_HTM[1154]="*Aṭṭhimāni, bhikkhave, abhibhāyatanāni.**There are these eight dimensions of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1155]="*Katamāni aṭṭha?**What eight?*";
P_HTM[1156]="*Ajjhattaṃ rūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati parittāni suvaṇṇadubbaṇṇāni;**Perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, limited, both pretty and ugly.*";
P_HTM[1157]="*‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti, evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[1158]="*Idaṃ paṭhamaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the first dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1159]="*Ajjhattaṃ rūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati appamāṇāni suvaṇṇadubbaṇṇāni;**Perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, limitless, both pretty and ugly.*";
P_HTM[1160]="*‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti, evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[1161]="*Idaṃ dutiyaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the second dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1162]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati parittāni suvaṇṇadubbaṇṇāni;**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, limited, both pretty and ugly.*";
P_HTM[1163]="*‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti, evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[1164]="*Idaṃ tatiyaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the third dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1165]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati appamāṇāni suvaṇṇadubbaṇṇāni;**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, limitless, both pretty and ugly.*";
P_HTM[1166]="*‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti, evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[1167]="*Idaṃ catutthaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the fourth dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1168]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati nīlāni nīlavaṇṇāni nīlanidassanāni nīlanibhāsāni.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, blue, with blue color, blue hue, and blue tint.*";
P_HTM[1169]="*Seyyathāpi nāma umāpupphaṃ nīlaṃ nīlavaṇṇaṃ nīlanidassanaṃ nīlanibhāsaṃ, seyyathā vā pana taṃ vatthaṃ bārāṇaseyyakaṃ ubhatobhāgavimaṭṭhaṃ nīlaṃ nīlavaṇṇaṃ nīlanidassanaṃ nīlanibhāsaṃ;**They’re like a flax flower that’s blue, with blue color, blue hue, and blue tint. Or a cloth from Bāraṇasī that’s smoothed on both sides, blue, with blue color, blue hue, and blue tint.*";
P_HTM[1170]="*evamevaṃ ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati nīlāni nīlavaṇṇāni nīlanidassanāni nīlanibhāsāni;**In the same way, not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, blue, with blue color, blue hue, and blue tint.*";
P_HTM[1171]="*‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti, evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[1172]="*Idaṃ pañcamaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the fifth dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1173]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati pītāni pītavaṇṇāni pītanidassanāni pītanibhāsāni.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, yellow, with yellow color, yellow hue, and yellow tint.*";
P_HTM[1174]="*Seyyathāpi nāma kaṇikārapupphaṃ pītaṃ pītavaṇṇaṃ pītanidassanaṃ pītanibhāsaṃ, seyyathā vā pana taṃ vatthaṃ bārāṇaseyyakaṃ ubhatobhāgavimaṭṭhaṃ pītaṃ pītavaṇṇaṃ pītanidassanaṃ pītanibhāsaṃ;**They’re like a champak flower that’s yellow, with yellow color, yellow hue, and yellow tint. Or a cloth from Bāraṇasī that’s smoothed on both sides, yellow, with yellow color, yellow hue, and yellow tint.*";
P_HTM[1175]="*evamevaṃ ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati pītāni pītavaṇṇāni pītanidassanāni pītanibhāsāni;**In the same way, not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, yellow, with yellow color, yellow hue, and yellow tint.*";
P_HTM[1176]="*‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti, evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[1177]="*Idaṃ chaṭṭhaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the sixth dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1178]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati lohitakāni lohitakavaṇṇāni lohitakanidassanāni lohitakanibhāsāni.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, red, with red color, red hue, and red tint.*";
P_HTM[1179]="*Seyyathāpi nāma bandhujīvakapupphaṃ lohitakaṃ lohitakavaṇṇaṃ lohitakanidassanaṃ lohitakanibhāsaṃ, seyyathā vā pana taṃ vatthaṃ bārāṇaseyyakaṃ ubhatobhāgavimaṭṭhaṃ lohitakaṃ lohitakavaṇṇaṃ lohitakanidassanaṃ lohitakanibhāsaṃ;**They’re like a scarlet mallow flower that’s red, with red color, red hue, and red tint. Or a cloth from Bāraṇasī that’s smoothed on both sides, red, with red color, red hue, and red tint.*";
P_HTM[1180]="*evamevaṃ ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati lohitakāni lohitakavaṇṇāni lohitakanidassanāni lohitakanibhāsāni;**In the same way, not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, red, with red color, red hue, and red tint.*";
P_HTM[1181]="*‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti, evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[1182]="*Idaṃ sattamaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the seventh dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1183]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati odātāni odātavaṇṇāni odātanidassanāni odātanibhāsāni.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, white, with white color, white hue, and white tint.*";
P_HTM[1184]="*Seyyathāpi nāma osadhitārakā odātā odātavaṇṇā odātanidassanā odātanibhāsā, seyyathā vā pana taṃ vatthaṃ bārāṇaseyyakaṃ ubhatobhāgavimaṭṭhaṃ odātaṃ odātavaṇṇaṃ odātanidassanaṃ odātanibhāsaṃ;**They’re like the morning star that’s white, with white color, white hue, and white tint. Or a cloth from Bāraṇasī that’s smoothed on both sides, white, with white color, white hue, and white tint.*";
P_HTM[1185]="*evamevaṃ ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati odātāni odātavaṇṇāni odātanidassanāni odātanibhāsāni;**In the same way, not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, white, with white color, white hue, and white tint.*";
P_HTM[1186]="*‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti, evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[1187]="*Idaṃ aṭṭhamaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the eighth dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1188]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, aṭṭha abhibhāyatanāni.**These are the eight dimensions of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1189]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ aṭṭhannaṃ abhibhāyatanānaṃ yadidaṃ ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati odātāni odātavaṇṇāni odātanidassanāni odātanibhāsāni;**The best of these dimensions of mastery is when someone, not perceiving form internally, sees visions externally, white, with white color, white hue, and white tint.*";
P_HTM[1190]="*‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti, evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[1191]="*Evaṃsaññinopi kho, bhikkhave, santi sattā.**Some sentient beings perceive like this.*";
P_HTM[1192]="*Evaṃsaññīnampi kho, bhikkhave, sattānaṃ attheva aññathattaṃ atthi vipariṇāmo.**But even the sentient beings who perceive like this decay and perish.*";
P_HTM[1193]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako tasmimpi nibbindati.**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with it.*";
P_HTM[1194]="*Tasmiṃ nibbindanto agge virajjati, pageva hīnasmiṃ. (5)**Their desire fades away even for the foremost, let alone the inferior.*";
P_HTM[1195]="*Catasso imā, bhikkhave, paṭipadā.**There are four ways of practice.*";
P_HTM[1196]="*Katamā catasso?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1197]="*Dukkhā paṭipadā dandhābhiññā, dukkhā paṭipadā khippābhiññā, sukhā paṭipadā dandhābhiññā, sukhā paṭipadā khippābhiññā—**~Painful practice with slow insight, ~painful practice with swift insight, ~pleasant practice with slow insight, and ~pleasant practice with swift insight.*";
P_HTM[1198]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, catasso paṭipadā.**These are the four ways of practice.*";
P_HTM[1199]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imāsaṃ catunnaṃ paṭipadānaṃ yadidaṃ sukhā paṭipadā khippābhiññā.**The best of these four ways of practice is the pleasant practice with swift insight.*";
P_HTM[1200]="*Evaṃpaṭipannāpi kho, bhikkhave, santi sattā.**Some sentient beings practice like this.*";
P_HTM[1201]="*Evaṃpaṭipannānampi kho, bhikkhave, sattānaṃ attheva aññathattaṃ atthi vipariṇāmo.**But even the sentient beings who practice like this decay and perish.*";
P_HTM[1202]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako tasmimpi nibbindati.**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with it.*";
P_HTM[1203]="*Tasmiṃ nibbindanto agge virajjati, pageva hīnasmiṃ. (6)**Their desire fades away even for the foremost, let alone the inferior.*";
P_HTM[1204]="*Catasso imā, bhikkhave, saññā.**There are these four perceptions.*";
P_HTM[1205]="*Katamā catasso?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1206]="*Parittameko sañjānāti, mahaggatameko sañjānāti, appamāṇameko sañjānāti, ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanameko sañjānāti—**One person perceives the limited. One person perceives the expansive. One person perceives the limitless. One person, aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, perceives the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[1207]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, catasso saññā.**These are the four perceptions.*";
P_HTM[1208]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imāsaṃ catunnaṃ saññānaṃ yadidaṃ ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanameko sañjānāti.**The best of these four perceptions is when a person, aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, perceives the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[1209]="*Evaṃsaññinopi kho, bhikkhave, santi sattā.**Some sentient beings perceive like this.*";
P_HTM[1210]="*Evaṃsaññīnampi kho, bhikkhave, sattānaṃ attheva aññathattaṃ atthi vipariṇāmo.**But even the sentient beings who perceive like this decay and perish.*";
P_HTM[1211]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako tasmimpi nibbindati.**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with it.*";
P_HTM[1212]="*Tasmiṃ nibbindanto agge virajjati, pageva hīnasmiṃ. (7)**Their desire fades away even for the foremost, let alone the inferior.*";
P_HTM[1213]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, bāhirakānaṃ diṭṭhigatānaṃ yadidaṃ ‘no cassaṃ, no ca me siyā, na bhavissāmi, na me bhavissatī’ti.**This is the best of the convictions of outsiders, that is: ‘I might not be, and it might not be mine. I will not be, and it will not be mine.’*";
P_HTM[1214]="*Evaṃdiṭṭhino, bhikkhave, etaṃ pāṭikaṅkhaṃ:**When someone has such a view, you can expect*";
P_HTM[1215]="*‘yā cāyaṃ bhave appaṭikulyatā, sā cassa na bhavissati;**that they will be repulsed by continued existence,*";
P_HTM[1216]="*yā cāyaṃ bhavanirodhe pāṭikulyatā, sā cassa na bhavissatī’ti.**and they will not be repulsed by the cessation of continued existence.*";
P_HTM[1217]="*Evaṃdiṭṭhinopi kho, bhikkhave, santi sattā.**Some sentient beings have such a view.*";
P_HTM[1218]="*Evaṃdiṭṭhīnampi kho, bhikkhave, sattānaṃ attheva aññathattaṃ atthi vipariṇāmo.**But even the sentient beings who have views like this decay and perish.*";
P_HTM[1219]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako tasmimpi nibbindati.**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with it.*";
P_HTM[1220]="*Tasmiṃ nibbindanto agge virajjati, pageva hīnasmiṃ. (8)**Their desire fades away even for the foremost, let alone the inferior.*";
P_HTM[1221]="*Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā paramatthavisuddhiṃ paññāpenti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who advocate ultimate purity.*";
P_HTM[1222]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, paramatthavisuddhiṃ paññapentānaṃ yadidaṃ sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**This is the best of the advocates of ultimate purity, that is, when someone, going totally beyond the dimension of nothingness, enters and remains in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[1223]="*Te tadabhiññāya tassa sacchikiriyāya dhammaṃ desenti.**They teach Dhamma in order to directly know and realize this.*";
P_HTM[1224]="*Evaṃvādinopi kho, bhikkhave, santi sattā.**Some sentient beings have such a doctrine.*";
P_HTM[1225]="*Evaṃvādīnampi kho, bhikkhave, sattānaṃ attheva aññathattaṃ atthi vipariṇāmo.**But even the sentient beings who have such a doctrine decay and perish.*";
P_HTM[1226]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako tasmimpi nibbindati.**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with it.*";
P_HTM[1227]="*Tasmiṃ nibbindanto agge virajjati, pageva hīnasmiṃ. (9)**Their desire fades away even for the foremost, let alone the inferior.*";
P_HTM[1228]="*Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ paññāpenti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who advocate ultimate extinguishment in this very life.*";
P_HTM[1229]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ paññapentānaṃ yadidaṃ channaṃ phassāyatanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ viditvā anupādā vimokkho.**This is the best of those who advocate extinguishment in this very life, that is, liberation by not grasping after truly understanding the origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape of the six fields of contact.*";
P_HTM[1230]="*Evaṃvādiṃ kho maṃ, bhikkhave, evamakkhāyiṃ eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā asatā tucchā musā abhūtena abbhācikkhanti:**Though I speak and explain like this, certain ascetics and brahmins misrepresent me with the false, hollow, lying, untruthful claim:*";
P_HTM[1231]="*‘samaṇo gotamo na kāmānaṃ pariññaṃ paññāpeti, na rūpānaṃ pariññaṃ paññāpeti, na vedanānaṃ pariññaṃ paññāpetī’ti.**‘The ascetic Gotama doesn’t advocate the complete understanding of sensual pleasures, sights, or feelings.’*";
P_HTM[1232]="*Kāmānañcāhaṃ, bhikkhave, pariññaṃ paññāpemi, rūpānañca pariññaṃ paññāpemi, vedanānañca pariññaṃ paññāpemi, diṭṭheva dhamme nicchāto nibbuto sītibhūto anupādā parinibbānaṃ paññāpemī”ti. (10)**But I do advocate the complete understanding of sensual pleasures, sights, and feelings. And I advocate complete extinguishment by not grasping in this very life, wishless, extinguished, and cooled.”*";
P_HTM[1233]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1234]="*10. Dutiyakosalasuttaṃ**Kosala (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1235]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[1236]="*Tena kho pana samayena rājā pasenadi kosalo uyyodhikā nivatto hoti vijitasaṅgāmo laddhādhippāyo.**Now at that time King Pasenadi of Kosala returned from combat after winning a battle and succeeding in his objective.*";
P_HTM[1237]="*Atha kho rājā pasenadi kosalo yena ārāmo tena pāyāsi.**Then King Pasenadi of Kosala went to the monastery.*";
P_HTM[1238]="*Yāvatikā yānassa bhūmi, yānena gantvā yānā paccorohitvā pattikova ārāmaṃ pāvisi.**He went by carriage as far as the terrain allowed, then descended and entered the monastery on foot.*";
P_HTM[1239]="*Tena kho pana samayena sambahulā bhikkhū abbhokāse caṅkamanti.**At that time several mendicants were walking meditation in the open air.*";
P_HTM[1240]="*Atha kho rājā pasenadi kosalo yena te bhikkhū tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā te bhikkhū etadavoca:**Then King Pasenadi of Kosala went up to them and said,*";
P_HTM[1241]="*“kahaṃ nu kho, bhante, bhagavā etarahi viharati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho.**“Sirs, where is the Blessed One at present, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha?*";
P_HTM[1242]="*Dassanakāmā hi mayaṃ, bhante, taṃ bhagavantaṃ arahantaṃ sammāsambuddhan”ti.**For I want to see the Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[1243]="*“Eso, mahārāja, vihāro saṃvutadvāro. Tena appasaddo upasaṅkamitvā ataramāno ālindaṃ pavisitvā ukkāsitvā aggaḷaṃ ākoṭehi; vivarissati te bhagavā dvāran”ti.**“Great king, that’s his dwelling, with the door closed. Approach it quietly, without hurrying; go onto the porch, clear your throat, and knock with the latch. The Buddha will open the door.”*";
P_HTM[1244]="*Atha kho rājā pasenadi kosalo yena so vihāro saṃvutadvāro, tena appasaddo upasaṅkamitvā ataramāno ālindaṃ pavisitvā ukkāsitvā aggaḷaṃ ākoṭesi. Vivari bhagavā dvāraṃ.**So the king approached the Buddha’s dwelling and knocked, and the Buddha opened the door.*";
P_HTM[1245]="*Atha kho rājā pasenadi kosalo vihāraṃ pavisitvā bhagavato pādesu sirasā nipatitvā bhagavato pādāni mukhena ca paricumbati pāṇīhi ca parisambāhati nāmañca sāveti:**Then King Pasenadi entered the Buddha’s dwelling. He bowed with his head to the Buddha’s feet, caressing them and covering them with kisses, and pronounced his name:*";
P_HTM[1246]="*“rājāhaṃ, bhante, pasenadi kosalo;**“Sir, I am Pasenadi, king of Kosala!*";
P_HTM[1247]="*rājāhaṃ, bhante, pasenadi kosalo”ti.**I am Pasenadi, king of Kosala!”*";
P_HTM[1248]="*“Kaṃ pana tvaṃ, mahārāja, atthavasaṃ sampassamāno imasmiṃ sarīre evarūpaṃ paramanipaccakāraṃ karosi, mettūpahāraṃ upadaṃsesī”ti?**“But great king, for what reason do you demonstrate such utmost devotion for this body, conveying your manifest love?”*";
P_HTM[1249]="*“Kataññutaṃ kho ahaṃ, bhante, kataveditaṃ sampassamāno bhagavati evarūpaṃ paramanipaccakāraṃ karomi, mettūpahāraṃ upadaṃsemi.**“Sir, it’s because of my gratitude and thanks for the Buddha that I demonstrate such utmost devotion, conveying my manifest love.*";
P_HTM[1250]="*Bhagavā hi, bhante, bahujanahitāya paṭipanno bahujanasukhāya bahuno janassa ariye ñāye patiṭṭhāpitā yadidaṃ kalyāṇadhammatāya kusaladhammatāya.**The Buddha is practicing for the welfare and happiness of the people. He has established many people in the noble method, that is, the principles of goodness and skillfulness.*";
P_HTM[1251]="*Yampi, bhante, bhagavā bahujanahitāya paṭipanno bahujanasukhāya bahuno janassa ariye ñāye patiṭṭhāpitā yadidaṃ kalyāṇadhammatāya kusaladhammatāya, idampi kho ahaṃ, bhante, atthavasaṃ sampassamāno bhagavati evarūpaṃ paramanipaccakāraṃ karomi, mettūpahāraṃ upadaṃsemi. (1)**This is a reason that I demonstrate such utmost devotion for the Buddha, conveying my manifest love.*";
P_HTM[1252]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, bhagavā sīlavā vuddhasīlo ariyasīlo kusalasīlo kusalasīlena samannāgato.**Furthermore, the Buddha is ethical, possessing ethical conduct that is mature, noble, and skillful.*";
P_HTM[1253]="*Yampi, bhante, bhagavā sīlavā vuddhasīlo ariyasīlo kusalasīlo kusalasīlena samannāgato, idampi kho ahaṃ, bhante, atthavasaṃ sampassamāno bhagavati evarūpaṃ paramanipaccakāraṃ karomi, mettūpahāraṃ upadaṃsemi. (2)**This is another reason that I demonstrate such utmost devotion for the Buddha, conveying my manifest love.*";
P_HTM[1254]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, bhagavā dīgharattaṃ āraññiko, araññavanapatthāni pantāni senāsanāni paṭisevati.**Furthermore, the Buddha lives in the wilderness, frequenting remote lodgings in the wilderness and the forest.*";
P_HTM[1255]="*Yampi, bhante, bhagavā dīgharattaṃ āraññiko, araññavanapatthāni pantāni senāsanāni paṭisevati, idampi kho ahaṃ, bhante, atthavasaṃ sampassamāno bhagavati evarūpaṃ paramanipaccakāraṃ karomi, mettūpahāraṃ upadaṃsemi. (3)**This is another reason that I demonstrate such utmost devotion for the Buddha, conveying my manifest love.*";
P_HTM[1256]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, bhagavā santuṭṭho itarītaracīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānapaccayabhesajjaparikkhārena.**Furthermore, the Buddha is content with any kind of robes, alms-food, lodgings, and medicines and supplies for the sick.*";
P_HTM[1257]="*Yampi, bhante, bhagavā santuṭṭho itarītaracīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānapaccayabhesajjaparikkhārena, idampi kho ahaṃ, bhante, atthavasaṃ sampassamāno bhagavati evarūpaṃ paramanipaccakāraṃ karomi, mettūpahāraṃ upadaṃsemi. (4)**This is another reason that I demonstrate such utmost devotion for the Buddha, conveying my manifest love.*";
P_HTM[1258]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, bhagavā āhuneyyo pāhuneyyo dakkhiṇeyyo añjalikaraṇīyo anuttaraṃ puññakkhettaṃ lokassa.**Furthermore, the Buddha is worthy of offerings dedicated to the gods, worthy of hospitality, worthy of a religious donation, worthy of greeting with joined palms, and is the supreme field of merit for the world.*";
P_HTM[1259]="*Yampi, bhante, bhagavā āhuneyyo pāhuneyyo dakkhiṇeyyo añjalikaraṇīyo anuttaraṃ puññakkhettaṃ lokassa, idampi kho ahaṃ, bhante, atthavasaṃ sampassamāno bhagavati evarūpaṃ paramanipaccakāraṃ karomi, mettūpahāraṃ upadaṃsemi. (5)**This is another reason that I demonstrate such utmost devotion for the Buddha, conveying my manifest love.*";
P_HTM[1260]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, bhagavā yāyaṃ kathā abhisallekhikā cetovivaraṇasappāyā, seyyathidaṃ—appicchakathā santuṭṭhikathā pavivekakathā asaṃsaggakathā vīriyārambhakathā sīlakathā samādhikathā paññākathā vimuttikathā vimuttiñāṇadassanakathā, evarūpāya kathāya nikāmalābhī akicchalābhī akasiralābhī.**Furthermore, the Buddha gets to take part in talk about self-effacement that helps open the heart, when he wants, without trouble or difficulty. That is, talk about fewness of wishes, contentment, seclusion, aloofness, arousing energy, ethics, immersion, wisdom, freedom, and the knowledge and vision of freedom.*";
P_HTM[1261]="*Yampi, bhante, bhagavā yāyaṃ kathā abhisallekhikā cetovivaraṇasappāyā, seyyathidaṃ—appicchakathā … pe … vimuttiñāṇadassanakathā, evarūpāya kathāya nikāmalābhī akicchalābhī akasiralābhī, idampi kho ahaṃ, bhante, atthavasaṃ sampassamāno bhagavati evarūpaṃ paramanipaccakāraṃ karomi, mettūpahāraṃ upadaṃsemi. (6)**This is another reason that I demonstrate such utmost devotion for the Buddha, conveying my manifest love.*";
P_HTM[1262]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, bhagavā catunnaṃ jhānānaṃ ābhicetasikānaṃ diṭṭhadhammasukhavihārānaṃ nikāmalābhī akicchalābhī akasiralābhī.**Furthermore, the Buddha gets the four absorptions—blissful meditations in the present life that belong to the higher mind—when he wants, without trouble or difficulty.*";
P_HTM[1263]="*Yampi, bhante, bhagavā catunnaṃ jhānānaṃ ābhicetasikānaṃ diṭṭhadhammasukhavihārānaṃ nikāmalābhī akicchalābhī akasiralābhī, idampi kho ahaṃ, bhante, atthavasaṃ sampassamāno bhagavati evarūpaṃ paramanipaccakāraṃ karomi, mettūpahāraṃ upadaṃsemi. (7)**This is another reason that I demonstrate such utmost devotion for the Buddha, conveying my manifest love.*";
P_HTM[1264]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, bhagavā anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati, seyyathidaṃ—ekampi jātiṃ dvepi jātiyo tissopi jātiyo catassopi jātiyo pañcapi jātiyo dasapi jātiyo vīsampi jātiyo tiṃsampi jātiyo cattālīsampi jātiyo paññāsampi jātiyo jātisatampi jātisahassampi jātisatasahassampi anekepi saṃvaṭṭakappe anekepi vivaṭṭakappe anekepi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭakappe: ‘amutrāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto amutra udapādiṃ; tatrāpāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto idhūpapanno’ti. Iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**Furthermore, the Buddha recollects many kinds of past lives. That is: one, two, three, four, five, ten, twenty, thirty, forty, fifty, a hundred, a thousand, a hundred thousand rebirths; many eons of the world contracting, many eons of the world expanding, many eons of the world contracting and expanding. He remembers: ‘There, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn somewhere else. There, too, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn here.’ And so he recollects his many kinds of past lives, with features and details.*";
P_HTM[1265]="*Yampi, bhante, bhagavā anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati, seyyathidaṃ—ekampi jātiṃ dvepi jātiyo … pe … iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati, idampi kho ahaṃ, bhante, atthavasaṃ sampassamāno bhagavati evarūpaṃ paramanipaccakāraṃ karomi, mettūpahāraṃ upadaṃsemi. (8)**This is another reason that I demonstrate such utmost devotion for the Buddha, conveying my manifest love.*";
P_HTM[1266]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, bhagavā dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passati cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe, sugate duggate yathākammūpage satte pajānāti: ‘ime vata bhonto sattā kāyaduccaritena samannāgatā vacīduccaritena samannāgatā manoduccaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ upavādakā micchādiṭṭhikā micchādiṭṭhikammasamādānā, te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapannā; ime vā pana bhonto sattā kāyasucaritena samannāgatā vacīsucaritena samannāgatā manosucaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ anupavādakā sammādiṭṭhikā sammādiṭṭhikammasamādānā, te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapannā’ti, iti dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passati … pe … yathākammūpage satte pajānāti.**Furthermore, with clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, the Buddha sees sentient beings passing away and being reborn—inferior and superior, beautiful and ugly, in a good place or a bad place. He understands how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds. ‘These dear beings did bad things by way of body, speech, and mind. They spoke ill of the noble ones; they had wrong view; and they acted out of that wrong view. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell. These dear beings, however, did good things by way of body, speech, and mind. They never spoke ill of the noble ones; they had right view; and they acted out of that right view. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.’ He understands how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds.*";
P_HTM[1267]="*Yampi, bhante, bhagavā dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena … pe … yathākammūpage satte pajānāti, idampi kho ahaṃ, bhante, atthavasaṃ sampassamāno bhagavati evarūpaṃ paramanipaccakāraṃ karomi, mettūpahāraṃ upadaṃsemi. (9)**This is another reason that I demonstrate such utmost devotion for the Buddha, conveying my manifest love.*";
P_HTM[1268]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, bhagavā āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, the Buddha has realized the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life, and lives having realized it with his own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[1269]="*Yampi, bhante, bhagavā āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ … pe … sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati, idampi kho ahaṃ, bhante, atthavasaṃ sampassamāno bhagavati evarūpaṃ paramanipaccakāraṃ karomi, mettūpahāraṃ upadaṃsemi. (10)**This is another reason that I demonstrate such utmost devotion for the Buddha, conveying my manifest love.*";
P_HTM[1270]="*Handa ca dāni mayaṃ, bhante, gacchāma.**Well, now, sir, I must go.*";
P_HTM[1271]="*Bahukiccā mayaṃ bahukaraṇīyā”ti.**I have many duties, and much to do.”*";
P_HTM[1272]="*“Yassadāni tvaṃ, mahārāja, kālaṃ maññasī”ti.**“Please, great king, go at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[1273]="*Atha kho rājā pasenadi kosalo uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmīti.**Then King Pasenadi got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[1274]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1275]="*Mahāvaggo tatiyo.* **";
P_HTM[1276]="*Sīhādhivutti kāyena,* **";
P_HTM[1277]="*cundena kasiṇena ca;* **";
P_HTM[1278]="*Kāḷī ca dve mahāpañhā,* **";
P_HTM[1279]="*kosalehi pare duveti.* **";
P_HTM[1280]="*123. Rāgapeyyālaṃ**With Upāli*";
P_HTM[1281]="*1. Upālisuttaṃ**With Upāli*";
P_HTM[1282]="*Atha kho āyasmā upāli yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā upāli bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Upāli went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1283]="*“kati nu kho, bhante, atthavase paṭicca tathāgatena sāvakānaṃ sikkhāpadaṃ paññattaṃ, pātimokkhaṃ uddiṭṭhan”ti?**“Sir, for how many reasons did the Realized One lay down training rules for his disciples and recite the monastic code?”*";
P_HTM[1284]="*“Dasa kho, upāli, atthavase paṭicca tathāgatena sāvakānaṃ sikkhāpadaṃ paññattaṃ, pātimokkhaṃ uddiṭṭhaṃ.**“Upāli, the Realized One laid down training rules for his disciples and recited the monastic code for ten reasons.*";
P_HTM[1285]="*Katame dasa?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[1286]="*Saṅghasuṭṭhutāya, saṅghaphāsutāya, dummaṅkūnaṃ puggalānaṃ niggahāya, pesalānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ phāsuvihārāya, diṭṭhadhammikānaṃ āsavānaṃ saṃvarāya, samparāyikānaṃ āsavānaṃ paṭighātāya, appasannānaṃ pasādāya, pasannānaṃ bhiyyobhāvāya, saddhammaṭṭhitiyā, vinayānuggahāya—**For the well-being of the Saṅgha and for the comfort of the Saṅgha. For keeping difficult persons in check and for the comfort of good-hearted mendicants. For restraining defilements that affect the present life and protecting against defilements that affect lives to come. For inspiring confidence in those without it, and increasing confidence in those who have it. For the continuation of the true teaching and the support of the training.*";
P_HTM[1287]="*ime kho, upāli, dasa atthavase paṭicca tathāgatena sāvakānaṃ sikkhāpadaṃ paññattaṃ, pātimokkhaṃ uddiṭṭhan”ti.**The Realized One laid down training rules for his disciples and recited the monastic code for these ten reasons.”*";
P_HTM[1288]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1289]="*2. Pātimokkhaṭṭhapanāsuttaṃ**Suspending the Recitation of the Monastic Code*";
P_HTM[1290]="*“Kati nu kho, bhante, pātimokkhaṭṭhapanā”ti?**“Sir, how many grounds are there to suspend the recitation of the monastic code?”*";
P_HTM[1291]="*“Dasa kho, upāli, pātimokkhaṭṭhapanā.**“Upāli, there are ten grounds to suspend the recitation of the monastic code.*";
P_HTM[1292]="*Katame dasa?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[1293]="*Pārājiko tassaṃ parisāyaṃ nisinno hoti, pārājikakathā vippakatā hoti, anupasampanno tassaṃ parisāyaṃ nisinno hoti, anupasampannakathā vippakatā hoti, sikkhaṃ paccakkhātako tassaṃ parisāyaṃ nisinno hoti, sikkhaṃ paccakkhātakakathā vippakatā hoti, paṇḍako tassaṃ parisāyaṃ nisinno hoti, paṇḍakakathā vippakatā hoti, bhikkhunidūsako tassaṃ parisāyaṃ nisinno hoti, bhikkhunidūsakakathā vippakatā hoti—**A mendicant who has committed an expulsion offense is sitting in the assembly. A discussion about whether someone has committed an expulsion offense is unfinished. A person who is not fully ordained is sitting in the assembly. A discussion about whether someone is fully ordained or not is unfinished. Someone who has rejected the training is sitting in the assembly. A discussion about whether someone has rejected the training or not is unfinished. A eunuch is sitting in the assembly. A discussion about whether someone is a eunuch is unfinished. A raper of nuns is sitting in the assembly. A discussion about whether or not someone is a raper of nuns is unfinished.*";
P_HTM[1294]="*ime kho, upāli, dasa pātimokkhaṭṭhapanā”ti.**These are the ten grounds to suspend the recitation of the monastic code.”*";
P_HTM[1295]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1296]="*3. Ubbāhikāsuttaṃ**A Judge*";
P_HTM[1297]="*“Katihi nu kho, bhante, dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu ubbāhikāya sammannitabbo”ti?**“Sir, how many qualities should a mendicant have to be agreed on as a judge?”*";
P_HTM[1298]="*“Dasahi kho, upāli, dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu ubbāhikāya sammannitabbo.**“Upāli, a mendicant should have ten qualities to be agreed on as a judge.*";
P_HTM[1299]="*Katamehi dasahi?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[1300]="*Idhupāli, bhikkhu sīlavā hoti; pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharati ācāragocarasampanno aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī, samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu;**It’s when a mendicant is ethical, restrained in the monastic code, conducting themselves well and seeking alms in suitable places. Seeing danger in the slightest fault, they keep the rules they’ve undertaken.*";
P_HTM[1301]="*bahussuto hoti sutadharo sutasannicayo, ye te dhammā ādikalyāṇā majjhekalyāṇā pariyosānakalyāṇā sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ abhivadanti, tathārūpāssa dhammā bahussutā honti dhātā vacasā paricitā manasānupekkhitā diṭṭhiyā suppaṭividdhā;**They’re very learned, remembering and keeping what they’ve learned. These teachings are good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased, describing a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure. They are very learned in such teachings, remembering them, reinforcing them by recitation, mentally scrutinizing them, and comprehending them theoretically.*";
P_HTM[1302]="*ubhayāni kho panassa pātimokkhāni vitthārena svāgatāni honti suvibhattāni suppavattīni suvinicchitāni suttaso anubyañjanaso;**Both monastic codes have been passed down to them in detail, well analyzed, well mastered, well judged in both the rules and accompanying material.*";
P_HTM[1303]="*vinaye kho pana ṭhito hoti asaṃhīro;**They’re firm and unfaltering in the training.*";
P_HTM[1304]="*paṭibalo hoti ubho atthapaccatthike saññāpetuṃ paññāpetuṃ nijjhāpetuṃ pekkhetuṃ pasādetuṃ;**When there are opposing parties, they’re able to persuade, advocate, and convince them, make them see the other side and trust each other.*";
P_HTM[1305]="*adhikaraṇasamuppādavūpasamakusalo hoti—**They’re skilled in raising and settling disciplinary issues.*";
P_HTM[1306]="*adhikaraṇaṃ jānāti;**They know what a disciplinary issue is.*";
P_HTM[1307]="*adhikaraṇasamudayaṃ jānāti;**They know how a disciplinary issue originates.*";
P_HTM[1308]="*adhikaraṇanirodhaṃ jānāti;**They know how a disciplinary issue ceases.*";
P_HTM[1309]="*adhikaraṇanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ jānāti.**They know the practical way leading to the cessation of a disciplinary issue.*";
P_HTM[1310]="*Imehi kho, upāli, dasahi dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu ubbāhikāya sammannitabbo”ti.**A mendicant should have these ten qualities to be agreed on as a judge.”*";
P_HTM[1311]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1312]="*4. Upasampadāsuttaṃ**Ordination*";
P_HTM[1313]="*“Katihi nu kho, bhante, dhammehi samannāgatena bhikkhunā upasampādetabban”ti?**“Sir, how many qualities should a mendicant have to give ordination?”*";
P_HTM[1314]="*“Dasahi kho, upāli, dhammehi samannāgatena bhikkhunā upasampādetabbaṃ.**“Upāli, a mendicant should have ten qualities to give ordination.*";
P_HTM[1315]="*Katamehi dasahi?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[1316]="*Idhupāli, bhikkhu sīlavā hoti, pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharati ācāragocarasampanno aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī, samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu;**It’s when a mendicant is ethical, restrained in the monastic code, conducting themselves well and seeking alms in suitable places. Seeing danger in the slightest fault, they keep the rules they’ve undertaken.*";
P_HTM[1317]="*bahussuto hoti sutadharo sutasannicayo, ye te dhammā ādikalyāṇā majjhekalyāṇā pariyosānakalyāṇā sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ abhivadanti, tathārūpāssa dhammā bahussutā honti dhātā vacasā paricitā manasānupekkhitā diṭṭhiyā suppaṭividdhā;**They’re very learned, remembering and keeping what they’ve learned. These teachings are good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased, describing a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure. They are very learned in such teachings, remembering them, reinforcing them by recitation, mentally scrutinizing them, and comprehending them theoretically.*";
P_HTM[1318]="*pātimokkhaṃ kho panassa vitthārena svāgataṃ hoti suvibhattaṃ suppavattaṃ suvinicchitaṃ suttaso anubyañjanaso;**Both monastic codes have been passed down to them in detail, well analyzed, well mastered, well judged in both the rules and accompanying material.*";
P_HTM[1319]="*paṭibalo hoti gilānaṃ upaṭṭhātuṃ vā upaṭṭhāpetuṃ vā;**They’re able to care for the sick or get someone else to do so.*";
P_HTM[1320]="*paṭibalo hoti anabhiratiṃ vūpakāsetuṃ vā vūpakāsāpetuṃ vā;**They’re able to settle dissatisfaction or get someone else to do so.*";
P_HTM[1321]="*paṭibalo hoti uppannaṃ kukkuccaṃ dhammato vinodetuṃ;**They’re able to dispel remorse when it has come up.*";
P_HTM[1322]="*paṭibalo hoti uppannaṃ diṭṭhigataṃ dhammato vivecetuṃ;**They’re able to rationally dissuade someone from misconceptions that come up.*";
P_HTM[1323]="*paṭibalo hoti adhisīle samādapetuṃ;**They’re able to encourage someone in the higher ethics,*";
P_HTM[1324]="*paṭibalo hoti adhicitte samādapetuṃ;**the higher mind,*";
P_HTM[1325]="*paṭibalo hoti adhipaññāya samādapetuṃ.**and the higher wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1326]="*Imehi kho, upāli, dasahi dhammehi samannāgatena bhikkhunā upasampādetabban”ti.**A mendicant should have these ten qualities to give ordination.”*";
P_HTM[1327]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1328]="*5. Nissayasuttaṃ**Dependence*";
P_HTM[1329]="*“Katihi nu kho, bhante, dhammehi samannāgatena bhikkhunā nissayo dātabbo”ti?**“Sir, how many qualities should a mendicant have to give dependence?”*";
P_HTM[1330]="*“Dasahi kho, upāli, dhammehi samannāgatena bhikkhunā nissayo dātabbo.**“Upāli, a mendicant should have ten qualities to give dependence.*";
P_HTM[1331]="*Katamehi dasahi?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[1332]="*Idhupāli, bhikkhu sīlavā hoti … pe … samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu;**It’s when a mendicant is ethical …*";
P_HTM[1333]="*bahussuto hoti … pe … diṭṭhiyā suppaṭividdhā;**They’re learned …*";
P_HTM[1334]="*pātimokkhaṃ kho panassa vitthārena svāgataṃ hoti suvibhattaṃ suppavattaṃ suvinicchitaṃ suttaso anubyañjanaso;**Both monastic codes have been passed down to them in detail, well analyzed, well mastered, well judged in both the rules and accompanying material.*";
P_HTM[1335]="*paṭibalo hoti gilānaṃ upaṭṭhātuṃ vā upaṭṭhāpetuṃ vā;**They’re able to care for the sick or get someone else to do so.*";
P_HTM[1336]="*paṭibalo hoti anabhiratiṃ vūpakāsetuṃ vā vūpakāsāpetuṃ vā;**They’re able to settle dissatisfaction or get someone else to do so.*";
P_HTM[1337]="*paṭibalo hoti uppannaṃ kukkuccaṃ dhammato vinodetuṃ;**They’re able to dispel remorse when it has come up.*";
P_HTM[1338]="*paṭibalo hoti uppannaṃ diṭṭhigataṃ dhammato vivecetuṃ;**They’re able to rationally dissuade someone from misconceptions that come up.*";
P_HTM[1339]="*paṭibalo hoti adhisīle … pe …**They’re able to encourage someone in the higher ethics,*";
P_HTM[1340]="*adhicitte …**the higher mind,*";
P_HTM[1341]="*adhipaññāya samādapetuṃ.**and the higher wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1342]="*Imehi kho, upāli, dasahi dhammehi samannāgatena bhikkhunā nissayo dātabbo”ti.**A mendicant should have these ten qualities to give dependence.”*";
P_HTM[1343]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1344]="*6. Sāmaṇerasuttaṃ**A Novice*";
P_HTM[1345]="*“Katihi nu kho, bhante, dhammehi samannāgatena bhikkhunā sāmaṇero upaṭṭhāpetabbo”ti?**“Sir, how many qualities should a mendicant have to be attended on by a novice?”*";
P_HTM[1346]="*“Dasahi kho, upāli, dhammehi samannāgatena bhikkhunā sāmaṇero upaṭṭhāpetabbo.**“Upāli, a mendicant should have ten qualities to be attended on by a novice.*";
P_HTM[1347]="*Katamehi dasahi?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[1348]="*Idhupāli, bhikkhu sīlavā hoti … pe … samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu;**It’s when a mendicant is ethical …*";
P_HTM[1349]="*bahussuto hoti … pe … diṭṭhiyā suppaṭividdhā;**They’re learned …*";
P_HTM[1350]="*pātimokkhaṃ kho panassa vitthārena svāgataṃ hoti suvibhattaṃ suppavattaṃ suvinicchitaṃ suttaso anubyañjanaso;**Both monastic codes have been passed down to them in detail, well analyzed, well mastered, well judged in both the rules and accompanying material.*";
P_HTM[1351]="*paṭibalo hoti gilānaṃ upaṭṭhātuṃ vā upaṭṭhāpetuṃ vā;**They’re able to care for the sick or get someone else to do so.*";
P_HTM[1352]="*paṭibalo hoti anabhiratiṃ vūpakāsetuṃ vā vūpakāsāpetuṃ vā;**They’re able to settle dissatisfaction or get someone else to do so.*";
P_HTM[1353]="*paṭibalo hoti uppannaṃ kukkuccaṃ dhammato vinodetuṃ;**They’re able to dispel remorse when it has come up.*";
P_HTM[1354]="*paṭibalo hoti uppannaṃ diṭṭhigataṃ dhammato vivecetuṃ;**They’re able to rationally dissuade someone from misconceptions that come up.*";
P_HTM[1355]="*paṭibalo hoti adhisīle samādapetuṃ;**They’re able to encourage someone in the higher ethics,*";
P_HTM[1356]="*paṭibalo hoti adhicitte samādapetuṃ;**the higher mind,*";
P_HTM[1357]="*paṭibalo hoti adhipaññāya samādapetuṃ.**and the higher wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1358]="*Imehi kho, upāli, dasahi dhammehi samannāgatena bhikkhunā sāmaṇero upaṭṭhāpetabbo”ti.**A mendicant should have these ten qualities to be attended on by a novice.”*";
P_HTM[1359]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1360]="*7. Saṅghabhedasuttaṃ**Schism in the Saṅgha*";
P_HTM[1361]="*“‘Saṃghabhedo, saṃghabhedo’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of ‘schism in the Saṅgha’.*";
P_HTM[1362]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, saṃgho bhinno hotī”ti?**How is schism in the Saṅgha defined?”*";
P_HTM[1363]="*“Idhupāli, bhikkhū adhammaṃ dhammoti dīpenti, dhammaṃ adhammoti dīpenti, avinayaṃ vinayoti dīpenti, vinayaṃ avinayoti dīpenti, abhāsitaṃ alapitaṃ tathāgatena bhāsitaṃ lapitaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, bhāsitaṃ lapitaṃ tathāgatena abhāsitaṃ alapitaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, anāciṇṇaṃ tathāgatena āciṇṇaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, āciṇṇaṃ tathāgatena anāciṇṇaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, apaññattaṃ tathāgatena paññattaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, paññattaṃ tathāgatena apaññattaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti.**“Upāli, it’s when a mendicant explains what is not the teaching as the teaching, and what is the teaching as not the teaching. They explain what is not the training as the training, and what is the training as not the training. They explain what was not spoken and stated by the Realized One as spoken and stated by the Realized One, and what was spoken and stated by the Realized One as not spoken and stated by the Realized One. They explain what was not practiced by the Realized One as practiced by the Realized One, and what was practiced by the Realized One as not practiced by the Realized One. They explain what was not prescribed by the Realized One as prescribed by the Realized One, and what was prescribed by the Realized One as not prescribed by the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[1364]="*Te imehi dasahi vatthūhi avakassanti apakassanti āveni kammāni karonti āveni pātimokkhaṃ uddisanti.**On these ten grounds they split off and go their own way. They perform legal acts autonomously and recite the monastic code autonomously.*";
P_HTM[1365]="*Ettāvatā kho, upāli, saṃgho bhinno hotī”ti.**That is how schism in the Saṅgha is defined.”*";
P_HTM[1366]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1367]="*8. Saṅghasāmaggīsuttaṃ**Harmony in the Saṅgha*";
P_HTM[1368]="*“‘Saṃghasāmaggī, saṃghasāmaggī’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of ‘harmony in the Saṅgha’.*";
P_HTM[1369]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, saṃgho samaggo hotī”ti?**How is harmony in the Saṅgha defined?”*";
P_HTM[1370]="*“Idhupāli, bhikkhū adhammaṃ adhammoti dīpenti, dhammaṃ dhammoti dīpenti, avinayaṃ avinayoti dīpenti, vinayaṃ vinayoti dīpenti, abhāsitaṃ alapitaṃ tathāgatena abhāsitaṃ alapitaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, bhāsitaṃ lapitaṃ tathāgatena bhāsitaṃ lapitaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, anāciṇṇaṃ tathāgatena anāciṇṇaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, āciṇṇaṃ tathāgatena āciṇṇaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, apaññattaṃ tathāgatena apaññattaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, paññattaṃ tathāgatena paññattaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti.**“Upāli, it’s when a mendicant explains what is not the teaching as not the teaching, and what is the teaching as the teaching. They explain what is not the training as not the training, and what is the training as the training. They explain what was not spoken and stated by the Realized One as not spoken and stated by the Realized One, and what was spoken and stated by the Realized One as spoken and stated by the Realized One. They explain what was not practiced by the Realized One as not practiced by the Realized One, and what was practiced by the Realized One as practiced by the Realized One. They explain what was not prescribed by the Realized One as not prescribed by the Realized One, and what was prescribed by the Realized One as prescribed by the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[1371]="*Te imehi dasahi vatthūhi na avakassanti na apakassanti na āveni kammāni karonti na āveni pātimokkhaṃ uddisanti.**On these ten grounds they don’t split off and go their own way. They don’t perform legal acts autonomously or recite the monastic code autonomously.*";
P_HTM[1372]="*Ettāvatā kho, upāli, saṃgho samaggo hotī”ti.**That is how harmony in the Saṅgha is defined.”*";
P_HTM[1373]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1374]="*9. Paṭhamaānandasuttaṃ**With Ānanda (1st)*";
P_HTM[1375]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Ānanda went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[1376]="*“‘saṅghabhedo saṅghabhedo’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of ‘schism in the Saṅgha’.*";
P_HTM[1377]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, saṅgho bhinno hotī”ti?**How is schism in the Saṅgha defined?”*";
P_HTM[1378]="*“Idhānanda, bhikkhū adhammaṃ dhammoti dīpenti, dhammaṃ adhammoti dīpenti, avinayaṃ vinayoti dīpenti … pe …**“Ānanda, it’s when a mendicant explains what is not the teaching as the teaching …*";
P_HTM[1379]="*paññattaṃ tathāgatena apaññattaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti.**and what was prescribed by the Realized One as not prescribed by the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[1380]="*Te imehi dasahi vatthūhi avakassanti apakassanti āveni kammāni karonti āveni pātimokkhaṃ uddisanti.**On these ten grounds they split off and go their own way. They perform legal acts autonomously and recite the monastic code autonomously.*";
P_HTM[1381]="*Ettāvatā kho, ānanda, saṅgho bhinno hotī”ti.**That is how schism in the Saṅgha is defined.”*";
P_HTM[1382]="*“Samaggaṃ pana, bhante, saṅghaṃ bhinditvā kiṃ so pasavatī”ti?**“But sir, what does someone who has caused a schism in a harmonious Saṅgha bring upon themselves?”*";
P_HTM[1383]="*“Kappaṭṭhikaṃ, ānanda, kibbisaṃ pasavatī”ti.**“They bring upon themselves evil that lasts for an eon.”*";
P_HTM[1384]="*“Kiṃ pana, bhante, kappaṭṭhikaṃ kibbisan”ti?**“But sir, what is the evil that lasts for an eon?”*";
P_HTM[1385]="*“Kappaṃ, ānanda, nirayamhi paccatīti—**“They burn in hell for an eon, Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[1386]="*Āpāyiko nerayiko,**A schismatic remains for the eon*";
P_HTM[1387]="*Kappaṭṭho saṃghabhedako;**in a place of loss, in hell.*";
P_HTM[1388]="*Vaggarato adhammaṭṭho,**Basing themselves in what is not the teaching,*";
P_HTM[1389]="*Yogakkhemā padhaṃsati;**favoring factions, they destroy their sanctuary.*";
P_HTM[1390]="*Saṃghaṃ samaggaṃ bhinditvā,**After causing schism in a harmonious Saṅgha,*";
P_HTM[1391]="*Kappaṃ nirayamhi paccatī”ti.**they burn in hell for an eon.”*";
P_HTM[1392]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1393]="*10. Dutiyaānandasuttaṃ**With Ānanda (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1394]="*“‘Saṅghasāmaggī, saṅghasāmaggī’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of ‘harmony in the Saṅgha’.*";
P_HTM[1395]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, saṅgho samaggo hotī”ti?**How is harmony in the Saṅgha defined?”*";
P_HTM[1396]="*“Idhānanda, bhikkhū adhammaṃ adhammoti dīpenti, dhammaṃ dhammoti dīpenti, avinayaṃ avinayoti dīpenti, vinayaṃ vinayoti dīpenti, abhāsitaṃ alapitaṃ tathāgatena abhāsitaṃ alapitaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, bhāsitaṃ lapitaṃ tathāgatena bhāsitaṃ lapitaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, anāciṇṇaṃ tathāgatena anāciṇṇaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, āciṇṇaṃ tathāgatena āciṇṇaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, apaññattaṃ tathāgatena apaññattaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, paññattaṃ tathāgatena paññattaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti.**“Ānanda, it’s when a mendicant explains what is not the teaching as not the teaching, and what is the teaching as the teaching. They explain what is not the training as not the training, and what is the training as the training. They explain what was not spoken and stated by the Realized One as not spoken and stated by the Realized One, and what was spoken and stated by the Realized One as spoken and stated by the Realized One. They explain what was not practiced by the Realized One as not practiced by the Realized One, and what was practiced by the Realized One as practiced by the Realized One. They explain what was not prescribed by the Realized One as not prescribed by the Realized One, and what was prescribed by the Realized One as prescribed by the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[1397]="*Te imehi dasahi vatthūhi na avakassanti na apakassanti na āveni kammāni karonti na āveni pātimokkhaṃ uddisanti.**On these ten grounds they don’t split off and go their own way. They don’t perform legal acts autonomously or recite the monastic code autonomously.*";
P_HTM[1398]="*Ettāvatā kho, ānanda, saṅgho samaggo hotī”ti.**That is how harmony in the Saṅgha is defined.”*";
P_HTM[1399]="*“Bhinnaṃ pana, bhante, saṅghaṃ samaggaṃ katvā kiṃ so pasavatī”ti?**“But sir, what does someone who has created harmony in a schismatic Saṅgha bring upon themselves?”*";
P_HTM[1400]="*“Brahmaṃ, ānanda, puññaṃ pasavatī”ti.**“They bring divine merit upon themselves.”*";
P_HTM[1401]="*“Kiṃ pana, bhante, brahmaṃ puññan”ti?**“But what is divine merit?”*";
P_HTM[1402]="*“Kappaṃ, ānanda, saggamhi modatīti—**“They rejoice in heaven for an eon, Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[1403]="*Sukhā saṃghassa sāmaggī,**A Saṅgha in harmony is happy,*";
P_HTM[1404]="*samaggānañca anuggaho;**as is support for those in harmony.*";
P_HTM[1405]="*Samaggarato dhammaṭṭho,**Basing themselves in the teaching,*";
P_HTM[1406]="*yogakkhemā na dhaṃsati;**favoring harmony, they destroy no sanctuary.*";
P_HTM[1407]="*Saṃghaṃ samaggaṃ katvāna,**After creating harmony in the Saṅgha,*";
P_HTM[1408]="*kappaṃ saggamhi modatī”ti.**they rejoice in heaven for an eon.”*";
P_HTM[1409]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1410]="*Upālivaggo catuttho.* **";
P_HTM[1411]="*Upāli ṭhapanā ubbāho,* **";
P_HTM[1412]="*upasampadanissayā;* **";
P_HTM[1413]="*Sāmaṇero ca dve bhedā,* **";
P_HTM[1414]="*ānandehi pare duveti.* **";
P_HTM[1415]="*123. Rāgapeyyālaṃ**Abuse*";
P_HTM[1416]="*1. Vivādasuttaṃ**Arguments*";
P_HTM[1417]="*Atha kho āyasmā upāli yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā upāli bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Upāli went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1418]="*“ko nu kho, bhante, hetu ko paccayo, yena saṃghe bhaṇḍanakalahaviggahavivādā uppajjanti, bhikkhū ca na phāsu viharantī”ti?**“What is the cause, sir, what is the reason, why arguments, quarrels, and disputes arise in the Saṅgha, and the mendicants don’t live happily?”*";
P_HTM[1419]="*“Idhupāli, bhikkhū adhammaṃ dhammoti dīpenti, dhammaṃ adhammoti dīpenti, avinayaṃ vinayoti dīpenti, vinayaṃ avinayoti dīpenti, abhāsitaṃ alapitaṃ tathāgatena bhāsitaṃ lapitaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, bhāsitaṃ lapitaṃ tathāgatena abhāsitaṃ alapitaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, anāciṇṇaṃ tathāgatena āciṇṇaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, āciṇṇaṃ tathāgatena anāciṇṇaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, apaññattaṃ tathāgatena paññattaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, paññattaṃ tathāgatena apaññattaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti.**“Upāli, it’s when a mendicant explains what is not the teaching as the teaching, and what is the teaching as not the teaching. They explain what is not the training as the training, and what is the training as not the training. They explain what was not spoken and stated by the Realized One as spoken and stated by the Realized One, and what was spoken and stated by the Realized One as not spoken and stated by the Realized One. They explain what was not practiced by the Realized One as practiced by the Realized One, and what was practiced by the Realized One as not practiced by the Realized One. They explain what was not prescribed by the Realized One as prescribed by the Realized One, and what was prescribed by the Realized One as not prescribed by the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[1420]="*Ayaṃ kho, upāli, hetu ayaṃ paccayo, yena saṃghe bhaṇḍanakalahaviggahavivādā uppajjanti, bhikkhū ca na phāsu viharantī”ti.**This is the cause, this is the reason why arguments, quarrels, and disputes arise in the Saṅgha, and the mendicants don’t live happily.”*";
P_HTM[1421]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1422]="*2. Paṭhamavivādamūlasuttaṃ**Roots of Arguments (1st)*";
P_HTM[1423]="*“Kati nu kho, bhante, vivādamūlānī”ti?**“Sir, how many roots of arguments are there?”*";
P_HTM[1424]="*“Dasa kho, upāli, vivādamūlāni.**“Upāli, there are ten roots of arguments.*";
P_HTM[1425]="*Katamāni dasa?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[1426]="*Idhupāli, bhikkhū adhammaṃ dhammoti dīpenti, dhammaṃ adhammoti dīpenti, avinayaṃ vinayoti dīpenti, vinayaṃ avinayoti dīpenti, abhāsitaṃ alapitaṃ tathāgatena bhāsitaṃ lapitaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, bhāsitaṃ lapitaṃ tathāgatena abhāsitaṃ alapitaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, anāciṇṇaṃ tathāgatena āciṇṇaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, āciṇṇaṃ tathāgatena anāciṇṇaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, apaññattaṃ tathāgatena paññattaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti, paññattaṃ tathāgatena apaññattaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpenti.**It’s when a mendicant explains what is not the teaching as the teaching, and what is the teaching as not the teaching. They explain what is not the training as the training, and what is the training as not the training. They explain what was not spoken and stated by the Realized One as spoken and stated by the Realized One, and what was spoken and stated by the Realized One as not spoken and stated by the Realized One. They explain what was not practiced by the Realized One as practiced by the Realized One, and what was practiced by the Realized One as not practiced by the Realized One. They explain what was not prescribed by the Realized One as prescribed by the Realized One, and what was prescribed by the Realized One as not prescribed by the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[1427]="*Imāni kho, upāli, dasa vivādamūlānī”ti.**These are the ten roots of arguments.”*";
P_HTM[1428]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1429]="*3. Dutiyavivādamūlasuttaṃ**Roots of Arguments (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1430]="*“Kati nu kho, bhante, vivādamūlānī”ti?**“Sir, how many roots of arguments are there?”*";
P_HTM[1431]="*“Dasa kho, upāli, vivādamūlāni.**“Upāli, there are ten roots of arguments.*";
P_HTM[1432]="*Katamāni dasa?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[1433]="*Idhupāli, bhikkhū anāpattiṃ āpattīti dīpenti, āpattiṃ anāpattīti dīpenti, lahukaṃ āpattiṃ garukāpattīti dīpenti, garukaṃ āpattiṃ lahukāpattīti dīpenti, duṭṭhullaṃ āpattiṃ aduṭṭhullāpattīti dīpenti, aduṭṭhullaṃ āpattiṃ duṭṭhullāpattīti dīpenti, sāvasesaṃ āpattiṃ anavasesāpattīti dīpenti, anavasesaṃ āpattiṃ sāvasesāpattīti dīpenti, sappaṭikammaṃ āpattiṃ appaṭikammāpattīti dīpenti, appaṭikammaṃ āpattiṃ sappaṭikammāpattīti dīpenti.**It’s when a mendicant explains what is not an offense as an offense, and what is an offense as not an offense. They explain a light offense as a serious offense, and a serious offense as a light offense. They explain an offense committed with corrupt intention as an offense not committed with corrupt intention, and an offense not committed with corrupt intention as an offense committed with corrupt intention. They explain an offense requiring rehabilitation as an offense not requiring rehabilitation, and an offense not requiring rehabilitation as an offense requiring rehabilitation. They explain an offense with redress as an offense without redress, and an offense without redress as an offense with redress.*";
P_HTM[1434]="*Imāni kho, upāli, dasa vivādamūlānī”ti.**These are the ten roots of arguments.”*";
P_HTM[1435]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1436]="*4. Kusinārasuttaṃ**At Kusināra*";
P_HTM[1437]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā kusinārāyaṃ viharati baliharaṇe vanasaṇḍe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Kusināra, in the Forest of Offerings.*";
P_HTM[1438]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[1439]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[1440]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[1441]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[1442]="*“Codakena, bhikkhave, bhikkhunā paraṃ codetukāmena pañca dhamme ajjhattaṃ paccavekkhitvā pañca dhamme ajjhattaṃ upaṭṭhāpetvā paro codetabbo.**“Mendicants, a mendicant who wants to accuse another should first check five things in themselves and establish five things in themselves.*";
P_HTM[1443]="*Katame pañca dhammā ajjhattaṃ paccavekkhitabbā?**What five things should they check in themselves?*";
P_HTM[1444]="*Codakena, bhikkhave, bhikkhunā paraṃ codetukāmena evaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ:**A mendicant who wants to accuse another should check this:*";
P_HTM[1445]="*‘parisuddhakāyasamācāro nu khomhi, parisuddhenamhi kāyasamācārena samannāgato acchiddena appaṭimaṃsena.**‘Is my bodily behavior pure? Do I have pure bodily behavior that is impeccable and irreproachable?*";
P_HTM[1446]="*Saṃvijjati nu kho me eso dhammo udāhu no’ti?**Is this thing found in me or not?’*";
P_HTM[1447]="*No ce, bhikkhave, bhikkhu parisuddhakāyasamācāro hoti parisuddhena kāyasamācārena samannāgato acchiddena appaṭimaṃsena, tassa bhavanti vattāro:**If it’s not, there will be people who say:*";
P_HTM[1448]="*‘iṅgha tāva āyasmā kāyikaṃ sikkhassū’ti, itissa bhavanti vattāro.**‘Come on, venerable, train your own bodily behavior first.’*";
P_HTM[1449]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, codakena bhikkhunā paraṃ codetukāmena evaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ:**Furthermore, a mendicant who wants to accuse another should check this:*";
P_HTM[1450]="*‘parisuddhavacīsamācāro nu khomhi, parisuddhenamhi vacīsamācārena samannāgato acchiddena appaṭimaṃsena.**‘Is my verbal behavior pure? Do I have pure verbal behavior that is impeccable and irreproachable?*";
P_HTM[1451]="*Saṃvijjati nu kho me eso dhammo udāhu no’ti?**Is this thing found in me or not?’*";
P_HTM[1452]="*No ce, bhikkhave, bhikkhu parisuddhavacīsamācāro hoti parisuddhena vacīsamācārena samannāgato acchiddena appaṭimaṃsena, tassa bhavanti vattāro:**If it’s not, there will be people who say:*";
P_HTM[1453]="*‘iṅgha tāva āyasmā vācasikaṃ sikkhassū’ti, itissa bhavanti vattāro.**‘Come on, venerable, train your own verbal behavior first.’*";
P_HTM[1454]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, codakena bhikkhunā paraṃ codetukāmena evaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ:**Furthermore, a mendicant who wants to accuse another should check this:*";
P_HTM[1455]="*‘mettaṃ nu kho me cittaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ sabrahmacārīsu anāghātaṃ.**‘Is my heart established in love for my spiritual companions, without resentment?*";
P_HTM[1456]="*Saṃvijjati nu kho me eso dhammo udāhu no’ti?**Is this thing found in me or not?’*";
P_HTM[1457]="*No ce, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno mettaṃ cittaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ hoti sabrahmacārīsu anāghātaṃ, tassa bhavanti vattāro:**If it’s not, there will be people who say:*";
P_HTM[1458]="*‘iṅgha tāva āyasmā sabrahmacārīsu mettaṃ cittaṃ upaṭṭhāpehī’ti, itissa bhavanti vattāro.**‘Come on, venerable, establish your heart in love for your spiritual companions first.’*";
P_HTM[1459]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, codakena bhikkhunā paraṃ codetukāmena evaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ:**Furthermore, a mendicant who wants to accuse another should check this:*";
P_HTM[1460]="*‘bahussuto nu khomhi sutadharo sutasannicayo, ye te dhammā ādikalyāṇā majjhekalyāṇā pariyosānakalyāṇā sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ abhivadanti, tathārūpā me dhammā bahussutā honti dhātā vacasā paricitā manasānupekkhitā diṭṭhiyā suppaṭividdhā.**‘Am I very learned, remembering and keeping what I’ve learned? These teachings are good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased, describing a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure. Am I very learned in such teachings, remembering them, reinforcing them by recitation, mentally scrutinizing them, and comprehending them theoretically?*";
P_HTM[1461]="*Saṃvijjati nu kho me eso dhammo udāhu no’ti?**Is this thing found in me or not?’*";
P_HTM[1462]="*No ce, bhikkhave, bhikkhu bahussuto hoti sutadharo sutasannicayo, ye te dhammā ādikalyāṇā majjhekalyāṇā pariyosānakalyāṇā sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ abhivadanti, tathārūpāssa dhammā bahussutā honti dhātā vacasā paricitā manasānupekkhitā diṭṭhiyā suppaṭividdhā, tassa bhavanti vattāro:**If it’s not, there will be people who say:*";
P_HTM[1463]="*‘iṅgha tāva āyasmā āgamaṃ pariyāpuṇassū’ti, itissa bhavanti vattāro.**‘Come on, venerable, memorize the scriptures first.’*";
P_HTM[1464]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, codakena bhikkhunā paraṃ codetukāmena evaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ:**Furthermore, a mendicant who wants to accuse another should check this:*";
P_HTM[1465]="*‘ubhayāni kho pana me pātimokkhāni vitthārena svāgatāni honti suvibhattāni suppavattīni suvinicchitāni suttaso anubyañjanaso.**‘Have both monastic codes been passed down to me in detail, well analyzed, well mastered, and well judged in both the rules and accompanying material?*";
P_HTM[1466]="*Saṃvijjati nu kho me eso dhammo udāhu no’ti?**Is this thing found in me or not?’*";
P_HTM[1467]="*No ce, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno ubhayāni pātimokkhāni vitthārena svāgatāni honti suvibhattāni suppavattīni suvinicchitāni suttaso anubyañjanaso, ‘idaṃ panāyasmā, kattha vuttaṃ bhagavatā’ti, iti puṭṭho na sampāyissati.**If it’s not, there will be people who say:*";
P_HTM[1468]="*Tassa bhavanti vattāro:* **";
P_HTM[1469]="*‘iṅgha tāva āyasmā vinayaṃ sikkhassū’ti, itissa bhavanti vattāro.**‘Come on, venerable, train in the code of conduct first.’*";
P_HTM[1470]="*Ime pañca dhammā ajjhattaṃ paccavekkhitabbā.**These are the five things they should check in themselves.*";
P_HTM[1471]="*Katame pañca dhammā ajjhattaṃ upaṭṭhāpetabbā?**What five things should they establish in themselves?*";
P_HTM[1472]="*‘Kālena vakkhāmi, no akālena;**‘I will speak at the right time, not at the wrong time.*";
P_HTM[1473]="*bhūtena vakkhāmi, no abhūtena;**I will speak truthfully, not falsely.*";
P_HTM[1474]="*saṇhena vakkhāmi, no pharusena;**I will speak gently, not harshly.*";
P_HTM[1475]="*atthasaṃhitena vakkhāmi, no anatthasaṃhitena;**I will speak beneficially, not harmfully.*";
P_HTM[1476]="*mettacitto vakkhāmi, no dosantaro’ti—**I will speak lovingly, not from secret hate.’*";
P_HTM[1477]="*ime pañca dhammā ajjhattaṃ upaṭṭhāpetabbā.**These are the five things they should establish in themselves.*";
P_HTM[1478]="*Codakena, bhikkhave, bhikkhunā paraṃ codetukāmena ime pañca dhamme ajjhattaṃ paccavekkhitvā ime pañca dhamme ajjhattaṃ upaṭṭhāpetvā paro codetabbo”ti.**A mendicant who wants to accuse another should first check these five things in themselves and establish these five things in themselves.”*";
P_HTM[1479]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1480]="*5. Rājantepurappavesanasuttaṃ**Entering a Royal Harem*";
P_HTM[1481]="*“Dasayime, bhikkhave, ādīnavā rājantepurappavesane.**“Mendicants, there are ten drawbacks to entering a royal harem.*";
P_HTM[1482]="*Katame dasa?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[1483]="*Idha, bhikkhave, rājā mahesiyā saddhiṃ nisinno hoti.**Firstly, a king is sitting with his chief queen*";
P_HTM[1484]="*Tatra bhikkhu pavisati.**when a monk enters.*";
P_HTM[1485]="*Mahesī vā bhikkhuṃ disvā sitaṃ pātukaroti, bhikkhu vā mahesiṃ disvā sitaṃ pātukaroti.**When the queen sees the monk she smiles, or when the monk sees the queen he smiles.*";
P_HTM[1486]="*Tattha rañño evaṃ hoti:**So the king thinks:*";
P_HTM[1487]="*‘addhā imesaṃ kataṃ vā karissanti vā’ti.**‘They’ve done it for sure, or they will do it.’*";
P_HTM[1488]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamo ādīnavo rājantepurappavesane. (1)**This is the first drawback of entering a royal harem.*";
P_HTM[1489]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, rājā bahukicco bahukaraṇīyo aññataraṃ itthiṃ gantvā na sarati:**Furthermore, a king has many duties, and much to do. He has sex with one of the women but doesn’t remember.*";
P_HTM[1490]="*‘sā tena gabbhaṃ gaṇhāti’.**She gets pregnant from that.*";
P_HTM[1491]="*Tattha rañño evaṃ hoti:**So the king thinks:*";
P_HTM[1492]="*‘na kho idha añño koci pavisati, aññatra pabbajitena.**‘No-one else has entered here, except for that monk.*";
P_HTM[1493]="*Siyā nu kho pabbajitassa kamman’ti.**Could this be the monk’s doing?’*";
P_HTM[1494]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyo ādīnavo rājantepurappavesane. (2)**This is the second drawback of entering a royal harem.*";
P_HTM[1495]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, rañño antepure aññataraṃ ratanaṃ nassati.**Furthermore, a gem is lost somewhere in the royal harem.*";
P_HTM[1496]="*Tattha rañño evaṃ hoti:**So the king thinks:*";
P_HTM[1497]="*‘na kho idha añño koci pavisati, aññatra pabbajitena.**‘No-one else has entered here, except for that monk.*";
P_HTM[1498]="*Siyā nu kho pabbajitassa kamman’ti.**Could this be the monk’s doing?’*";
P_HTM[1499]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyo ādīnavo rājantepurappavesane. (3)**This is the third drawback of entering a royal harem.*";
P_HTM[1500]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, rañño antepure abbhantarā guyhamantā bahiddhā sambhedaṃ gacchanti.**Furthermore, secret deliberations in the royal harem are leaked outside.*";
P_HTM[1501]="*Tattha rañño evaṃ hoti:**So the king thinks:*";
P_HTM[1502]="*‘na kho idha añño koci pavisati, aññatra pabbajitena.**‘No-one else has entered here, except for that monk.*";
P_HTM[1503]="*Siyā nu kho pabbajitassa kamman’ti.**Could this be the monk’s doing?’*";
P_HTM[1504]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, catuttho ādīnavo rājantepurappavesane. (4)**This is the fourth drawback of entering a royal harem.*";
P_HTM[1505]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, rañño antepure pitā vā puttaṃ pattheti putto vā pitaraṃ pattheti.**Furthermore, in a royal harem, a father longs for their son, or a son longs for his father.*";
P_HTM[1506]="*Tesaṃ evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[1507]="*‘na kho idha añño koci pavisati, aññatra pabbajitena.**‘No-one else has entered here, except for that monk.*";
P_HTM[1508]="*Siyā nu kho pabbajitassa kamman’ti.**Could this be the monk’s doing?’*";
P_HTM[1509]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, pañcamo ādīnavo rājantepurappavesane. (5)**This is the fifth drawback of entering a royal harem.*";
P_HTM[1510]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, rājā nīcaṭṭhāniyaṃ ucce ṭhāne ṭhapeti.**Furthermore, the king promotes someone to a higher position.*";
P_HTM[1511]="*Yesaṃ taṃ amanāpaṃ tesaṃ evaṃ hoti:**Those who are upset by this think:*";
P_HTM[1512]="*‘rājā kho pabbajitena saṃsaṭṭho.**‘The king is close to that monk.*";
P_HTM[1513]="*Siyā nu kho pabbajitassa kamman’ti.**Could this be the monk’s doing?’*";
P_HTM[1514]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, chaṭṭho ādīnavo rājantepurappavesane. (6)**This is the sixth drawback of entering a royal harem.*";
P_HTM[1515]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, rājā uccaṭṭhāniyaṃ nīce ṭhāne ṭhapeti.**Furthermore, the king demotes someone to a lower position.*";
P_HTM[1516]="*Yesaṃ taṃ amanāpaṃ tesaṃ evaṃ hoti:**Those who are upset by this think:*";
P_HTM[1517]="*‘rājā kho pabbajitena saṃsaṭṭho.**‘The king is close to that monk.*";
P_HTM[1518]="*Siyā nu kho pabbajitassa kamman’ti.**Could this be the monk’s doing?’*";
P_HTM[1519]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, sattamo ādīnavo rājantepurappavesane. (7)**This is the seventh drawback of entering a royal harem.*";
P_HTM[1520]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, rājā akāle senaṃ uyyojeti.**Furthermore, the king dispatches the army at the wrong time.*";
P_HTM[1521]="*Yesaṃ taṃ amanāpaṃ tesaṃ evaṃ hoti:**Those who are upset by this think:*";
P_HTM[1522]="*‘rājā kho pabbajitena saṃsaṭṭho.**‘The king is close to that monk.*";
P_HTM[1523]="*Siyā nu kho pabbajitassa kamman’ti.**Could this be the monk’s doing?’*";
P_HTM[1524]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, aṭṭhamo ādīnavo rājantepurappavesane. (8)**This is the eighth drawback of entering a royal harem.*";
P_HTM[1525]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, rājā kāle senaṃ uyyojetvā antarāmaggato nivattāpeti.**Furthermore, the king dispatches the army at the right time, but orders it to turn back while still on the road.*";
P_HTM[1526]="*Yesaṃ taṃ amanāpaṃ tesaṃ evaṃ hoti:**Those who are upset by this think:*";
P_HTM[1527]="*‘rājā kho pabbajitena saṃsaṭṭho.**‘The king is close to that monk.*";
P_HTM[1528]="*Siyā nu kho pabbajitassa kamman’ti.**Could this be the monk’s doing?’*";
P_HTM[1529]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, navamo ādīnavo rājantepurappavesane. (9)**This is the ninth drawback of entering a royal harem.*";
P_HTM[1530]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, rañño antepuraṃ hatthisammaddaṃ assasammaddaṃ rathasammaddaṃ rajanīyāni rūpasaddagandharasaphoṭṭhabbāni, yāni na pabbajitassa sāruppāni.**Furthermore, in the royal harem there is a trampling of elephants, horses, and chariots, as well as arousing sights, sounds, smells, tastes, and touches that do not befit a monk.*";
P_HTM[1531]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, dasamo ādīnavo rājantepurappavesane.**This is the tenth drawback of entering a royal harem.*";
P_HTM[1532]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dasa ādīnavā rājantepurappavesane”ti. (10)**These are the ten drawbacks of entering a royal harem.”*";
P_HTM[1533]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1534]="*6. Sakkasuttaṃ**With the Sakyans*";
P_HTM[1535]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sakkesu viharati kapilavatthusmiṃ nigrodhārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Sakyans, near Kapilavatthu in the Banyan Tree Monastery.*";
P_HTM[1536]="*Atha kho sambahulā sakkā upāsakā tadahuposathe yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinne kho sakke upāsake bhagavā etadavoca:**Then on the sabbath several Sakyan lay followers went up to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side. The Buddha said to them:*";
P_HTM[1537]="*“api nu tumhe, sakkā, aṭṭhaṅgasamannāgataṃ uposathaṃ upavasathā”ti?**“Sakyans, do you observe the sabbath with its eight factors?”*";
P_HTM[1538]="*“Appekadā mayaṃ, bhante, aṭṭhaṅgasamannāgataṃ uposathaṃ upavasāma, appekadā na upavasāmā”ti.**“Sir, sometimes we do, sometimes we don’t.”*";
P_HTM[1539]="*“Tesaṃ vo, sakkā, alābhā tesaṃ dulladdhaṃ, ye tumhe evaṃ sokasabhaye jīvite maraṇasabhaye jīvite appekadā aṭṭhaṅgasamannāgataṃ uposathaṃ upavasatha, appekadā na upavasatha.**“That’s your loss, Sakyans, it’s your misfortune. In this life with its fear of sorrow and death, you sometimes keep the sabbath and you sometimes don’t.*";
P_HTM[1540]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, sakkā,**What do you think, Sakyans?*";
P_HTM[1541]="*idha puriso yena kenaci kammaṭṭhānena anāpajja akusalaṃ divasaṃ aḍḍhakahāpaṇaṃ nibbiseyya.**Take a man who earns half a dollar for an honest day’s work.*";
P_HTM[1542]="*Dakkho puriso uṭṭhānasampannoti alaṃvacanāyā”ti?**Is this enough to call him a deft and industrious man?”*";
P_HTM[1543]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1544]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, sakkā,**“What do you think, Sakyans?*";
P_HTM[1545]="*idha puriso yena kenaci kammaṭṭhānena anāpajja akusalaṃ divasaṃ kahāpaṇaṃ nibbiseyya.**Take a man who earns a dollar for an honest day’s work.*";
P_HTM[1546]="*Dakkho puriso uṭṭhānasampannoti alaṃvacanāyā”ti?**Is this enough to call him a deft and industrious man?”*";
P_HTM[1547]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1548]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, sakkā,**“What do you think, Sakyans?*";
P_HTM[1549]="*idha puriso yena kenaci kammaṭṭhānena anāpajja akusalaṃ divasaṃ dve kahāpaṇe nibbiseyya …**Take a man who, for an honest day’s work, earns two dollars …*";
P_HTM[1550]="*tayo kahāpaṇe nibbiseyya …**three dollars …*";
P_HTM[1551]="*cattāro kahāpaṇe nibbiseyya …**four dollars …*";
P_HTM[1552]="*pañca kahāpaṇe nibbiseyya …**five dollars …*";
P_HTM[1553]="*cha kahāpaṇe nibbiseyya …**six dollars …*";
P_HTM[1554]="*satta kahāpaṇe nibbiseyya …**seven dollars …*";
P_HTM[1555]="*aṭṭha kahāpaṇe nibbiseyya …**eight dollars …*";
P_HTM[1556]="*nava kahāpaṇe nibbiseyya …**nine dollars …*";
P_HTM[1557]="*dasa kahāpaṇe nibbiseyya …**ten dollars …*";
P_HTM[1558]="*vīsa kahāpaṇe nibbiseyya …**twenty dollars …*";
P_HTM[1559]="*tiṃsa kahāpaṇe nibbiseyya …**thirty dollars …*";
P_HTM[1560]="*cattārīsaṃ kahāpaṇe nibbiseyya …**forty dollars …*";
P_HTM[1561]="*paññāsaṃ kahāpaṇe nibbiseyya …**fifty dollars …*";
P_HTM[1562]="*kahāpaṇasataṃ nibbiseyya.**a hundred dollars.*";
P_HTM[1563]="*Dakkho puriso uṭṭhānasampannoti alaṃvacanāyā”ti?**Is this enough to call him a deft and industrious man?”*";
P_HTM[1564]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1565]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, sakkā,**“What do you think, Sakyans?*";
P_HTM[1566]="*api nu so puriso divase divase kahāpaṇasataṃ kahāpaṇasahassaṃ nibbisamāno laddhaṃ laddhaṃ nikkhipanto vassasatāyuko vassasatajīvī mahantaṃ bhogakkhandhaṃ adhigaccheyyā”ti?**Suppose that man earned a hundred or a thousand dollars every day and saved it all up. If he lived for a hundred years, would he not accumulate a large mass of wealth?”*";
P_HTM[1567]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1568]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, sakkā,**“What do you think, Sakyans?*";
P_HTM[1569]="*api nu so puriso bhogahetu bhoganidānaṃ bhogādhikaraṇaṃ ekaṃ vā rattiṃ ekaṃ vā divasaṃ upaḍḍhaṃ vā rattiṃ upaḍḍhaṃ vā divasaṃ ekantasukhappaṭisaṃvedī vihareyyā”ti?**Would that man, on account of that wealth, experience perfect happiness for a single day or night, or even half a day or night?”*";
P_HTM[1570]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1571]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?**“Why is that?”*";
P_HTM[1572]="*“Kāmā hi, bhante, aniccā tucchā musā mosadhammā”ti.**“Because sensual pleasures, sir, are impermanent, hollow, false, and deceptive.”*";
P_HTM[1573]="*“Idha pana vo, sakkā, mama sāvako dasa vassāni appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto yathā mayānusiṭṭhaṃ tathā paṭipajjamāno satampi vassāni satampi vassasatāni satampi vassasahassāni ekantasukhappaṭisaṃvedī vihareyya.**“But take one of my disciples who lives diligent, keen, and resolute for ten years, practicing in line with my instructions. They can experience perfect happiness for a hundred years, ten thousand years, or a hundred thousand years.*";
P_HTM[1574]="*So ca khvassa sakadāgāmī vā anāgāmī vā apaṇṇakaṃ vā sotāpanno.**And they could become a once-returner or a non-returner, or guaranteed a stream-enterer.*";
P_HTM[1575]="*Tiṭṭhantu, sakkā, dasa vassāni.**Let alone ten years,*";
P_HTM[1576]="*Idha mama sāvako nava vassāni …**take one of my disciples who lives diligent, keen, and resolute for nine years …*";
P_HTM[1577]="*aṭṭha vassāni …**eight years …*";
P_HTM[1578]="*satta vassāni …**seven years …*";
P_HTM[1579]="*cha vassāni …**six years …*";
P_HTM[1580]="*pañca vassāni …**five years …*";
P_HTM[1581]="*cattāri vassāni …**four years …*";
P_HTM[1582]="*tīṇi vassāni …**three years …*";
P_HTM[1583]="*dve vassāni …**two years …*";
P_HTM[1584]="*ekaṃ vassaṃ appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto yathā mayānusiṭṭhaṃ tathā paṭipajjamāno satampi vassāni satampi vassasatāni satampi vassasahassāni ekantasukhappaṭisaṃvedī vihareyya, so ca khvassa sakadāgāmī vā anāgāmī vā apaṇṇakaṃ vā sotāpanno.**one year …*";
P_HTM[1585]="*Tiṭṭhatu, sakkā, ekaṃ vassaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1586]="*Idha mama sāvako dasa māse appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto yathā mayānusiṭṭhaṃ tathā paṭipajjamāno satampi vassāni satampi vassasatāni satampi vassasahassāni ekantasukhappaṭisaṃvedī vihareyya, so ca khvassa sakadāgāmī vā anāgāmī vā apaṇṇakaṃ vā sotāpanno.**ten months …*";
P_HTM[1587]="*Tiṭṭhantu, sakkā, dasa māsā.* **";
P_HTM[1588]="*Idha mama sāvako nava māse …**nine months …*";
P_HTM[1589]="*aṭṭha māse …**eight months …*";
P_HTM[1590]="*satta māse …**seven months …*";
P_HTM[1591]="*cha māse …**six months …*";
P_HTM[1592]="*pañca māse …**five months …*";
P_HTM[1593]="*cattāro māse …**four months …*";
P_HTM[1594]="*tayo māse …**three months …*";
P_HTM[1595]="*dve māse …**two months …*";
P_HTM[1596]="*ekaṃ māsaṃ …**one month …*";
P_HTM[1597]="*aḍḍhamāsaṃ appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto yathā mayānusiṭṭhaṃ tathā paṭipajjamāno satampi vassāni satampi vassasatāni satampi vassasahassāni ekantasukhappaṭisaṃvedī vihareyya, so ca khvassa sakadāgāmī vā anāgāmī vā apaṇṇakaṃ vā sotāpanno.**a fortnight …*";
P_HTM[1598]="*Tiṭṭhatu, sakkā, aḍḍhamāso.* **";
P_HTM[1599]="*Idha mama sāvako dasa rattindive appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto yathā mayānusiṭṭhaṃ tathā paṭipajjamāno satampi vassāni satampi vassasatāni satampi vassasahassāni ekantasukhappaṭisaṃvedī vihareyya, so ca khvassa sakadāgāmī vā anāgāmī vā apaṇṇakaṃ vā sotāpanno.**ten days …*";
P_HTM[1600]="*Tiṭṭhantu, sakkā, dasa rattindivā.* **";
P_HTM[1601]="*Idha mama sāvako nava rattindive …**nine days …*";
P_HTM[1602]="*aṭṭha rattindive …**eight days …*";
P_HTM[1603]="*satta rattindive …**seven days …*";
P_HTM[1604]="*cha rattindive …**six days …*";
P_HTM[1605]="*pañca rattindive …**five days …*";
P_HTM[1606]="*cattāro rattindive …**four days …*";
P_HTM[1607]="*tayo rattindive …**three days …*";
P_HTM[1608]="*dve rattindive …**two days …*";
P_HTM[1609]="*ekaṃ rattindivaṃ appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto yathā mayānusiṭṭhaṃ tathā paṭipajjamāno satampi vassāni satampi vassasatāni satampi vassasahassāni ekantasukhappaṭisaṃvedī vihareyya, so ca khvassa sakadāgāmī vā anāgāmī vā apaṇṇakaṃ vā sotāpanno.**Let alone two days, take one of my disciples who lives diligent, keen, and resolute for one day, practicing in line with my instructions. They can experience perfect happiness for a hundred years, ten thousand years, or a hundred thousand years. And they could become a once-returner or a non-returner, or guaranteed a stream-enterer.*";
P_HTM[1610]="*Tesaṃ vo, sakkā, alābhā tesaṃ dulladdhaṃ, ye tumhe evaṃ sokasabhaye jīvite maraṇasabhaye jīvite appekadā aṭṭhaṅgasamannāgataṃ uposathaṃ upavasatha, appekadā na upavasathā”ti.**It’s your loss, Sakyans, it’s your misfortune. In this life with its fear of sorrow and death, you sometimes keep the sabbath and you sometimes don’t.”*";
P_HTM[1611]="*“Ete mayaṃ, bhante, ajjatagge aṭṭhaṅgasamannāgataṃ uposathaṃ upavasissāmā”ti.**“Well, sir, from this day forth we will observe the sabbath with its eight factors.”*";
P_HTM[1612]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1613]="*7. Mahālisuttaṃ**With Mahāli*";
P_HTM[1614]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā vesāliyaṃ viharati mahāvane kūṭāgārasālāyaṃ.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Vesālī, at the Great Wood, in the hall with the peaked roof.*";
P_HTM[1615]="*Atha kho mahāli licchavi yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho mahāli licchavi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Mahāli the Licchavi went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1616]="*“ko nu kho, bhante, hetu, ko paccayo pāpassa kammassa kiriyāya pāpassa kammassa pavattiyā”ti?**“What is the cause, sir, what is the reason for doing bad deeds, for performing bad deeds?”*";
P_HTM[1617]="*“Lobho kho, mahāli, hetu, lobho paccayo pāpassa kammassa kiriyāya pāpassa kammassa pavattiyā.**“Greed is a cause, Mahāli, greed is a reason for doing bad deeds, for performing bad deeds.*";
P_HTM[1618]="*Doso kho, mahāli, hetu, doso paccayo pāpassa kammassa kiriyāya pāpassa kammassa pavattiyā.**Hate is a cause of bad deeds …*";
P_HTM[1619]="*Moho kho, mahāli, hetu, moho paccayo pāpassa kammassa kiriyāya pāpassa kammassa pavattiyā.**Delusion is a cause of bad deeds …*";
P_HTM[1620]="*Ayoniso manasikāro kho, mahāli, hetu, ayoniso manasikāro paccayo pāpassa kammassa kiriyāya pāpassa kammassa pavattiyā.**Improper attention is a cause of bad deeds …*";
P_HTM[1621]="*Micchāpaṇihitaṃ kho, mahāli, cittaṃ hetu, micchāpaṇihitaṃ cittaṃ paccayo pāpassa kammassa kiriyāya pāpassa kammassa pavattiyāti.**A wrongly directed mind is a cause of bad deeds …*";
P_HTM[1622]="*Ayaṃ kho, mahāli, hetu, ayaṃ paccayo pāpassa kammassa kiriyāya pāpassa kammassa pavattiyā”ti.**This is the cause, Mahāli, this is the reason for doing bad deeds, for performing bad deeds.”*";
P_HTM[1623]="*“Ko pana, bhante, hetu ko paccayo kalyāṇassa kammassa kiriyāya kalyāṇassa kammassa pavattiyā”ti?**“What is the cause, sir, what is the reason for doing good deeds, for performing good deeds?”*";
P_HTM[1624]="*“Alobho kho, mahāli, hetu, alobho paccayo kalyāṇassa kammassa kiriyāya kalyāṇassa kammassa pavattiyā.**“Contentment is a cause, Mahāli, contentment is a reason for doing good deeds, for performing good deeds.*";
P_HTM[1625]="*Adoso kho, mahāli, hetu, adoso paccayo kalyāṇassa kammassa kiriyāya kalyāṇassa kammassa pavattiyā.**Love is a cause of good deeds …*";
P_HTM[1626]="*Amoho kho, mahāli, hetu, amoho paccayo kalyāṇassa kammassa kiriyāya kalyāṇassa kammassa pavattiyā.**Understanding is a cause of good deeds …*";
P_HTM[1627]="*Yoniso manasikāro kho, mahāli, hetu, yoniso manasikāro paccayo kalyāṇassa kammassa kiriyāya kalyāṇassa kammassa pavattiyā.**Proper attention is a cause of good deeds …*";
P_HTM[1628]="*Sammāpaṇihitaṃ kho, mahāli, cittaṃ hetu, sammāpaṇihitaṃ cittaṃ paccayo kalyāṇassa kammassa kiriyāya kalyāṇassa kammassa pavattiyā.**A rightly directed mind is a cause of good deeds …*";
P_HTM[1629]="*Ayaṃ kho, mahāli, hetu, ayaṃ paccayo kalyāṇassa kammassa kiriyāya kalyāṇassa kammassa pavattiyā.**This is the cause, Mahāli, this is the reason for doing good deeds, for performing good deeds.*";
P_HTM[1630]="*Ime ca, mahāli, dasa dhammā loke na saṃvijjeyyuṃ, nayidha paññāyetha adhammacariyāvisamacariyāti vā dhammacariyāsamacariyāti vā.**If these ten things were not found in the world, we wouldn’t see either unprincipled and immoral conduct, or principled and moral conduct.*";
P_HTM[1631]="*Yasmā ca kho, mahāli, ime dasa dhammā loke saṃvijjanti, tasmā paññāyati adhammacariyāvisamacariyāti vā dhammacariyāsamacariyāti vā”ti.**But since these ten things are found in the world, we see both unprincipled and immoral conduct, and principled and moral conduct.”*";
P_HTM[1632]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1633]="*8. Pabbajitaabhiṇhasuttaṃ**Ten Regular Reflections for a Renunciate*";
P_HTM[1634]="*“Dasayime, bhikkhave, dhammā pabbajitena abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbā.**“Mendicants, one who has gone forth should often review these ten things.*";
P_HTM[1635]="*Katame dasa?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[1636]="*‘Vevaṇṇiyamhi ajjhupagato’ti pabbajitena abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ. (1)**One who has gone forth should often review this: ‘I have secured freedom from class.’*";
P_HTM[1637]="*‘Parapaṭibaddhā me jīvikā’ti pabbajitena abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ. (2)**‘My livelihood is tied up with others.’*";
P_HTM[1638]="*‘Añño me ākappo karaṇīyo’ti pabbajitena abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ. (3)**‘My behavior should be different.’*";
P_HTM[1639]="*‘Kacci nu kho me attā sīlato na upavadatī’ti pabbajitena abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ. (4)**‘I hope there’s no reason to blame myself when it comes to ethical conduct?’*";
P_HTM[1640]="*‘Kacci nu kho maṃ anuvicca viññū sabrahmacārī sīlato na upavadantī’ti pabbajitena abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ. (5)**‘I hope that, after examination, sensible spiritual companions don’t reproach any aspect of my ethics?’*";
P_HTM[1641]="*‘Sabbehi me piyehi manāpehi nānābhāvo vinābhāvo’ti pabbajitena abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ. (6)**‘I must be parted and separated from all I hold dear and beloved.’*";
P_HTM[1642]="*‘Kammassakomhi kammadāyādo kammayoni kammabandhu kammapaṭisaraṇo,**‘I am the owner of my deeds and heir to my deeds. Deeds are my womb, my relative, and my refuge.*";
P_HTM[1643]="*yaṃ kammaṃ karissāmi kalyāṇaṃ vā pāpakaṃ vā tassa dāyādo bhavissāmī’ti pabbajitena abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ. (7)**I shall be the heir of whatever deeds I do, whether good or bad.’*";
P_HTM[1644]="*‘Kathaṃbhūtassa me rattindivā vītivattantī’ti pabbajitena abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ. (8)**‘As the days and nights flit by, what sort of person am I becoming?’*";
P_HTM[1645]="*‘Kacci nu kho ahaṃ suññāgāre abhiramāmī’ti pabbajitena abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ. (9)**‘Do I love to stay in empty huts?’*";
P_HTM[1646]="*‘Atthi nu kho me uttari manussadhammo alamariyañāṇadassanaviseso adhigato, yenāhaṃ pacchime kāle sabrahmacārīhi puṭṭho na maṅku bhavissāmī’ti pabbajitena abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ. (10)**‘Do I have any superhuman distinctions in knowledge and vision worthy of the noble ones, so that when my spiritual companions question me on my deathbed I will not be embarrassed?’*";
P_HTM[1647]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dasa dhammā pabbajitena abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbā”ti.**One who has gone forth should often review these ten things.”*";
P_HTM[1648]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1649]="*9. Sarīraṭṭhadhammasuttaṃ**Existing Because of the Body*";
P_HTM[1650]="*“Dasayime, bhikkhave, dhammā sarīraṭṭhā.**“Mendicants, these ten things exist because of the body.*";
P_HTM[1651]="*Katame dasa?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[1652]="*Sītaṃ, uṇhaṃ, jighacchā, pipāsā, uccāro, passāvo, kāyasaṃvaro, vacīsaṃvaro, ājīvasaṃvaro, ponobhaviko bhavasaṅkhāro—**Cold, heat, hunger, thirst, feces, urine, restraint of body, speech, and livelihood, and the will to live that leads to future lives.*";
P_HTM[1653]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, dasa dhammā sarīraṭṭhā”ti.**These ten things exist because of the body.”*";
P_HTM[1654]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1655]="*10. Bhaṇḍanasuttaṃ**Arguments*";
P_HTM[1656]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[1657]="*Tena kho pana samayena sambahulā bhikkhū pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkantā upaṭṭhānasālāyaṃ sannisinnā sannipatitā bhaṇḍanajātā kalahajātā vivādāpannā aññamaññaṃ mukhasattīhi vitudantā viharanti.**Now at that time, after the meal, on return from alms-round, several mendicants sat together in the meeting hall. They were arguing, quarreling, and disputing, wounding each other with barbed words.*";
P_HTM[1658]="*Atha kho bhagavā sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yena upaṭṭhānasālā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then in the late afternoon, the Buddha came out of retreat and went to the assembly hall. He sat down on the seat spread out,*";
P_HTM[1659]="*Nisajja kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**and addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1660]="*“kāya nuttha, bhikkhave, etarahi kathāya sannisinnā sannipatitā, kā ca pana vo antarākathā vippakatā”ti?**“Mendicants, what were you sitting talking about just now? What conversation was unfinished?”*";
P_HTM[1661]="*“Idha mayaṃ, bhante, pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkantā upaṭṭhānasālāyaṃ sannisinnā sannipatitā bhaṇḍanajātā kalahajātā vivādāpannā aññamaññaṃ mukhasattīhi vitudantā viharāmā”ti.**“Sir, after the meal, on return from alms-round, we sat together in the meeting hall, arguing, quarreling, and disputing, wounding each other with barbed words.”*";
P_HTM[1662]="*“Na kho panetaṃ, bhikkhave, tumhākaṃ patirūpaṃ kulaputtānaṃ saddhāya agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajitānaṃ, yaṃ tumhe bhaṇḍanajātā kalahajātā vivādāpannā aññamaññaṃ mukhasattīhi vitudantā vihareyyātha.**“Mendicants, this is not appropriate for you gentlemen who have gone forth in faith from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[1663]="*Dasayime, bhikkhave, dhammā sāraṇīyā piyakaraṇā garukaraṇā saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattanti.**There are ten warm-hearted qualities that make for fondness and respect, conducing to inclusion, harmony, and unity, without quarreling.*";
P_HTM[1664]="*Katame dasa?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[1665]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlavā hoti, pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharati ācāragocarasampanno aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī, samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu.**Firstly, a mendicant is ethical, restrained in the monastic code, conducting themselves well and seeking alms in suitable places. Seeing danger in the slightest fault, they keep the rules they’ve undertaken.*";
P_HTM[1666]="*Yampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlavā hoti … pe … samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu,**When a mendicant is ethical,*";
P_HTM[1667]="*ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo piyakaraṇo garukaraṇo saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (1)**this warm-hearted quality makes for fondness and respect, conducing to inclusion, harmony, and unity, without quarreling.*";
P_HTM[1668]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu bahussuto hoti sutadharo sutasannicayo, ye te dhammā ādikalyāṇā majjhekalyāṇā pariyosānakalyāṇā sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ abhivadanti, tathārūpāssa dhammā bahussutā honti dhātā vacasā paricitā manasānupekkhitā diṭṭhiyā suppaṭividdhā.**Furthermore, a mendicant is very learned, remembering and keeping what they’ve learned. These teachings are good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased, describing a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure. They are very learned in such teachings, remembering them, reinforcing them by recitation, mentally scrutinizing them, and comprehending them theoretically. …*";
P_HTM[1669]="*Yampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu bahussuto hoti … pe … diṭṭhiyā suppaṭividdhā,* **";
P_HTM[1670]="*ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo piyakaraṇo garukaraṇo saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (2)* **";
P_HTM[1671]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kalyāṇamitto hoti kalyāṇasahāyo kalyāṇasampavaṅko.**Furthermore, a mendicant has good friends, companions, and associates. …*";
P_HTM[1672]="*Yampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kalyāṇamitto hoti kalyāṇasahāyo kalyāṇasampavaṅko,* **";
P_HTM[1673]="*ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo piyakaraṇo garukaraṇo saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (3)* **";
P_HTM[1674]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu suvaco hoti sovacassakaraṇehi dhammehi samannāgato khamo padakkhiṇaggāhī anusāsaniṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant is easy to admonish, having qualities that make them easy to admonish. They’re patient, and take instruction respectfully. …*";
P_HTM[1675]="*Yampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu suvaco hoti sovacassakaraṇehi dhammehi samannāgato khamo padakkhiṇaggāhī anusāsaniṃ,* **";
P_HTM[1676]="*ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo piyakaraṇo garukaraṇo saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (4)* **";
P_HTM[1677]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yāni tāni sabrahmacārīnaṃ uccāvacāni kiṅkaraṇīyāni—tattha dakkho hoti analaso, tatrūpāyāya vīmaṃsāya samannāgato alaṃ kātuṃ alaṃ saṃvidhātuṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant is deft and tireless in a diverse spectrum of duties for their spiritual companions, understanding how to go about things in order to complete and organize the work. …*";
P_HTM[1678]="*Yampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yāni tāni sabrahmacārīnaṃ uccāvacāni kiṅkaraṇīyāni—tattha dakkho hoti analaso tatrūpāyāya vīmaṃsāya samannāgato alaṃ kātuṃ alaṃ saṃvidhātuṃ,* **";
P_HTM[1679]="*ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo piyakaraṇo garukaraṇo saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (5)* **";
P_HTM[1680]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu dhammakāmo hoti piyasamudāhāro, abhidhamme abhivinaye uḷārapāmojjo.**Furthermore, a mendicant loves the teachings and is a delight to converse with, being full of joy in the teaching and training. …*";
P_HTM[1681]="*Yampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu dhammakāmo hoti piyasamudāhāro, abhidhamme abhivinaye uḷārapāmojjo,* **";
P_HTM[1682]="*ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo piyakaraṇo garukaraṇo saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (6)* **";
P_HTM[1683]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu āraddhavīriyo viharati akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ upasampadāya, thāmavā daḷhaparakkamo anikkhittadhuro kusalesu dhammesu.**Furthermore, a mendicant lives with energy roused up for giving up unskillful qualities and embracing skillful qualities. They are strong, staunchly vigorous, not slacking off when it comes to developing skillful qualities. …*";
P_HTM[1684]="*Yampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu āraddhavīriyo viharati akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ upasampadāya, thāmavā daḷhaparakkamo anikkhittadhuro kusalesu dhammesu,* **";
P_HTM[1685]="*ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo piyakaraṇo garukaraṇo saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (7)* **";
P_HTM[1686]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti itarītaracīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānapaccayabhesajjaparikkhārena.**Furthermore, a mendicant is content with any kind of robes, alms-food, lodgings, and medicines and supplies for the sick. …*";
P_HTM[1687]="*Yampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti itarītaracīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānapaccayabhesajjaparikkhārena,* **";
P_HTM[1688]="*ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo … pe … saṃvattati. (8)* **";
P_HTM[1689]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu satimā hoti, paramena satinepakkena samannāgato, cirakatampi cirabhāsitampi saritā anussaritā.**Furthermore, a mendicant is mindful. They have utmost mindfulness and alertness, and can remember and recall what was said and done long ago. …*";
P_HTM[1690]="*Yampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu satimā hoti, paramena satinepakkena samannāgato, cirakatampi cirabhāsitampi saritā anussaritā,* **";
P_HTM[1691]="*ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo … pe … saṃvattati. (9)* **";
P_HTM[1692]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu paññavā hoti, udayatthagāminiyā paññāya samannāgato ariyāya nibbedhikāya sammā dukkhakkhayagāminiyā.**Furthermore, a mendicant is wise. They have the wisdom of arising and passing away which is noble, penetrative, and leads to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[1693]="*Yampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu paññavā hoti, udayatthagāminiyā paññāya samannāgato ariyāya nibbedhikāya sammā dukkhakkhayagāminiyā,**When a mendicant is wise,*";
P_HTM[1694]="*ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo … pe … saṃvattati. (10)**this warm-hearted quality makes for fondness and respect, helping the Saṅgha to live in harmony and unity, without quarreling.*";
P_HTM[1695]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dasa dhammā sāraṇīyā piyakaraṇā garukaraṇā saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattantī”ti.**These ten warm-hearted qualities make for fondness and respect, conducing to inclusion, harmony, and unity, without quarreling.”*";
P_HTM[1696]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1697]="*Akkosavaggo pañcamo.* **";
P_HTM[1698]="*Vivādā dve ca mūlāni,* **";
P_HTM[1699]="*kusinārapavesane;* **";
P_HTM[1700]="*Sakko mahāli abhiṇhaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[1701]="*sarīraṭṭhā ca bhaṇḍanāti.* **";
P_HTM[1702]="*Paṭhamo paṇṇāsako samatto.* **";
P_HTM[1703]="*123. Rāgapeyyālaṃ**Your Own Mind*";
P_HTM[1704]="*1. Sacittasuttaṃ**Your Own Mind*";
P_HTM[1705]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[1706]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[1707]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[1708]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[1709]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[1710]="*“No ce, bhikkhave, bhikkhu paracittapariyāyakusalo hoti, atha ‘sacittapariyāyakusalo bhavissāmī’ti—**“Mendicants, if a mendicant isn’t skilled in the ways of another’s mind, then they should train themselves: ‘I will be skilled in the ways of my own mind.’*";
P_HTM[1711]="*evañhi vo, bhikkhave, sikkhitabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1712]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sacittapariyāyakusalo hoti?**And how is a mendicant skilled in the ways of their own mind?*";
P_HTM[1713]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, itthī vā puriso vā daharo yuvā maṇḍanakajātiko ādāse vā parisuddhe pariyodāte acche vā udakapatte sakaṃ mukhanimittaṃ paccavekkhamāno sace tattha passati rajaṃ vā aṅgaṇaṃ vā, tasseva rajassa vā aṅgaṇassa vā pahānāya vāyamati.**Suppose there was a woman or man who was young, youthful, and fond of adornments, and they check their own reflection in a clean bright mirror or a clear bowl of water. If they see any dirt or blemish there, they’d try to remove it.*";
P_HTM[1714]="*No ce tattha passati rajaṃ vā aṅgaṇaṃ vā, tenevattamano hoti paripuṇṇasaṅkappo:**But if they don’t see any dirt or blemish there, they’re happy with that, as they’ve got all they wished for:*";
P_HTM[1715]="*‘lābhā vata me, parisuddhaṃ vata me’ti.**‘How fortunate that I’m clean!’*";
P_HTM[1716]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno paccavekkhaṇā bahukārā hoti kusalesu dhammesu:**In the same way, checking is very helpful for a mendicant’s skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[1717]="*‘abhijjhālu nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, anabhijjhālu nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, byāpannacitto nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, abyāpannacitto nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, thinamiddhapariyuṭṭhito nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, vigatathinamiddho nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, uddhato nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, anuddhato nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, vicikiccho nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, tiṇṇavicikiccho nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, kodhano nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, akkodhano nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, saṃkiliṭṭhacitto nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, asaṃkiliṭṭhacitto nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, sāraddhakāyo nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, asāraddhakāyo nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, kusīto nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, āraddhavīriyo nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, asamāhito nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, samāhito nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmī’ti.**‘Am I often covetous or not? Am I often malicious or not? Am I often overcome with dullness and drowsiness or not? Am I often restless or not? Am I often doubtful or not? Am I often irritable or not? Am I often corrupted in mind or not? Am I often disturbed in body or not? Am I often energetic or not? Am I often immersed in samādhi or not?’*";
P_HTM[1718]="*Sace, bhikkhave, bhikkhu paccavekkhamāno evaṃ jānāti:**Suppose that, upon checking, a mendicant knows this:*";
P_HTM[1719]="*‘abhijjhālu bahulaṃ viharāmi, byāpannacitto bahulaṃ viharāmi, thinamiddhapariyuṭṭhito bahulaṃ viharāmi, uddhato bahulaṃ viharāmi, vicikiccho bahulaṃ viharāmi, kodhano bahulaṃ viharāmi, saṅkiliṭṭhacitto bahulaṃ viharāmi, sāraddhakāyo bahulaṃ viharāmi, kusīto bahulaṃ viharāmi, asamāhito bahulaṃ viharāmī’ti, tena, bhikkhave, bhikkhunā tesaṃyeva pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya adhimatto chando ca vāyāmo ca ussāho ca ussoḷhī ca appaṭivānī ca sati ca sampajaññañca karaṇīyaṃ.**‘I am often covetous, malicious, overcome with dullness and drowsiness, restless, doubtful, irritable, defiled in mind, disturbed in body, lazy, and not immersed in samādhi.’ In order to give up those bad, unskillful qualities, they should apply outstanding enthusiasm, effort, zeal, vigor, perseverance, mindfulness, and situational awareness.*";
P_HTM[1720]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ādittacelo vā ādittasīso vā. Tasseva celassa vā sīsassa vā nibbāpanāya adhimattaṃ chandañca vāyāmañca ussāhañca ussoḷhiñca appaṭivāniñca satiñca sampajaññañca kareyya.**Suppose your clothes or head were on fire. In order to extinguish it, you’d apply outstanding enthusiasm, effort, zeal, vigor, perseverance, mindfulness, and situational awareness.*";
P_HTM[1721]="*Evamevaṃ kho tena, bhikkhave, bhikkhunā tesaṃyeva pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya adhimatto chando ca vāyāmo ca ussāho ca ussoḷhī ca appaṭivānī ca sati ca sampajaññañca karaṇīyaṃ.**In the same way, in order to give up those bad, unskillful qualities, that mendicant should apply outstanding enthusiasm …*";
P_HTM[1722]="*Sace pana, bhikkhave, bhikkhu paccavekkhamāno evaṃ jānāti:**But suppose that, upon checking, a mendicant knows this:*";
P_HTM[1723]="*‘anabhijjhālu bahulaṃ viharāmi, abyāpannacitto bahulaṃ viharāmi, vigatathinamiddho bahulaṃ viharāmi, anuddhato bahulaṃ viharāmi, tiṇṇavicikiccho bahulaṃ viharāmi, akkodhano bahulaṃ viharāmi, asaṅkiliṭṭhacitto bahulaṃ viharāmi, asāraddhakāyo bahulaṃ viharāmi, āraddhavīriyo bahulaṃ viharāmi, samāhito bahulaṃ viharāmī’ti, tena, bhikkhave, bhikkhunā tesuyeva kusalesu dhammesu patiṭṭhāya uttari āsavānaṃ khayāya yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**‘I am often content, kind-hearted, free of dullness and drowsiness, calm, confident, loving, pure in mind, undisturbed in body, energetic, and immersed in samādhi.’ Grounded on those skillful qualities, they should practice meditation further to end the defilements.”*";
P_HTM[1724]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1725]="*2. Sāriputtasuttaṃ**With Sāriputta*";
P_HTM[1726]="*Tatra kho āyasmā sāriputto bhikkhū āmantesi:**There Sāriputta addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1727]="*“āvuso bhikkhave”ti.**“Reverends, mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[1728]="*“Āvuso”ti kho te bhikkhū āyasmato sāriputtassa paccassosuṃ.**“Reverend,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[1729]="*Āyasmā sāriputto etadavoca:**Sāriputta said this:*";
P_HTM[1730]="*“No ce, āvuso, bhikkhu paracittapariyāyakusalo hoti, atha ‘sacittapariyāyakusalo bhavissāmī’ti—**“Mendicants, if a mendicant isn’t skilled in the ways of another’s mind, then they should train themselves: ‘I will be skilled in the ways of my own mind.’*";
P_HTM[1731]="*evañhi vo, āvuso, sikkhitabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1732]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu sacittapariyāyakusalo hoti?**And how is a mendicant skilled in the ways of their own mind?*";
P_HTM[1733]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso, itthī vā puriso vā daharo yuvā maṇḍanakajātiko ādāse vā parisuddhe pariyodāte acche vā udapatte sakaṃ mukhanimittaṃ paccavekkhamāno sace tattha passati rajaṃ vā aṅgaṇaṃ vā, tasseva rajassa vā aṅgaṇassa vā pahānāya vāyamati.**Suppose there was a woman or man who was young, youthful, and fond of adornments, and they check their own reflection in a clean bright mirror or a clear bowl of water. If they see any dirt or blemish there, they’d try to remove it.*";
P_HTM[1734]="*No ce tattha passati rajaṃ vā aṅgaṇaṃ vā, tenevattamano hoti paripuṇṇasaṅkappo:**But if they don’t see any dirt or blemish there, they’re happy with that, as they’ve got all they wished for:*";
P_HTM[1735]="*‘lābhā vata me, parisuddhaṃ vata me’ti.**‘How fortunate that I’m clean!’*";
P_HTM[1736]="*Evamevaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhuno paccavekkhaṇā bahukārā hoti kusalesu dhammesu:**In the same way, checking is very helpful for a mendicant’s skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[1737]="*‘abhijjhālu nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, anabhijjhālu nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, byāpannacitto nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, abyāpannacitto nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, thinamiddhapariyuṭṭhito nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, vigatathinamiddho nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, uddhato nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, anuddhato nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, vicikiccho nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, tiṇṇavicikiccho nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, kodhano nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, akkodhano nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, saṅkiliṭṭhacitto nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, asaṅkiliṭṭhacitto nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, sāraddhakāyo nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, asāraddhakāyo nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, kusīto nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, āraddhavīriyo nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, samāhito nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, asamāhito nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmī’ti.**‘Am I often covetous or not? Am I often malicious or not? Am I often overcome with dullness and drowsiness or not? Am I often restless or not? Am I often doubtful or not? Am I often irritable or not? Am I often defiled in mind or not? Am I often disturbed in body or not? Am I often energetic or not? Am I often immersed in samādhi or not?’*";
P_HTM[1738]="*Sace, āvuso, bhikkhu paccavekkhamāno evaṃ jānāti:**Suppose that, upon checking, a mendicant knows this:*";
P_HTM[1739]="*‘abhijjhālu bahulaṃ viharāmi … pe … asamāhito bahulaṃ viharāmī’ti, tenāvuso, bhikkhunā tesaṃyeva pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya adhimatto chando ca vāyāmo ca ussāho ca ussoḷhī ca appaṭivānī ca sati ca sampajaññañca karaṇīyaṃ.**‘I am often covetous, malicious, overcome with dullness and drowsiness, restless, doubtful, angry, defiled in mind, disturbed in body, lazy, and not immersed in samādhi.’ In order to give up those bad, unskillful qualities, they should apply outstanding enthusiasm, effort, zeal, vigor, perseverance, mindfulness, and situational awareness.*";
P_HTM[1740]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso, ādittacelo vā ādittasīso vā. Tasseva celassa vā sīsassa vā nibbāpanāya adhimattaṃ chandañca vāyāmañca ussāhañca ussoḷhiñca appaṭivāniñca satiñca sampajaññañca kareyya.**Suppose your clothes or head were on fire. In order to extinguish it, you’d apply outstanding enthusiasm, effort, zeal, vigor, perseverance, mindfulness, and situational awareness.*";
P_HTM[1741]="*Evamevaṃ kho, āvuso, tena bhikkhunā tesaṃyeva pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya adhimatto chando ca vāyāmo ca ussāho ca ussoḷhī ca appaṭivānī ca sati ca sampajaññañca karaṇīyaṃ.**In the same way, in order to give up those bad, unskillful qualities, that mendicant should apply outstanding enthusiasm …*";
P_HTM[1742]="*Sace panāvuso, bhikkhu paccavekkhamāno evaṃ jānāti:**But suppose that, upon checking, a mendicant knows this:*";
P_HTM[1743]="*‘anabhijjhālu bahulaṃ viharāmi … pe … samāhito bahulaṃ viharāmī’ti, tenāvuso, bhikkhunā tesuyeva kusalesu dhammesu patiṭṭhāya uttari āsavānaṃ khayāya yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**‘I am often content, kind-hearted, rid of dullness and drowsiness, calm, confident, loving, pure in mind, undisturbed in body, energetic, and immersed in samādhi.’ Grounded on those skillful qualities, they should practice meditation further to end the defilements.”*";
P_HTM[1744]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1745]="*3. Ṭhitisuttaṃ**Stagnation*";
P_HTM[1746]="*“Ṭhitimpāhaṃ, bhikkhave, na vaṇṇayāmi kusalesu dhammesu, pageva parihāniṃ.**“Mendicants, I don’t praise stagnation in skillful qualities, let alone decline.*";
P_HTM[1747]="*Vuḍḍhiñca kho ahaṃ, bhikkhave, vaṇṇayāmi kusalesu dhammesu, no ṭhitiṃ no hāniṃ.**I praise growth in skillful qualities, not stagnation or decline.*";
P_HTM[1748]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, hāni hoti kusalesu dhammesu, no ṭhiti no vuḍḍhi?**And how is there decline in skillful qualities, not stagnation or growth?*";
P_HTM[1749]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yattako hoti saddhāya sīlena sutena cāgena paññāya paṭibhānena, tassa te dhammā neva tiṭṭhanti no vaḍḍhanti.**It’s when a mendicant has a certain degree of faith, ethics, generosity, wisdom, and eloquence. Those qualities neither stagnate nor grow in them.*";
P_HTM[1750]="*Hānimetaṃ, bhikkhave, vadāmi kusalesu dhammesu, no ṭhitiṃ no vuḍḍhiṃ.**I call this decline in skillful qualities, not stagnation or growth.*";
P_HTM[1751]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, hāni hoti kusalesu dhammesu, no ṭhiti no vuḍḍhi.**This is how there’s decline in skillful qualities, not stagnation or growth.*";
P_HTM[1752]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave ṭhiti hoti kusalesu dhammesu, no hāni no vuḍḍhi?**And how is there stagnation in skillful qualities, not decline or growth?*";
P_HTM[1753]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yattako hoti saddhāya sīlena sutena cāgena paññāya paṭibhānena, tassa te dhammā neva hāyanti no vaḍḍhanti.**It’s when a mendicant has a certain degree of faith, ethics, generosity, wisdom, and eloquence. Those qualities neither decline nor grow in them.*";
P_HTM[1754]="*Ṭhitimetaṃ, bhikkhave, vadāmi kusalesu dhammesu, no hāniṃ no vuḍḍhiṃ.**I call this stagnation in skillful qualities, not decline or growth.*";
P_HTM[1755]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, ṭhiti hoti kusalesu dhammesu, no vuḍḍhi no hāni.**This is how there’s stagnation in skillful qualities, not decline or growth.*";
P_HTM[1756]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, vuḍḍhi hoti kusalesu dhammesu, no ṭhiti no hāni?**And how is there growth in skillful qualities, not stagnation or decline?*";
P_HTM[1757]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yattako hoti saddhāya sīlena sutena cāgena paññāya paṭibhānena, tassa te dhammā neva tiṭṭhanti no hāyanti.**It’s when a mendicant has a certain degree of faith, ethics, generosity, wisdom, and eloquence. Those qualities neither stagnate nor decline in them.*";
P_HTM[1758]="*Vuḍḍhimetaṃ, bhikkhave, vadāmi kusalesu dhammesu, no ṭhitiṃ no hāniṃ.**I call this growth in skillful qualities, not stagnation or decline.*";
P_HTM[1759]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, vuḍḍhi hoti kusalesu dhammesu, no ṭhiti no hāni.**This is how there’s growth in skillful qualities, not stagnation or decline.*";
P_HTM[1760]="*No ce, bhikkhave, bhikkhu paracittapariyāyakusalo hoti, atha ‘sacittapariyāyakusalo bhavissāmī’ti—**If a mendicant isn’t skilled in the ways of another’s mind, then they should train themselves: ‘I will be skilled in the ways of my own mind.’*";
P_HTM[1761]="*evañhi vo, bhikkhave, sikkhitabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1762]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sacittapariyāyakusalo hoti?**And how is a mendicant skilled in the ways of their own mind?*";
