P_HTM[1780]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, itthī vā puriso vā daharo yuvā maṇḍanakajātiko ādāse vā parisuddhe pariyodāte acche vā udapatte sakaṃ mukhanimittaṃ paccavekkhamāno sace tattha passati rajaṃ vā aṅgaṇaṃ vā, tasseva rajassa vā aṅgaṇassa vā pahānāya vāyamati.**Suppose there was a woman or man who was young, youthful, and fond of adornments, and they check their own reflection in a clean bright mirror or a clear bowl of water. If they see any dirt or blemish there, they’d try to remove it.*";
P_HTM[1781]="*No ce tattha passati rajaṃ vā aṅgaṇaṃ vā, tenevattamano hoti paripuṇṇasaṅkappo:**But if they don’t see any dirt or blemish there, they’re happy with that, as they’ve got all they wished for:*";
P_HTM[1782]="*‘lābhā vata me, parisuddhaṃ vata me’ti.**‘How fortunate that I’m clean!’*";
P_HTM[1783]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno paccavekkhaṇā bahukārā hoti kusalesu dhammesu:**In the same way, checking is very helpful for a mendicant’s skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[1784]="*‘lābhī nu khomhi ajjhattaṃ cetosamathassa, na nu khomhi lābhī ajjhattaṃ cetosamathassa, lābhī nu khomhi adhipaññādhammavipassanāya, na nu khomhi lābhī adhipaññādhammavipassanāyā’ti.**‘Do I have internal serenity of heart or not? Do I have the higher wisdom of discernment of principles or not?’*";
P_HTM[1785]="*Sace, bhikkhave, bhikkhu paccavekkhamāno evaṃ jānāti:**Suppose that, upon checking, a mendicant knows this:*";
P_HTM[1786]="*‘lābhīmhi ajjhattaṃ cetosamathassa, na lābhī adhipaññādhammavipassanāyā’ti, tena, bhikkhave, bhikkhunā ajjhattaṃ cetosamathe patiṭṭhāya adhipaññādhammavipassanāya yogo karaṇīyo.**‘I have serenity but not discernment.’ Grounded on serenity, they should practice meditation to get discernment.*";
P_HTM[1787]="*So aparena samayena lābhī ceva hoti ajjhattaṃ cetosamathassa lābhī ca adhipaññādhammavipassanāya.**After some time they have both serenity and discernment.*";
P_HTM[1788]="*Sace pana, bhikkhave, bhikkhu paccavekkhamāno evaṃ jānāti:**But suppose that, upon checking, a mendicant knows this:*";
P_HTM[1789]="*‘lābhīmhi adhipaññādhammavipassanāya, na lābhī ajjhattaṃ cetosamathassā’ti, tena, bhikkhave, bhikkhunā adhipaññādhammavipassanāya patiṭṭhāya ajjhattaṃ cetosamathe yogo karaṇīyo.**‘I have discernment but not serenity.’ Grounded on discernment, they should practice meditation to get serenity.*";
P_HTM[1790]="*So aparena samayena lābhī ceva hoti adhipaññādhammavipassanāya lābhī ca ajjhattaṃ cetosamathassa.**After some time they have both serenity and discernment.*";
P_HTM[1791]="*Sace pana, bhikkhave, bhikkhu paccavekkhamāno evaṃ jānāti:**But suppose that, upon checking, a mendicant knows this:*";
P_HTM[1792]="*‘na lābhī ajjhattaṃ cetosamathassa, na lābhī adhipaññādhammavipassanāyā’ti, tena, bhikkhave, bhikkhunā tesaṃyeva kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ paṭilābhāya adhimatto chando ca vāyāmo ca ussāho ca ussoḷhī ca appaṭivānī ca sati ca sampajaññañca karaṇīyaṃ.**‘I have neither serenity nor discernment.’ In order to get those skillful qualities, they should apply outstanding enthusiasm, effort, zeal, vigor, perseverance, mindfulness, and situational awareness.*";
P_HTM[1793]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ādittacelo vā ādittasīso vā.**Suppose your clothes or head were on fire. In order to extinguish it, you’d apply outstanding enthusiasm, effort, zeal, vigor, perseverance, mindfulness, and situational awareness.*";
P_HTM[1794]="*Tasseva celassa vā sīsassa vā nibbāpanāya adhimattaṃ chandañca vāyāmañca ussāhañca ussoḷhiñca appaṭivāniñca satiñca sampajaññañca kareyya.* **";
P_HTM[1795]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tena bhikkhunā tesaṃyeva kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ paṭilābhāya adhimatto chando ca vāyāmo ca ussāho ca ussoḷhī ca appaṭivānī ca sati ca sampajaññañca karaṇīyaṃ.**In the same way, in order to get those skillful qualities, that person should apply outstanding enthusiasm …*";
P_HTM[1796]="*So aparena samayena lābhī ceva hoti ajjhattaṃ cetosamathassa lābhī ca adhipaññādhammavipassanāya.**After some time they have both serenity and discernment.*";
P_HTM[1797]="*Sace pana, bhikkhave, bhikkhu paccavekkhamāno evaṃ jānāti:**But suppose that, upon checking, a mendicant knows this:*";
P_HTM[1798]="*‘lābhīmhi ajjhattaṃ cetosamathassa, lābhī adhipaññādhammavipassanāyā’ti, tena, bhikkhave, bhikkhunā tesuyeva kusalesu dhammesu patiṭṭhāya uttari āsavānaṃ khayāya yogo karaṇīyo.**‘I have both serenity and discernment.’ Grounded on those skillful qualities, they should practice meditation further to end the defilements.*";
P_HTM[1799]="*Cīvarampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**I say that there are two kinds of robes:*";
P_HTM[1800]="*sevitabbampi asevitabbampi.**those you should wear, and those you shouldn’t wear.*";
P_HTM[1801]="*Piṇḍapātampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**I say that there are two kinds of almsfood:*";
P_HTM[1802]="*sevitabbampi asevitabbampi.**that which you should eat, and that which you shouldn’t eat.*";
P_HTM[1803]="*Senāsanampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**I say that there are two kinds of lodging:*";
P_HTM[1804]="*sevitabbampi asevitabbampi.**those you should frequent, and those you shouldn’t frequent.*";
P_HTM[1805]="*Gāmanigamampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**I say that there are two kinds of market town:*";
P_HTM[1806]="*sevitabbampi asevitabbampi.**those you should frequent, and those you shouldn’t frequent.*";
P_HTM[1807]="*Janapadapadesampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**I say that there are two kinds of country:*";
P_HTM[1808]="*sevitabbampi asevitabbampi.**those you should frequent, and those you shouldn’t frequent.*";
P_HTM[1809]="*Puggalampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**I say that there are two kinds of people:*";
P_HTM[1810]="*sevitabbampi asevitabbampi.**those you should frequent, and those you shouldn’t frequent.*";
P_HTM[1811]="*‘Cīvarampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of robes:*";
P_HTM[1812]="*sevitabbampi asevitabbampī’ti,**those you should wear, and those you shouldn’t wear.’*";
P_HTM[1813]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[1814]="*Tattha yaṃ jaññā cīvaraṃ:**Take a robe of which you know this:*";
P_HTM[1815]="*‘idaṃ kho me cīvaraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyantī’ti, evarūpaṃ cīvaraṃ na sevitabbaṃ.**‘When I wear this robe, unskillful qualities grow, and skillful qualities decline.’ You should not wear that kind of robe.*";
P_HTM[1816]="*Tattha yaṃ jaññā cīvaraṃ:**Take a robe of which you know this:*";
P_HTM[1817]="*‘idaṃ kho me cīvaraṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhantī’ti, evarūpaṃ cīvaraṃ sevitabbaṃ.**‘When I wear this robe, unskillful qualities decline, and skillful qualities grow.’ You should wear that kind of robe.*";
P_HTM[1818]="*‘Cīvarampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of robes:*";
P_HTM[1819]="*sevitabbampi asevitabbampī’ti,**those you should wear, and those you shouldn’t wear.’*";
P_HTM[1820]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ, idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[1821]="*‘Piṇḍapātampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of almsfood:*";
P_HTM[1822]="*sevitabbampi asevitabbampī’ti,**that which you should eat, and that which you shouldn’t eat.’*";
P_HTM[1823]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[1824]="*Tattha yaṃ jaññā piṇḍapātaṃ:**Take almsfood of which you know this:*";
P_HTM[1825]="*‘imaṃ kho me piṇḍapātaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyantī’ti, evarūpo piṇḍapāto na sevitabbo.**‘When I eat this almsfood, unskillful qualities grow, and skillful qualities decline.’ You should not eat that kind of almsfood.*";
P_HTM[1826]="*Tattha yaṃ jaññā piṇḍapātaṃ:**Take almsfood of which you know this:*";
P_HTM[1827]="*‘imaṃ kho me piṇḍapātaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhantī’ti, evarūpo piṇḍapāto sevitabbo.**‘When I eat this almsfood, unskillful qualities decline, and skillful qualities grow.’ You should eat that kind of almsfood.*";
P_HTM[1828]="*‘Piṇḍapātampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of almsfood:*";
P_HTM[1829]="*sevitabbampi asevitabbampī’ti,**that which you should eat, and that which you shouldn’t eat.’*";
P_HTM[1830]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ, idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[1831]="*‘Senāsanampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of lodging:*";
P_HTM[1832]="*sevitabbampi asevitabbampī’ti,**those you should frequent, and those you shouldn’t frequent.’*";
P_HTM[1833]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[1834]="*Tattha yaṃ jaññā senāsanaṃ:**Take a lodging of which you know this:*";
P_HTM[1835]="*‘idaṃ kho me senāsanaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyantī’ti, evarūpaṃ senāsanaṃ na sevitabbaṃ.**‘When I frequent this lodging, unskillful qualities grow, and skillful qualities decline.’ You should not frequent that kind of lodging.*";
P_HTM[1836]="*Tattha yaṃ jaññā senāsanaṃ:**Take a lodging of which you know this:*";
P_HTM[1837]="*‘idaṃ kho me senāsanaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhantī’ti, evarūpaṃ senāsanaṃ sevitabbaṃ.**‘When I frequent this lodging, unskillful qualities decline, and skillful qualities grow.’ You should frequent that kind of lodging.*";
P_HTM[1838]="*‘Senāsanampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of lodging:*";
P_HTM[1839]="*sevitabbampi asevitabbampī’ti,**those you should frequent, and those you shouldn’t frequent.’*";
P_HTM[1840]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ, idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[1841]="*‘Gāmanigamampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of market town:*";
P_HTM[1842]="*sevitabbampi asevitabbampī’ti,**those you should frequent, and those you shouldn’t frequent.’*";
P_HTM[1843]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[1844]="*Tattha yaṃ jaññā gāmanigamaṃ:**Take a market town of which you know this:*";
P_HTM[1845]="*‘imaṃ kho me gāmanigamaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyantī’ti, evarūpo gāmanigamo na sevitabbo.**‘When I frequent this market town, unskillful qualities grow, and skillful qualities decline.’ You should not frequent that kind of market town.*";
P_HTM[1846]="*Tattha yaṃ jaññā gāmanigamaṃ:**Take a market town of which you know this:*";
P_HTM[1847]="*‘imaṃ kho me gāmanigamaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhantī’ti, evarūpo gāmanigamo sevitabbo.**‘When I frequent this market town, unskillful qualities decline, and skillful qualities grow.’ You should frequent that kind of market town.*";
P_HTM[1848]="*‘Gāmanigamampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of market town:*";
P_HTM[1849]="*sevitabbampi asevitabbampī’ti,**those you should frequent, and those you shouldn’t frequent.’*";
P_HTM[1850]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ, idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[1851]="*‘Janapadapadesampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of country:*";
P_HTM[1852]="*sevitabbampi asevitabbampī’ti,**those you should frequent, and those you shouldn’t frequent.’*";
P_HTM[1853]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[1854]="*Tattha yaṃ jaññā janapadapadesaṃ:**Take a country of which you know this:*";
P_HTM[1855]="*‘imaṃ kho me janapadapadesaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyantī’ti, evarūpo janapadapadeso na sevitabbo.**‘When I frequent this country, unskillful qualities grow, and skillful qualities decline.’ You should not frequent that kind of country.*";
P_HTM[1856]="*Tattha yaṃ jaññā janapadapadesaṃ:**Take a country of which you know this:*";
P_HTM[1857]="*‘imaṃ kho me janapadapadesaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhantī’ti, evarūpo janapadapadeso sevitabbo.**‘When I frequent this country, unskillful qualities decline, and skillful qualities grow.’ You should frequent that kind of country.*";
P_HTM[1858]="*‘Janapadapadesampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of country:*";
P_HTM[1859]="*sevitabbampi asevitabbampī’ti,**those you should frequent, and those you shouldn’t frequent.’*";
P_HTM[1860]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ, idametaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.*";
P_HTM[1861]="*‘Puggalampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of people:*";
P_HTM[1862]="*sevitabbampi asevitabbampī’ti,**those you should frequent, and those you shouldn’t frequent.’*";
P_HTM[1863]="*iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ?**That’s what I said, but why did I say it?*";
P_HTM[1864]="*Tattha yaṃ jaññā puggalaṃ:**Take a person of whom you know this:*";
P_HTM[1865]="*‘imaṃ kho me puggalaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhanti, kusalā dhammā parihāyantī’ti, evarūpo puggalo na sevitabbo.**‘When I frequent this person, unskillful qualities grow, and skillful qualities decline.’ You should not frequent that kind of person.*";
P_HTM[1866]="*Tattha yaṃ jaññā puggalaṃ:**Take a person of whom you know this:*";
P_HTM[1867]="*‘imaṃ kho me puggalaṃ sevato akusalā dhammā parihāyanti, kusalā dhammā abhivaḍḍhantī’ti, evarūpo puggalo sevitabbo.**‘When I frequent this person, unskillful qualities decline, and skillful qualities grow.’ You should frequent that kind of person.*";
P_HTM[1868]="*‘Puggalampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duvidhena vadāmi—**‘I say that there are two kinds of people:*";
P_HTM[1869]="*sevitabbampi asevitabbampī’ti,**those you should frequent, and those you shouldn’t frequent.’*";
P_HTM[1870]="*iti yaṃ taṃ vuttaṃ, idametaṃ paṭicca vuttan”ti.**That’s what I said, and this is why I said it.”*";
P_HTM[1871]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1872]="*5. Parihānasuttaṃ**Decline*";
P_HTM[1873]="*Tatra kho āyasmā sāriputto bhikkhū āmantesi:**There Sāriputta addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1874]="*“āvuso bhikkhave”ti.**“Reverends, mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[1875]="*“Āvuso”ti kho te bhikkhū āyasmato sāriputtassa paccassosuṃ.**“Reverend,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[1876]="*Āyasmā sāriputto etadavoca:**Sāriputta said this:*";
P_HTM[1877]="*“‘Parihānadhammo puggalo, parihānadhammo puggalo’ti, āvuso, vuccati.**“Reverends, they speak of a person liable to decline,*";
P_HTM[1878]="*‘Aparihānadhammo puggalo, aparihānadhammo puggalo’ti, āvuso, vuccati.**and one not liable to decline.*";
P_HTM[1879]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, āvuso, parihānadhammo puggalo vutto bhagavatā, kittāvatā ca pana aparihānadhammo puggalo vutto bhagavatā”ti?**But how did the Buddha define a person liable to decline, and one not liable to decline?”*";
P_HTM[1880]="*“Dūratopi kho mayaṃ, āvuso, āgacchāma āyasmato sāriputtassa santike etassa bhāsitassa atthamaññātuṃ.**“Reverend, we would travel a long way to learn the meaning of this statement in the presence of Venerable Sāriputta.*";
P_HTM[1881]="*Sādhu vatāyasmantaṃyeva sāriputtaṃ paṭibhātu etassa bhāsitassa attho.**May Venerable Sāriputta himself please clarify the meaning of this.*";
P_HTM[1882]="*Āyasmato sāriputtassa sutvā bhikkhū dhāressantī”ti.**The mendicants will listen and remember it.”*";
P_HTM[1883]="*“Tenahāvuso, suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Then listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[1884]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho te bhikkhū āyasmato sāriputtassa paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, reverend,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[1885]="*Āyasmā sāriputto etadavoca:**Sāriputta said this:*";
P_HTM[1886]="*“Kittāvatā nu kho, āvuso, parihānadhammo puggalo vutto bhagavatā?**“How did the Buddha define a person liable to decline?*";
P_HTM[1887]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu assutañceva dhammaṃ na suṇāti, sutā cassa dhammā sammosaṃ gacchanti, ye cassa dhammā pubbe cetaso asamphuṭṭhapubbā te cassa na samudācaranti, aviññātañceva na vijānāti.**It’s when a mendicant doesn’t get to hear a teaching they haven’t heard before. They forget those teachings they have heard. They don’t keep rehearsing the teachings they’ve already got to know. And they don’t come to understand what they haven’t understood before.*";
P_HTM[1888]="*Ettāvatā kho, āvuso, parihānadhammo puggalo vutto bhagavatā.**That’s how the Buddha defined a person liable to decline.*";
P_HTM[1889]="*Kittāvatā ca panāvuso, aparihānadhammo puggalo vutto bhagavatā?**And how did the Buddha define a person not liable to decline?*";
P_HTM[1890]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu assutañceva dhammaṃ suṇāti, sutā cassa dhammā na sammosaṃ gacchanti, ye cassa dhammā pubbe cetaso asamphuṭṭhapubbā te cassa samudācaranti, aviññātañceva vijānāti.**It’s when a mendicant gets to hear a teaching they haven’t heard before. They remember those teachings they have heard. They keep rehearsing the teachings they’ve already got to know. And they come to understand what they haven’t understood before.*";
P_HTM[1891]="*Ettāvatā kho, āvuso, aparihānadhammo puggalo vutto bhagavatā.**That’s how the Buddha defined a person not liable to decline.*";
P_HTM[1892]="*No ce, āvuso, bhikkhu paracittapariyāyakusalo hoti, atha ‘sacittapariyāyakusalo bhavissāmī’ti—**If a mendicant isn’t skilled in the ways of another’s mind, then they should train themselves: ‘I will be skilled in the ways of my own mind.’*";
P_HTM[1893]="*evañhi vo, āvuso, sikkhitabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1894]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu sacittapariyāyakusalo hoti?**And how is a mendicant skilled in the ways of their own mind?*";
P_HTM[1895]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso, itthī vā puriso vā daharo yuvā maṇḍanakajātiko ādāse vā parisuddhe pariyodāte acche vā udapatte sakaṃ mukhanimittaṃ paccavekkhamāno sace tattha passati rajaṃ vā aṅgaṇaṃ vā, tasseva rajassa vā aṅgaṇassa vā pahānāya vāyamati.**Suppose there was a woman or man who was young, youthful, and fond of adornments, and they check their own reflection in a clean bright mirror or a clear bowl of water. If they see any dirt or blemish there, they’d try to remove it.*";
P_HTM[1896]="*No ce tattha passati rajaṃ vā aṅgaṇaṃ vā, tenevattamano hoti paripuṇṇasaṅkappo:**But if they don’t see any dirt or blemish there, they’re happy with that, as they’ve got all they wished for:*";
P_HTM[1897]="*‘lābhā vata me, parisuddhaṃ vata me’ti.**‘How fortunate that I’m clean!’*";
P_HTM[1898]="*Evameva kho, āvuso, bhikkhuno paccavekkhaṇā bahukārā hoti kusalesu dhammesu:**In the same way, checking is very helpful for a mendicant’s skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[1899]="*‘anabhijjhālu nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, saṃvijjati nu kho me eso dhammo udāhu no, abyāpannacitto nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, saṃvijjati nu kho me eso dhammo udāhu no, vigatathinamiddho nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, saṃvijjati nu kho me eso dhammo udāhu no, anuddhato nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, saṃvijjati nu kho me eso dhammo udāhu no, tiṇṇavicikiccho nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, saṃvijjati nu kho me eso dhammo udāhu no, akkodhano nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, saṃvijjati nu kho me eso dhammo udāhu no, asaṅkiliṭṭhacitto nu kho bahulaṃ viharāmi, saṃvijjati nu kho me eso dhammo udāhu no, lābhī nu khomhi ajjhattaṃ dhammapāmojjassa, saṃvijjati nu kho me eso dhammo udāhu no, lābhī nu khomhi ajjhattaṃ cetosamathassa, saṃvijjati nu kho me eso dhammo udāhu no, lābhī nu khomhi adhipaññādhammavipassanāya, saṃvijjati nu kho me eso dhammo udāhu no’ti.**‘Is contentment often found in me or not? Is kind-heartedness often found in me or not? Is freedom from dullness and drowsiness often found in me or not? Is calm often found in me or not? Is confidence often found in me or not? Is love often found in me or not? Is purity of mind often found in me or not? Is internal joy with the teaching found in me or not? Is internal serenity of heart found in me or not? Is the higher wisdom of discernment of principles found in me or not?’*";
P_HTM[1900]="*Sace pana, āvuso, bhikkhu paccavekkhamāno sabbepime kusale dhamme attani na samanupassati, tenāvuso, bhikkhunā sabbesaṃyeva imesaṃ kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ paṭilābhāya adhimatto chando ca vāyāmo ca ussāho ca ussoḷhī ca appaṭivānī ca sati ca sampajaññañca karaṇīyaṃ.**Suppose a mendicant, while checking, doesn’t see any of these skillful qualities in themselves. In order to get them they should apply outstanding enthusiasm, effort, zeal, vigor, perseverance, mindfulness, and situational awareness.*";
P_HTM[1901]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso, ādittacelo vā ādittasīso vā.**Suppose your clothes or head were on fire. In order to extinguish it, you’d apply outstanding enthusiasm, effort, zeal, vigor, perseverance, mindfulness, and situational awareness.*";
P_HTM[1902]="*Tasseva celassa vā sīsassa vā nibbāpanāya adhimattaṃ chandañca vāyāmañca ussāhañca ussoḷhiñca appaṭivāniñca satiñca sampajaññañca kareyya.* **";
P_HTM[1903]="*Evamevaṃ kho, āvuso, tena bhikkhunā sabbesaṃyeva kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ paṭilābhāya adhimatto chando ca vāyāmo ca ussāho ca ussoḷhī ca appaṭivānī ca sati ca sampajaññañca karaṇīyaṃ.**In the same way, they should apply outstanding enthusiasm to get those skillful qualities …*";
P_HTM[1904]="*Sace panāvuso, bhikkhu paccavekkhamāno ekacce kusale dhamme attani samanupassati, ekacce kusale dhamme attani na samanupassati, tenāvuso, bhikkhunā ye kusale dhamme attani samanupassati tesu kusalesu dhammesu patiṭṭhāya, ye kusale dhamme attani na samanupassati tesaṃ kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ paṭilābhāya adhimatto chando ca vāyāmo ca ussāho ca ussoḷhī ca appaṭivānī ca sati ca sampajaññañca karaṇīyaṃ.**Suppose a mendicant, while checking, sees some of these skillful qualities in themselves, but doesn’t see others. Grounded on the skillful qualities they see, they should apply outstanding enthusiasm, effort, zeal, vigor, perseverance, mindfulness, and situational awareness in order to get the skillful qualities they don’t see.*";
P_HTM[1905]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso, ādittacelo vā ādittasīso vā.**Suppose your clothes or head were on fire. In order to extinguish it, you’d apply outstanding enthusiasm, effort, zeal, vigor, perseverance, mindfulness, and situational awareness.*";
P_HTM[1906]="*Tasseva celassa vā sīsassa vā nibbāpanāya adhimattaṃ chandañca vāyāmañca ussāhañca ussoḷhiñca appaṭivāniñca satiñca sampajaññañca kareyya.* **";
P_HTM[1907]="*Evamevaṃ kho, āvuso, tena bhikkhunā ye kusale dhamme attani samanupassati tesu kusalesu dhammesu patiṭṭhāya, ye kusale dhamme attani na samanupassati tesaṃ kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ paṭilābhāya adhimatto chando ca vāyāmo ca ussāho ca ussoḷhī ca appaṭivānī ca sati ca sampajaññañca karaṇīyaṃ.**In the same way, grounded on the skillful qualities they see, they should apply outstanding enthusiasm to get those skillful qualities they don’t see.*";
P_HTM[1908]="*Sace panāvuso, bhikkhu paccavekkhamāno sabbepime kusale dhamme attani samanupassati, tenāvuso, bhikkhunā sabbesveva imesu kusalesu dhammesu patiṭṭhāya uttari āsavānaṃ khayāya yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**But suppose a mendicant, while checking, sees all of these skillful qualities in themselves. Grounded on all these skillful qualities they should practice meditation further to end the defilements.”*";
P_HTM[1909]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1910]="*6. Paṭhamasaññāsuttaṃ**Perceptions (1st)*";
P_HTM[1911]="*“Dasayimā, bhikkhave, saññā bhāvitā bahulīkatā mahapphalā honti mahānisaṃsā amatogadhā amatapariyosānā.**“Mendicants, these ten perceptions, when developed and cultivated, are very fruitful and beneficial. They culminate in the deathless and end with the deathless.*";
P_HTM[1912]="*Katamā dasa?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[1913]="*Asubhasaññā, maraṇasaññā, āhāre paṭikūlasaññā, sabbaloke anabhiratasaññā, aniccasaññā, anicce dukkhasaññā, dukkhe anattasaññā, pahānasaññā, virāgasaññā, nirodhasaññā—**The perceptions of ugliness, death, repulsiveness of food, dissatisfaction with the whole world, impermanence, suffering in impermanence, and not-self in suffering, giving up, fading away, and cessation.*";
P_HTM[1914]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, dasa saññā bhāvitā bahulīkatā mahapphalā honti mahānisaṃsā amatogadhā amatapariyosānā”ti.**These ten perceptions, when developed and cultivated, are very fruitful and beneficial. They culminate in the deathless and end with the deathless.”*";
P_HTM[1915]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1916]="*7. Dutiyasaññāsuttaṃ**Perceptions (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1917]="*“Dasayimā, bhikkhave, saññā bhāvitā bahulīkatā mahapphalā honti mahānisaṃsā amatogadhā amatapariyosānā.**“Mendicants, these ten perceptions, when developed and cultivated, are very fruitful and beneficial. They culminate in the deathless and end with the deathless.*";
P_HTM[1918]="*Katamā dasa?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[1919]="*Aniccasaññā, anattasaññā, maraṇasaññā, āhāre paṭikūlasaññā, sabbaloke anabhiratasaññā, aṭṭhikasaññā, puḷavakasaññā, vinīlakasaññā, vicchiddakasaññā, uddhumātakasaññā—**The perceptions of impermanence, not-self, death, repulsiveness of food, dissatisfaction with the whole world, a skeleton, a worm-infested corpse, a livid corpse, a split open corpse, and a bloated corpse.*";
P_HTM[1920]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, dasa saññā bhāvitā bahulīkatā mahapphalā honti mahānisaṃsā amatogadhā amatapariyosānā”ti.**These ten perceptions, when developed and cultivated, are very fruitful and beneficial. They culminate in the deathless and end with the deathless.”*";
P_HTM[1921]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1922]="*8. Mūlakasuttaṃ**Rooted*";
P_HTM[1923]="*“Sace, bhikkhave, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:**“Mendicants, if wanderers who follow other paths were to ask:*";
P_HTM[1924]="*‘kiṃmūlakā, āvuso, sabbe dhammā, kiṃsambhavā sabbe dhammā, kiṃsamudayā sabbe dhammā, kiṃsamosaraṇā sabbe dhammā, kiṃpamukhā sabbe dhammā, kiṃadhipateyyā sabbe dhammā, kiṃuttarā sabbe dhammā, kiṃsārā sabbe dhammā, kiṃogadhā sabbe dhammā, kiṃpariyosānā sabbe dhammā’ti, evaṃ puṭṭhā tumhe, bhikkhave, tesaṃ aññatitthiyānaṃ paribbājakānaṃ kinti byākareyyāthā”ti?**‘Reverends, all things have what as their root? What produces them? What is their origin? What is their meeting place? What is their chief? What is their ruler? What is their overseer? What is their core? What is their culmination? What is their final end?’ How would you answer them?”*";
P_HTM[1925]="*“Bhagavaṃmūlakā no, bhante, dhammā bhagavaṃnettikā bhagavaṃpaṭisaraṇā. Sādhu vata, bhante, bhagavantaṃyeva paṭibhātu etassa bhāsitassa attho. Bhagavato sutvā bhikkhū dhāressantī”ti.**“Our teachings are rooted in the Buddha. He is our guide and our refuge. Sir, may the Buddha himself please clarify the meaning of this. The mendicants will listen and remember it.”*";
P_HTM[1926]="*“Tena hi, bhikkhave, suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, mendicants, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[1927]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[1928]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[1929]="*“Sace, bhikkhave, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:**“Mendicants, if wanderers who follow other paths were to ask:*";
P_HTM[1930]="*‘kiṃmūlakā, āvuso, sabbe dhammā, kiṃsambhavā sabbe dhammā, kiṃsamudayā sabbe dhammā, kiṃsamosaraṇā sabbe dhammā, kiṃpamukhā sabbe dhammā, kiṃ adhipateyyā sabbe dhammā, kiṃuttarā sabbe dhammā, kiṃsārā sabbe dhammā, kiṃogadhā sabbe dhammā, kiṃpariyosānā sabbe dhammā’ti,**‘Reverends, all things have what as their root? What produces them? What is their origin? What is their meeting place? What is their chief? What is their ruler? What is their overseer? What is their core? What is their culmination? What is their final end?’*";
P_HTM[1931]="*evaṃ puṭṭhā tumhe, bhikkhave, tesaṃ aññatitthiyānaṃ paribbājakānaṃ evaṃ byākareyyātha:**You should answer them:*";
P_HTM[1932]="*‘chandamūlakā, āvuso, sabbe dhammā, manasikārasambhavā sabbe dhammā, phassasamudayā sabbe dhammā, vedanāsamosaraṇā sabbe dhammā, samādhippamukhā sabbe dhammā, satādhipateyyā sabbe dhammā, paññuttarā sabbe dhammā, vimuttisārā sabbe dhammā, amatogadhā sabbe dhammā, nibbānapariyosānā sabbe dhammā’ti.**‘Reverends, all things are rooted in desire. Attention produces them. Contact is their origin. Feeling is their meeting place. Immersion is their chief. Mindfulness is their ruler. Wisdom is their overseer. Freedom is their core. They culminate in the deathless. And extinguishment is their final end.’*";
P_HTM[1933]="*Evaṃ puṭṭhā tumhe, bhikkhave, tesaṃ aññatitthiyānaṃ paribbājakānaṃ evaṃ byākareyyāthā”ti.**When questioned by wanderers who follow other paths, that’s how you should answer them.”*";
P_HTM[1934]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1935]="*9. Pabbajjāsuttaṃ**Going Forth*";
P_HTM[1936]="*“Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**“So you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[1937]="*‘yathāpabbajjāparicitañca no cittaṃ bhavissati, na cuppannā pāpakā akusalā dhammā cittaṃ pariyādāya ṭhassanti;**‘Our minds will be consolidated as they were when we went forth, and arisen bad unskillful qualities will not occupy our minds.*";
P_HTM[1938]="*aniccasaññāparicitañca no cittaṃ bhavissati, anattasaññāparicitañca no cittaṃ bhavissati, asubhasaññāparicitañca no cittaṃ bhavissati, ādīnavasaññāparicitañca no cittaṃ bhavissati, lokassa samañca visamañca ñatvā taṃsaññāparicitañca no cittaṃ bhavissati, lokassa bhavañca vibhavañca ñatvā taṃsaññāparicitañca no cittaṃ bhavissati, lokassa samudayañca atthaṅgamañca ñatvā taṃsaññāparicitañca no cittaṃ bhavissati, pahānasaññāparicitañca no cittaṃ bhavissati, virāgasaññāparicitañca no cittaṃ bhavissati, nirodhasaññāparicitañca no cittaṃ bhavissatī’ti—**Our minds will be consolidated in the perceptions of impermanence, not-self, ugliness, and drawbacks. Knowing what is just and unjust in the world, our minds will be consolidated in that perception. Knowing about continued existence and ending of existence in the world, our minds will be consolidated in that perception. Knowing the origination and ending of the world, our minds will be consolidated in that perception. Our minds will be consolidated in the perceptions of giving up, fading away, and cessation.’*";
P_HTM[1939]="*evañhi vo, bhikkhave, sikkhitabbaṃ.**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[1940]="*Yato kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno yathāpabbajjāparicitañca cittaṃ hoti na cuppannā pāpakā akusalā dhammā cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhanti, aniccasaññāparicitañca cittaṃ hoti, anattasaññāparicitañca cittaṃ hoti, asubhasaññāparicitañca cittaṃ hoti, ādīnavasaññāparicitañca cittaṃ hoti, lokassa samañca visamañca ñatvā taṃsaññāparicitañca cittaṃ hoti, lokassa bhavañca vibhavañca ñatvā taṃsaññāparicitañca cittaṃ hoti, lokassa samudayañca atthaṅgamañca ñatvā taṃsaññāparicitañca cittaṃ hoti, pahānasaññāparicitañca cittaṃ hoti, virāgasaññāparicitañca cittaṃ hoti, nirodhasaññāparicitañca cittaṃ hoti, tassa dvinnaṃ phalānaṃ aññataraṃ phalaṃ pāṭikaṅkhaṃ—**When your minds are consolidated in these ten perceptions, you can expect one of two results:*";
P_HTM[1941]="*diṭṭheva dhamme aññā, sati vā upādisese anāgāmitā”ti.**enlightenment in the present life, or if there’s something left over, non-return.”*";
P_HTM[1942]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1943]="*10. Girimānandasuttaṃ**With Girimānanda*";
P_HTM[1944]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[1945]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā girimānando ābādhiko hoti dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**Now at that time Venerable Girimānanda was sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[1946]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Ānanda went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1947]="*“Āyasmā, bhante, girimānando ābādhiko hoti dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**“Sir, Venerable Girimānanda is sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[1948]="*Sādhu, bhante, bhagavā yenāyasmā girimānando tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā”ti.**Sir, please go to Venerable Girimānanda out of compassion.”*";
P_HTM[1949]="*“Sace kho tvaṃ, ānanda, girimānandassa bhikkhuno dasa saññā bhāseyyāsi, ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ vijjati yaṃ girimānandassa bhikkhuno dasa saññā sutvā so ābādho ṭhānaso paṭippassambheyya.**“Ānanda, if you were to recite to the mendicant Girimānanda these ten perceptions, it’s possible that after hearing them his illness will die down on the spot.*";
P_HTM[1950]="*Katamā dasa?**What ten?*";
P_HTM[1951]="*Aniccasaññā, anattasaññā, asubhasaññā, ādīnavasaññā, pahānasaññā, virāgasaññā, nirodhasaññā, sabbaloke anabhiratasaññā, sabbasaṅkhāresu anicchāsaññā, ānāpānassati.**The perceptions of impermanence, not-self, ugliness, drawbacks, giving up, fading away, cessation, dissatisfaction with the whole world, non-desire for all conditions, and mindfulness of breathing.*";
P_HTM[1952]="*Katamā cānanda, aniccasaññā?**And what is the perception of impermanence?*";
P_HTM[1953]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu araññagato vā rukkhamūlagato vā suññāgāragato vā iti paṭisañcikkhati:**It’s when a mendicant has gone to a wilderness, or to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, and reflects like this:*";
P_HTM[1954]="*‘rūpaṃ aniccaṃ, vedanā aniccā, saññā aniccā, saṅkhārā aniccā, viññāṇaṃ aniccan’ti.**‘Form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness are impermanent.’*";
P_HTM[1955]="*Iti imesu pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu aniccānupassī viharati.**And so they meditate observing impermanence in the five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[1956]="*Ayaṃ vuccatānanda, aniccasaññā. (1)**This is called the perception of impermanence.*";
P_HTM[1957]="*Katamā cānanda, anattasaññā?**And what is the perception of not-self?*";
P_HTM[1958]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu araññagato vā rukkhamūlagato vā suññāgāragato vā iti paṭisañcikkhati:**It’s when a mendicant has gone to a wilderness, or to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, and reflects like this:*";
P_HTM[1959]="*‘cakkhu anattā, rūpā anattā, sotaṃ anattā, saddā anattā, ghānaṃ anattā, gandhā anattā, jivhā anattā, rasā anattā, kāyā anattā, phoṭṭhabbā anattā, mano anattā, dhammā anattā’ti.**‘The eye and sights, ear and sounds, nose and smells, tongue and tastes, body and touches, and mind and thoughts are not-self.’*";
P_HTM[1960]="*Iti imesu chasu ajjhattikabāhiresu āyatanesu anattānupassī viharati.**And so they meditate observing not-self in the six interior and exterior sense fields.*";
P_HTM[1961]="*Ayaṃ vuccatānanda, anattasaññā. (2)**This is called the perception of not-self.*";
P_HTM[1962]="*Katamā cānanda, asubhasaññā?**And what is the perception of ugliness?*";
P_HTM[1963]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu imameva kāyaṃ uddhaṃ pādatalā adho kesamatthakā tacapariyantaṃ pūraṃ nānāppakārassa asucino paccavekkhati:**It’s when a mendicant examines their own body up from the soles of the feet and down from the tips of the hairs, wrapped in skin and full of many kinds of filth.*";
P_HTM[1964]="*‘atthi imasmiṃ kāye kesā lomā nakhā dantā taco, maṃsaṃ nhāru aṭṭhi aṭṭhimiñjaṃ vakkaṃ, hadayaṃ yakanaṃ kilomakaṃ pihakaṃ papphāsaṃ, antaṃ antaguṇaṃ udariyaṃ karīsaṃ, pittaṃ semhaṃ pubbo lohitaṃ sedo medo, assu vasā kheḷo siṅghāṇikā lasikā muttan’ti.**‘In this body there is head hair, body hair, nails, teeth, skin, flesh, sinews, bones, bone marrow, kidneys, heart, liver, diaphragm, spleen, lungs, intestines, mesentery, undigested food, feces, bile, phlegm, pus, blood, sweat, fat, tears, grease, saliva, snot, synovial fluid, urine.’*";
P_HTM[1965]="*Iti imasmiṃ kāye asubhānupassī viharati.**And so they meditate observing ugliness in this body.*";
P_HTM[1966]="*Ayaṃ vuccatānanda, asubhasaññā. (3)**This is called the perception of ugliness.*";
P_HTM[1967]="*Katamā cānanda, ādīnavasaññā?**And what is the perception of drawbacks?*";
P_HTM[1968]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu araññagato vā rukkhamūlagato vā suññāgāragato vā iti paṭisañcikkhati:**It’s when a mendicant has gone to a wilderness, or to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, and reflects like this:*";
P_HTM[1969]="*‘bahudukkho kho ayaṃ kāyo bahuādīnavo. Iti imasmiṃ kāye vividhā ābādhā uppajjanti, seyyathidaṃ—**‘This body has much suffering and many drawbacks. For this body is beset with many kinds of affliction, such as the following.*";
P_HTM[1970]="*cakkhurogo sotarogo ghānarogo jivhārogo kāyarogo sīsarogo kaṇṇarogo mukharogo dantarogo oṭṭharogo kāso sāso pināso ḍāho jaro kucchirogo mucchā pakkhandikā sūlā visūcikā kuṭṭhaṃ gaṇḍo kilāso soso apamāro daddu kaṇḍu kacchu nakhasā vitacchikā lohitaṃ pittaṃ madhumeho aṃsā piḷakā bhagandalā pittasamuṭṭhānā ābādhā semhasamuṭṭhānā ābādhā vātasamuṭṭhānā ābādhā sannipātikā ābādhā utupariṇāmajā ābādhā visamaparihārajā ābādhā opakkamikā ābādhā kammavipākajā ābādhā sītaṃ uṇhaṃ jighacchā pipāsā uccāro passāvo’ti.**Diseases of the eye, inner ear, nose, tongue, body, head, outer ear, mouth, teeth, and lips. Cough, asthma, catarrh, inflammation, fever, stomach ache, fainting, dysentery, gastric pain, cholera, leprosy, boils, eczema, tuberculosis, epilepsy, herpes, itch, scabs, smallpox, scabies, hemorrhage, diabetes, piles, pimples, and ulcers. Afflictions stemming from disorders of bile, phlegm, wind, or their conjunction. Afflictions caused by change in weather, by not taking care of yourself, by overexertion, or as the result of past deeds. Cold, heat, hunger, thirst, defecation, and urination.’*";
P_HTM[1971]="*Iti imasmiṃ kāye ādīnavānupassī viharati.**And so they meditate observing drawbacks in this body.*";
P_HTM[1972]="*Ayaṃ vuccatānanda, ādīnavasaññā. (4)**This is called the perception of drawbacks.*";
P_HTM[1973]="*Katamā cānanda, pahānasaññā?**And what is the perception of giving up?*";
P_HTM[1974]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu uppannaṃ kāmavitakkaṃ nādhivāseti, pajahati, vinodeti, byantīkaroti, anabhāvaṃ gameti. Uppannaṃ byāpādavitakkaṃ nādhivāseti, pajahati, vinodeti, byantīkaroti, anabhāvaṃ gameti. Uppannaṃ vihiṃsāvitakkaṃ nādhivāseti, pajahati, vinodeti, byantīkaroti, anabhāvaṃ gameti. Uppannuppanne pāpake akusale dhamme nādhivāseti, pajahati, vinodeti, byantīkaroti, anabhāvaṃ gameti.**It’s when a mendicant doesn’t tolerate a sensual, malicious, or cruel thought that has arisen, and they don’t tolerate any bad, unskillful qualities that have arisen, but give them up, get rid of them, eliminate them, and obliterate them.*";
P_HTM[1975]="*Ayaṃ vuccatānanda, pahānasaññā. (5)**This is called the perception of giving up.*";
P_HTM[1976]="*Katamā cānanda, virāgasaññā?**And what is the perception of fading away?*";
P_HTM[1977]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu araññagato vā rukkhamūlagato vā suññāgāragato vā iti paṭisañcikkhati:**It’s when a mendicant has gone to a wilderness, or to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, and reflects like this:*";
P_HTM[1978]="*‘etaṃ santaṃ etaṃ paṇītaṃ yadidaṃ sabbasaṅkhārasamatho sabbūpadhippaṭinissaggo taṇhākkhayo virāgo nibbānan’ti.**‘This is peaceful; this is sublime—that is, the stilling of all activities, the letting go of all attachments, the ending of craving, fading away, extinguishment.’*";
P_HTM[1979]="*Ayaṃ vuccatānanda, virāgasaññā. (6)**This is called the perception of fading away.*";
P_HTM[1980]="*Katamā cānanda, nirodhasaññā?**And what is the perception of cessation?*";
P_HTM[1981]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu araññagato vā rukkhamūlagato vā suññāgāragato vā iti paṭisañcikkhati:**It’s when a mendicant has gone to a wilderness, or to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, and reflects like this:*";
P_HTM[1982]="*‘etaṃ santaṃ etaṃ paṇītaṃ yadidaṃ sabbasaṅkhārasamatho sabbūpadhippaṭinissaggo taṇhākkhayo nirodho nibbānan’ti.**‘This is peaceful; this is sublime—that is, the stilling of all activities, the letting go of all attachments, the ending of craving, cessation, extinguishment.’*";
P_HTM[1983]="*Ayaṃ vuccatānanda, nirodhasaññā. (7)**This is called the perception of cessation.*";
P_HTM[1984]="*Katamā cānanda, sabbaloke anabhiratasaññā?**And what is the perception of dissatisfaction with the whole world?*";
P_HTM[1985]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu ye loke upādānā cetaso adhiṭṭhānābhinivesānusayā, te pajahanto viharati anupādiyanto.**It’s when a mendicant lives giving up and not grasping on to the attraction and grasping to the world, the mental fixation, insistence, and underlying tendencies.*";
P_HTM[1986]="*Ayaṃ vuccatānanda, sabbaloke anabhiratasaññā. (8)**This is called the perception of dissatisfaction with the whole world.*";
P_HTM[1987]="*Katamā cānanda, sabbasaṅkhāresu anicchāsaññā?**And what is the perception of non-desire for all conditions?*";
P_HTM[1988]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu sabbasaṅkhāresu aṭṭīyati harāyati jigucchati.**It’s when a mendicant is horrified, repelled, and disgusted with all conditions.*";
P_HTM[1989]="*Ayaṃ vuccatānanda, sabbasaṅkhāresu anicchāsaññā. (9)**This is called the perception of non-desire for all conditions.*";
P_HTM[1990]="*Katamā cānanda, ānāpānassati?**And what is mindfulness of breathing?*";
P_HTM[1991]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu araññagato vā rukkhamūlagato vā suññāgāragato vā nisīdati pallaṅkaṃ ābhujitvā ujuṃ kāyaṃ paṇidhāya parimukhaṃ satiṃ upaṭṭhapetvā.**It’s when a mendicant has gone to a wilderness, or to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, sits down cross-legged, with their body straight, and establishes mindfulness right there.*";
P_HTM[1992]="*So satova assasati satova passasati.**Just mindful, they breathe in. Mindful, they breathe out.*";
P_HTM[1993]="*Dīghaṃ vā assasanto ‘dīghaṃ assasāmī’ti pajānāti. Dīghaṃ vā passasanto ‘dīghaṃ passasāmī’ti pajānāti.**When breathing in heavily they know: ‘I’m breathing in heavily.’ When breathing out heavily they know: ‘I’m breathing out heavily.’*";
P_HTM[1994]="*Rassaṃ vā assasanto ‘rassaṃ assasāmī’ti pajānāti. Rassaṃ vā passasanto ‘rassaṃ passasāmī’ti pajānāti.**When breathing in lightly they know: ‘I’m breathing in lightly.’ When breathing out lightly they know: ‘I’m breathing out lightly.’*";
P_HTM[1995]="*‘Sabbakāyapaṭisaṃvedī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati. ‘Sabbakāyapaṭisaṃvedī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati.**They practice breathing in experiencing the whole body. They practice breathing out experiencing the whole body.*";
P_HTM[1996]="*‘Passambhayaṃ kāyasaṅkhāraṃ assasissāmī’ti sikkhati. ‘Passambhayaṃ kāyasaṅkhāraṃ passasissāmī’ti sikkhati.**They practice breathing in stilling the body’s motion. They practice breathing out stilling the body’s motion.*";
P_HTM[1997]="*‘Pītipaṭisaṃvedī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati. ‘Pītipaṭisaṃvedī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati.**They practice breathing in experiencing rapture. They practice breathing out experiencing rapture.*";
P_HTM[1998]="*‘Sukhapaṭisaṃvedī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati. ‘Sukhapaṭisaṃvedī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati.**They practice breathing in experiencing bliss. They practice breathing out experiencing bliss.*";
P_HTM[1999]="*‘Cittasaṅkhārapaṭisaṃvedī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati. ‘Cittasaṅkhārapaṭisaṃvedī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati.**They practice breathing in experiencing these emotions. They practice breathing out experiencing these emotions.*";
P_HTM[2000]="*‘Passambhayaṃ cittasaṅkhāraṃ assasissāmī’ti sikkhati. ‘Passambhayaṃ cittasaṅkhāraṃ passasissāmī’ti sikkhati.**They practice breathing in stilling these emotions. They practice breathing out stilling these emotions.*";
P_HTM[2001]="*‘Cittapaṭisaṃvedī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati. ‘Cittapaṭisaṃvedī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati.**They practice breathing in experiencing the mind. They practice breathing out experiencing the mind.*";
P_HTM[2002]="*Abhippamodayaṃ cittaṃ … pe …**They practice breathing in gladdening the mind. They practice breathing out gladdening the mind.*";
P_HTM[2003]="*samādahaṃ cittaṃ … pe …**They practice breathing in immersing the mind. They practice breathing out immersing the mind.*";
P_HTM[2004]="*vimocayaṃ cittaṃ … pe …**They practice breathing in freeing the mind. They practice breathing out freeing the mind.*";
P_HTM[2005]="*aniccānupassī … pe …**They practice breathing in observing impermanence. They practice breathing out observing impermanence.*";
P_HTM[2006]="*virāgānupassī … pe …**They practice breathing in observing fading away. They practice breathing out observing fading away.*";
P_HTM[2007]="*nirodhānupassī … pe …**They practice breathing in observing cessation. They practice breathing out observing cessation.*";
P_HTM[2008]="*‘paṭinissaggānupassī assasissāmī’ti sikkhati. ‘Paṭinissaggānupassī passasissāmī’ti sikkhati.**They practice breathing in observing letting go. They practice breathing out observing letting go.*";
P_HTM[2009]="*Ayaṃ vuccatānanda, ānāpānassati. (10)**This is called mindfulness of breathing.*";
P_HTM[2010]="*Sace kho tvaṃ, ānanda, girimānandassa bhikkhuno imā dasa saññā bhāseyyāsi, ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ vijjati yaṃ girimānandassa bhikkhuno imā dasa saññā sutvā so ābādho ṭhānaso paṭippassambheyyā”ti.**If you were to recite to the mendicant Girimānanda these ten perceptions, it’s possible that after hearing them his illness will die down on the spot.”*";
P_HTM[2011]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato santike imā dasa saññā uggahetvā yenāyasmā girimānando tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmato girimānandassa imā dasa saññā abhāsi.**Then Ānanda, having learned these ten perceptions from the Buddha himself, went to Girimānanda and recited them.*";
P_HTM[2012]="*Atha kho āyasmato girimānandassa dasa saññā sutvā so ābādho ṭhānaso paṭippassambhi.**Then after Girimānanda heard these ten perceptions his illness died down on the spot.*";
P_HTM[2013]="*Vuṭṭhahi cāyasmā girimānando tamhā ābādhā. Tathā pahīno ca panāyasmato girimānandassa so ābādho ahosīti.**And that’s how he recovered from that illness.*";
P_HTM[2014]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2015]="*Sacittavaggo paṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[2016]="*Sacittañca sāriputta,* **";
P_HTM[2017]="*ṭhiti ca samathena ca;* **";
P_HTM[2018]="*Parihāno ca dve saññā,* **";
P_HTM[2019]="*mūlā pabbajitaṃ girīti.* **";
P_HTM[2020]="*123. Rāgapeyyālaṃ**Pairs*";
P_HTM[2021]="*1. Avijjāsuttaṃ**Ignorance*";
P_HTM[2022]="*“Purimā, bhikkhave, koṭi na paññāyati avijjāya: ‘ito pubbe avijjā nāhosi, atha pacchā samabhavī’ti.**“Mendicants, it is said that no first point of ignorance is evident, before which there was no ignorance, and afterwards it came to be.*";
P_HTM[2023]="*Evañcetaṃ, bhikkhave, vuccati, atha ca pana paññāyati: ‘idappaccayā avijjā’ti.**And yet it is evident that there is a specific condition for ignorance.*";
P_HTM[2024]="*Avijjampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that ignorance is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2025]="*Ko cāhāro avijjāya?**And what is the fuel for ignorance?*";
P_HTM[2026]="*‘Pañca nīvaraṇā’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘The five hindrances.’*";
P_HTM[2027]="*Pañcapāhaṃ, bhikkhave, nīvaraṇe sāhāre vadāmi, no anāhāre.**I say that the five hindrances are fueled by something, they’re not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2028]="*Ko cāhāro pañcannaṃ nīvaraṇānaṃ?**And what is the fuel for the five hindrances?*";
P_HTM[2029]="*‘Tīṇi duccaritānī’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘The three kinds of misconduct.’*";
P_HTM[2030]="*Tīṇipāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duccaritāni sāhārāni vadāmi, no anāhārāni.**I say that the three kinds of misconduct are fueled by something, they’re not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2031]="*Ko cāhāro tiṇṇaṃ duccaritānaṃ?**And what is the fuel for the three kinds of misconduct?*";
P_HTM[2032]="*‘Indriyaasaṃvaro’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Lack of sense restraint.’*";
P_HTM[2033]="*Indriyaasaṃvarampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that lack of sense restraint is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2034]="*Ko cāhāro indriyaasaṃvarassa?**And what is the fuel for lack of sense restraint?*";
P_HTM[2035]="*‘Asatāsampajaññan’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Lack of mindfulness and situational awareness.’*";
P_HTM[2036]="*Asatāsampajaññampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that lack of mindfulness and situational awareness is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2037]="*Ko cāhāro asatāsampajaññassa?**And what is the fuel for lack of mindfulness and situational awareness?*";
P_HTM[2038]="*‘Ayonisomanasikāro’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Improper attention.’*";
P_HTM[2039]="*Ayonisomanasikārampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that improper attention is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2040]="*Ko cāhāro ayonisomanasikārassa?**And what is the fuel for improper attention?*";
P_HTM[2041]="*‘Assaddhiyan’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Lack of faith.’*";
P_HTM[2042]="*Assaddhiyampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that lack of faith is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2043]="*Ko cāhāro assaddhiyassa?**And what is the fuel for lack of faith?*";
P_HTM[2044]="*‘Asaddhammassavanan’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Not listening to the true teaching.’*";
P_HTM[2045]="*Asaddhammassavanampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that not listening to the true teaching is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2046]="*Ko cāhāro asaddhammassavanassa?**And what is the fuel for not listening to the true teaching?*";
P_HTM[2047]="*‘Asappurisasaṃsevo’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Not associating with good people.’*";
P_HTM[2048]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, asappurisasaṃsevo paripūro asaddhammassavanaṃ paripūreti, asaddhammassavanaṃ paripūraṃ assaddhiyaṃ paripūreti, assaddhiyaṃ paripūraṃ ayonisomanasikāraṃ paripūreti, ayonisomanasikāro paripūro asatāsampajaññaṃ paripūreti, asatāsampajaññaṃ paripūraṃ indriyaasaṃvaraṃ paripūreti, indriyaasaṃvaro paripūro tīṇi duccaritāni paripūreti, tīṇi duccaritāni paripūrāni pañca nīvaraṇe paripūrenti, pañca nīvaraṇā paripūrā avijjaṃ paripūrenti;**In this way, when the factor of not associating with good people is fulfilled, it fulfills the factor of not listening to the true teaching. When the factor of not listening to the true teaching is fulfilled, it fulfills the factor of lack of faith … improper attention … lack of mindfulness and situational awareness … lack of sense restraint … the three kinds of misconduct … the five hindrances. When the five hindrances are fulfilled, they fulfill ignorance.*";
P_HTM[2049]="*evametissā avijjāya āhāro hoti, evañca pāripūri.**That’s the fuel for ignorance, and that’s how it’s fulfilled.*";
P_HTM[2050]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, uparipabbate thullaphusitake deve vassante () taṃ udakaṃ yathāninnaṃ pavattamānaṃ pabbatakandarapadarasākhā paripūreti, pabbatakandarapadarasākhā paripūrā kusobbhe paripūrenti. Kusobbhā paripūrā mahāsobbhe paripūrenti, mahāsobbhā paripūrā kunnadiyo paripūrenti, kunnadiyo paripūrā mahānadiyo paripūrenti, mahānadiyo paripūrā mahāsamuddaṃ sāgaraṃ paripūrenti;**It’s like when the rain pours down on a mountain top, and the water flows downhill to fill the hollows, crevices, and creeks. As they become full, they fill up the pools. The pools fill up the lakes, the lakes fill up the streams, and the streams fill up the rivers. And as the rivers become full, they fill up the ocean.*";
P_HTM[2051]="*evametassa mahāsamuddassa sāgarassa āhāro hoti, evañca pāripūri.**That’s the fuel for the ocean, and that’s how it’s filled up.*";
P_HTM[2052]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, asappurisasaṃsevo paripūro asaddhammassavanaṃ paripūreti, asaddhammassavanaṃ paripūraṃ assaddhiyaṃ paripūreti, assaddhiyaṃ paripūraṃ ayonisomanasikāraṃ paripūreti, ayonisomanasikāro paripūro asatāsampajaññaṃ paripūreti, asatāsampajaññaṃ paripūraṃ indriyaasaṃvaraṃ paripūreti, indriyaasaṃvaro paripūro tīṇi duccaritāni paripūreti, tīṇi duccaritāni paripūrāni pañca nīvaraṇe paripūrenti, pañca nīvaraṇā paripūrā avijjaṃ paripūrenti;**In the same way, when the factor of not associating with good people is fulfilled, it fulfills the factor of not listening to the true teaching. When the factor of not listening to the true teaching is fulfilled, it fulfills the factor of lack of faith … improper attention … lack of mindfulness and situational awareness … lack of sense restraint …the three kinds of misconduct … the five hindrances. When the five hindrances are fulfilled, they fulfill ignorance.*";
P_HTM[2053]="*evametissā avijjāya āhāro hoti, evañca pāripūri.**That’s the fuel for ignorance, and that’s how it’s fulfilled.*";
P_HTM[2054]="*Vijjāvimuttimpāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that knowledge and freedom are fueled by something, they’re not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2055]="*Ko cāhāro vijjāvimuttiyā?**And what is the fuel for knowledge and freedom?*";
P_HTM[2056]="*‘Satta bojjhaṅgā’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘The seven awakening factors.’*";
P_HTM[2057]="*Sattapāhaṃ, bhikkhave, bojjhaṅge sāhāre vadāmi, no anāhāre.**I say that the seven awakening factors are fueled by something, they’re not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2058]="*Ko cāhāro sattannaṃ bojjhaṅgānaṃ?**And what is the fuel for the seven awakening factors?*";
P_HTM[2059]="*‘Cattāro satipaṭṭhānā’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘The four kinds of mindfulness meditation.’*";
P_HTM[2060]="*Cattāropāhaṃ, bhikkhave, satipaṭṭhāne sāhāre vadāmi, no anāhāre.**I say that the four kinds of mindfulness meditation are fueled by something, they’re not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2061]="*Ko cāhāro catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ?**And what is the fuel for the four kinds of mindfulness meditation?*";
P_HTM[2062]="*‘Tīṇi sucaritānī’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘The three kinds of good conduct.’*";
P_HTM[2063]="*Tīṇipāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sucaritāni sāhārāni vadāmi, no anāhārāni.**I say that the three kinds of good conduct are fueled by something, they’re not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2064]="*Ko cāhāro tiṇṇaṃ sucaritānaṃ?**And what is the fuel for the three kinds of good conduct?*";
P_HTM[2065]="*‘Indriyasaṃvaro’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Sense restraint.’*";
P_HTM[2066]="*Indriyasaṃvarampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that sense restraint is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2067]="*Ko cāhāro indriyasaṃvarassa?**And what is the fuel for sense restraint?*";
P_HTM[2068]="*‘Satisampajaññan’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Mindfulness and situational awareness.’*";
P_HTM[2069]="*Satisampajaññampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that mindfulness and situational awareness is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2070]="*Ko cāhāro satisampajaññassa?**And what is the fuel for mindfulness and situational awareness?*";
P_HTM[2071]="*‘Yonisomanasikāro’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Proper attention.’*";
P_HTM[2072]="*Yonisomanasikārampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that proper attention is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2073]="*Ko cāhāro yonisomanasikārassa?**And what is the fuel for proper attention?*";
P_HTM[2074]="*‘Saddhā’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Faith.’*";
P_HTM[2075]="*Saddhampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that faith is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2076]="*Ko cāhāro saddhāya?**And what is the fuel for faith?*";
P_HTM[2077]="*‘Saddhammassavanan’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Listening to the true teaching.’*";
P_HTM[2078]="*Saddhammassavanampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that listening to the true teaching is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2079]="*Ko cāhāro saddhammassavanassa?**And what is the fuel for listening to the true teaching?*";
P_HTM[2080]="*‘Sappurisasaṃsevo’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Associating with good people.’*";
P_HTM[2081]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, sappurisasaṃsevo paripūro saddhammassavanaṃ paripūreti, saddhammassavanaṃ paripūraṃ saddhaṃ paripūreti, saddhā paripūrā yonisomanasikāraṃ paripūreti, yonisomanasikāro paripūro satisampajaññaṃ paripūreti, satisampajaññaṃ paripūraṃ indriyasaṃvaraṃ paripūreti, indriyasaṃvaro paripūro tīṇi sucaritāni paripūreti, tīṇi sucaritāni paripūrāni cattāro satipaṭṭhāne paripūrenti, cattāro satipaṭṭhānā paripūrā satta bojjhaṅge paripūrenti, satta bojjhaṅgā paripūrā vijjāvimuttiṃ paripūrenti;**In this way, when the factor of associating with good people is fulfilled, it fulfills the factor of listening to the true teaching. When the factor of listening to the true teaching is fulfilled, it fulfills the factor of faith … proper attention … mindfulness and situational awareness … sense restraint …the three kinds of good conduct … the four kinds of mindfulness meditation … the seven awakening factors. When the seven awakening factors are fulfilled, they fulfill knowledge and freedom.*";
P_HTM[2082]="*evametissā vijjāvimuttiyā āhāro hoti, evañca pāripūri.**That’s the fuel for knowledge and freedom, and that’s how it’s fulfilled.*";
P_HTM[2083]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, uparipabbate thullaphusitake deve vassante taṃ udakaṃ yathāninnaṃ pavattamānaṃ pabbatakandarapadarasākhā paripūreti, pabbatakandarapadarasākhā paripūrā kusobbhe paripūrenti, kusobbhā paripūrā mahāsobbhe paripūrenti, mahāsobbhā paripūrā kunnadiyo paripūrenti, kunnadiyo paripūrā mahānadiyo paripūrenti, mahānadiyo paripūrā mahāsamuddaṃ sāgaraṃ paripūrenti;**It’s like when it rains heavily on a mountain top, and the water flows downhill to fill the hollows, crevices, and creeks. As they become full, they fill up the pools. The pools fill up the lakes, the lakes fill up the streams, and the streams fill up the rivers. And as the rivers become full, they fill up the ocean.*";
P_HTM[2084]="*evametassa mahāsamuddassa sāgarassa āhāro hoti, evañca pāripūri.**That’s the fuel for the ocean, and that’s how it’s filled up.*";
P_HTM[2085]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, sappurisasaṃsevo paripūro saddhammassavanaṃ paripūreti, saddhammassavanaṃ paripūraṃ saddhaṃ paripūreti, saddhā paripūrā yonisomanasikāraṃ paripūreti, yonisomanasikāro paripūro satisampajaññaṃ paripūreti, satisampajaññaṃ paripūraṃ indriyasaṃvaraṃ paripūreti, indriyasaṃvaro paripūro tīṇi sucaritāni paripūreti, tīṇi sucaritāni paripūrāni cattāro satipaṭṭhāne paripūrenti, cattāro satipaṭṭhānā paripūrā satta bojjhaṅge paripūrenti, satta bojjhaṅgā paripūrā vijjāvimuttiṃ paripūrenti;**In the same way, when the factor of associating with good people is fulfilled, it fulfills the factor of listening to the true teaching. When the factor of listening to the true teaching is fulfilled, it fulfills the factor of faith … proper attention … mindfulness and situational awareness … sense restraint …the three kinds of good conduct … the four kinds of mindfulness meditation … the seven awakening factors. When the seven awakening factors are fulfilled, they fulfill knowledge and freedom.*";
P_HTM[2086]="*evametissā vijjāvimuttiyā āhāro hoti, evañca pāripūrī”ti.**That’s the fuel for knowledge and freedom, and that’s how it’s fulfilled.”*";
P_HTM[2087]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2088]="*2. Ḍtaṇhāsuttaṃ**Craving*";
P_HTM[2089]="*“Purimā, bhikkhave, koṭi na paññāyati bhavataṇhāya: ‘ito pubbe bhavataṇhā nāhosi, atha pacchā samabhavī’ti.**“Mendicants, it is said that no first point of craving for continued existence is evident, before which there was no craving for continued existence, and afterwards it came to be.*";
P_HTM[2090]="*Evañcetaṃ, bhikkhave, vuccati, atha ca pana paññāyati: ‘idappaccayā bhavataṇhā’ti.**And yet it is evident that there is a specific condition for craving for continued existence.*";
P_HTM[2091]="*Bhavataṇhampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that craving for continued existence is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2092]="*Ko cāhāro bhavataṇhāya?**And what is the fuel for craving for continued existence?*";
P_HTM[2093]="*‘Avijjā’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Ignorance.’*";
P_HTM[2094]="*Avijjampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that ignorance is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2095]="*Ko cāhāro avijjāya?**And what is the fuel for ignorance?*";
P_HTM[2096]="*‘Pañca nīvaraṇā’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘The five hindrances.’*";
P_HTM[2097]="*Pañca nīvaraṇepāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāre vadāmi, no anāhāre.**I say that the five hindrances are fueled by something, they’re not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2098]="*Ko cāhāro pañcannaṃ nīvaraṇānaṃ?**And what is the fuel for the five hindrances?*";
P_HTM[2099]="*‘Tīṇi duccaritānī’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘The three kinds of misconduct.’*";
P_HTM[2100]="*Tīṇipāhaṃ, bhikkhave, duccaritāni sāhārāni vadāmi, no anāhārāni.**I say that the three kinds of misconduct are fueled by something, they’re not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2101]="*Ko cāhāro tiṇṇannaṃ duccaritānaṃ?**And what is the fuel for the three kinds of misconduct?*";
P_HTM[2102]="*‘Indriyaasaṃvaro’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Lack of sense restraint.’*";
P_HTM[2103]="*Indriyaasaṃvarampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that lack of sense restraint is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2104]="*Ko cāhāro indriyaasaṃvarassa?**And what is the fuel for lack of sense restraint?*";
P_HTM[2105]="*‘Asatāsampajaññan’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Lack of mindfulness and situational awareness.’*";
P_HTM[2106]="*Asatāsampajaññampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that lack of mindfulness and situational awareness is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2107]="*Ko cāhāro asatā sampajaññassa?**And what is the fuel for lack of mindfulness and situational awareness?*";
P_HTM[2108]="*‘Ayonisomanasikāro’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Improper attention.’*";
P_HTM[2109]="*Ayonisomanasikārampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that improper attention is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2110]="*Ko cāhāro ayonisomanasikārassa?**And what is the fuel for improper attention?*";
P_HTM[2111]="*‘Assaddhiyan’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Lack of faith.’*";
P_HTM[2112]="*Assaddhiyampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that lack of faith is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2113]="*Ko cāhāro assaddhiyassa?**And what is the fuel for lack of faith?*";
P_HTM[2114]="*‘Assaddhammassavanan’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Listening to an untrue teaching.’*";
P_HTM[2115]="*Assaddhammassavanampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that listening to an untrue teaching is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2116]="*Ko cāhāro assaddhammassavanassa?**And what is the fuel for listening to an untrue teaching?*";
P_HTM[2117]="*‘Asappurisasaṃsevo’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Associating with bad people.’*";
P_HTM[2118]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, asappurisasaṃsevo paripūro assaddhammassavanaṃ paripūreti, assaddhammassavanaṃ paripūraṃ assaddhiyaṃ paripūreti, assaddhiyaṃ paripūraṃ ayonisomanasikāraṃ paripūreti, ayonisomanasikāro paripūro asatāsampajaññaṃ paripūreti, asatāsampajaññaṃ paripūraṃ indriyaasaṃvaraṃ paripūreti, indriyaasaṃvaro paripūro tīṇi duccaritāni paripūreti, tīṇi duccaritāni paripūrāni pañca nīvaraṇe paripūrenti, pañca nīvaraṇā paripūrā avijjaṃ paripūrenti, avijjā paripūrā bhavataṇhaṃ paripūreti;**In this way, when the factor of associating with bad people is fulfilled, it fulfills the factor of listening to an untrue teaching. When the factor of listening to an untrue teaching is fulfilled, it fulfills the factor of lack of faith … improper attention … lack of mindfulness and situational awareness … lack of sense restraint …the three kinds of misconduct … the five hindrances … ignorance. When ignorance is fulfilled, it fulfills craving for continued existence.*";
P_HTM[2119]="*evametissā bhavataṇhāya āhāro hoti, evañca pāripūri.**That’s the fuel for craving for continued existence, and that’s how it’s fulfilled.*";
P_HTM[2120]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, uparipabbate thullaphusitake deve vassante taṃ udakaṃ yathāninnaṃ pavattamānaṃ pabbatakandarapadarasākhā paripūreti, pabbatakandarapadarasākhā paripūrā kusobbhe paripūrenti, kusobbhā paripūrā mahāsobbhe paripūrenti, mahāsobbhā paripūrā kunnadiyo paripūrenti, kunnadiyo paripūrā mahānadiyo paripūrenti, mahānadiyo paripūrā mahāsamuddaṃ sāgaraṃ paripūrenti;**It’s like when it rains heavily on a mountain top, and the water flows downhill to fill the hollows, crevices, and creeks. As they become full, they fill up the pools. The pools fill up the lakes, the lakes fill up the streams, and the streams fill up the rivers. And as the rivers become full, they fill up the ocean.*";
P_HTM[2121]="*evametassa mahāsamuddassa sāgarassa āhāro hoti, evañca pāripūri.**That’s the fuel for the ocean, and that’s how it’s filled up.*";
P_HTM[2122]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, asappurisasaṃsevo paripūro assaddhammassavanaṃ paripūreti, assaddhammassavanaṃ paripūraṃ assaddhiyaṃ paripūreti, assaddhiyaṃ paripūraṃ ayonisomanasikāraṃ paripūreti, ayonisomanasikāro paripūro asatāsampajaññaṃ paripūreti, asatāsampajaññaṃ paripūraṃ indriyaasaṃvaraṃ paripūreti, indriyaasaṃvaro paripūro tīṇi duccaritāni paripūreti, tīṇi duccaritāni paripūrāni pañca nīvaraṇe paripūrenti, pañca nīvaraṇā paripūrā avijjaṃ paripūrenti, avijjā paripūrā bhavataṇhaṃ paripūreti;**In the same way, when the factor of associating with bad people is fulfilled, it fulfills the factor of listening to an untrue teaching. When the factor of listening to an untrue teaching is fulfilled, it fulfills the factor of lack of faith … improper attention … lack of mindfulness and situational awareness … lack of sense restraint …the three kinds of misconduct … the five hindrances … ignorance. When ignorance is fulfilled, it fulfills craving for continued existence.*";
P_HTM[2123]="*evametissā bhavataṇhāya āhāro hoti, evañca pāripūri.**That’s the fuel for craving for continued existence, and that’s how it’s fulfilled.*";
P_HTM[2124]="*Vijjāvimuttimpāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that knowledge and freedom are fueled by something, they’re not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2125]="*Ko cāhāro vijjāvimuttiyā?**And what is the fuel for knowledge and freedom?*";
P_HTM[2126]="*‘Satta bojjhaṅgā’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘The seven awakening factors.’*";
P_HTM[2127]="*Sattapāhaṃ, bhikkhave, bojjhaṅge sāhāre vadāmi, no anāhāre.**I say that the seven awakening factors are fueled by something, they’re not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2128]="*Ko cāhāro sattannaṃ bojjhaṅgānaṃ?**And what is the fuel for the seven awakening factors?*";
P_HTM[2129]="*‘Cattāro satipaṭṭhānā’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘The four kinds of mindfulness meditation.’*";
P_HTM[2130]="*Cattāropāhaṃ, bhikkhave, satipaṭṭhāne sāhāre vadāmi, no anāhāre.**I say that the four kinds of mindfulness meditation are fueled by something, they’re not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2131]="*Ko cāhāro catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ?**And what is the fuel for the four kinds of mindfulness meditation?*";
P_HTM[2132]="*‘Tīṇi sucaritānī’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘The three kinds of good conduct.’*";
P_HTM[2133]="*Tīṇipāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sucaritāni sāhārāni vadāmi, no anāhārāni.**I say that the three kinds of good conduct are fueled by something, they’re not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2134]="*Ko cāhāro tiṇṇannaṃ sucaritānaṃ?**And what is the fuel for the three kinds of good conduct?*";
P_HTM[2135]="*‘Indriyasaṃvaro’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Sense restraint.’*";
P_HTM[2136]="*Indriyasaṃvarampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that sense restraint is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2137]="*Ko cāhāro indriyasaṃvarassa?**And what is the fuel for sense restraint?*";
P_HTM[2138]="*‘Satisampajaññan’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Mindfulness and situational awareness.’*";
P_HTM[2139]="*Satisampajaññampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that mindfulness and situational awareness is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2140]="*Ko cāhāro satisampajaññassa?**And what is the fuel for mindfulness and situational awareness?*";
P_HTM[2141]="*‘Yonisomanasikāro’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Proper attention.’*";
P_HTM[2142]="*Yonisomanasikārampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that proper attention is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2143]="*Ko cāhāro yonisomanasikārassa?**And what is the fuel for proper attention?*";
P_HTM[2144]="*‘Saddhā’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Faith.’*";
P_HTM[2145]="*Saddhampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that faith is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2146]="*Ko cāhāro saddhāya?**And what is the fuel for faith?*";
P_HTM[2147]="*‘Saddhammassavanan’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Listening to the true teaching.’*";
P_HTM[2148]="*Saddhammassavanampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sāhāraṃ vadāmi, no anāhāraṃ.**I say that listening to the true teaching is fueled by something, it’s not unfueled.*";
P_HTM[2149]="*Ko cāhāro saddhammassavanassa?**And what is the fuel for listening to the true teaching?*";
P_HTM[2150]="*‘Sappurisasaṃsevo’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘Associating with good people.’*";
P_HTM[2151]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, sappurisasaṃsevo paripūro saddhammassavanaṃ paripūreti, saddhammassavanaṃ paripūraṃ saddhaṃ paripūreti, saddhā paripūrā yonisomanasikāraṃ paripūreti, yonisomanasikāro paripūro satisampajaññaṃ paripūreti, satisampajaññaṃ paripūraṃ indriyasaṃvaraṃ paripūreti, indriyasaṃvaro paripūro tīṇi sucaritāni paripūreti, tīṇi sucaritāni paripūrāni cattāro satipaṭṭhāne paripūrenti, cattāro satipaṭṭhānā paripūrā satta bojjhaṅge paripūrenti, satta bojjhaṅgā paripūrā vijjāvimuttiṃ paripūrenti;**In this way, when the factor of associating with good people is fulfilled, it fulfills the factor of listening to the true teaching. When the factor of listening to the true teaching is fulfilled, it fulfills the factor of faith … proper attention … mindfulness and situational awareness … sense restraint …the three kinds of good conduct … the four kinds of mindfulness meditation … the seven awakening factors. When the seven awakening factors are fulfilled, they fulfill knowledge and freedom.*";
P_HTM[2152]="*evametissā vijjāvimuttiyā āhāro hoti, evañca pāripūri.**That’s the fuel for knowledge and freedom, and that’s how it’s fulfilled.*";
P_HTM[2153]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, uparipabbate thullaphusitake deve vassante taṃ udakaṃ yathāninnaṃ pavattamānaṃ … pe …**It’s like when it rains heavily on a mountain top, and the water flows downhill to fill the hollows, crevices, and creeks. As they become full, they fill up the pools. The pools fill up the lakes, the lakes fill up the streams, and the streams fill up the rivers. And as the rivers become full, they fill up the ocean.*";
P_HTM[2154]="*evametassa mahāsamuddassa sāgarassa āhāro hoti, evañca pāripūri.**That’s the fuel for the ocean, and that’s how it’s filled up.*";
P_HTM[2155]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, sappurisasaṃsevo paripūro saddhammassavanaṃ paripūreti … pe …**In this way, when the factor of associating with good people is fulfilled, it fulfills the factor of listening to the true teaching. When the factor of listening to the true teaching is fulfilled, it fulfills the factor of faith … proper attention … mindfulness and situational awareness … sense restraint …the three kinds of good conduct … the four kinds of mindfulness meditation … the seven awakening factors. When the seven awakening factors are fulfilled, they fulfill knowledge and freedom.*";
P_HTM[2156]="*evametissā vijjāvimuttiyā āhāro hoti, evañca pāripūrī”ti.**That’s the fuel for knowledge and freedom, and that’s how it’s fulfilled.”*";
P_HTM[2157]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2158]="*3. Niṭṭhaṅgatasuttaṃ**Come to a Conclusion*";
P_HTM[2159]="*“Ye keci, bhikkhave, mayi niṭṭhaṃ gatā sabbe te diṭṭhisampannā.**“Mendicants, all those who have come to a conclusion about me are accomplished in view.*";
P_HTM[2160]="*Tesaṃ diṭṭhisampannānaṃ pañcannaṃ idha niṭṭhā, pañcannaṃ idha vihāya niṭṭhā.**Of those who are accomplished in view, five conclude their path in this realm, and five conclude their path after leaving this realm behind.*";
P_HTM[2161]="*Katamesaṃ pañcannaṃ idha niṭṭhā?**Which five conclude their path in this realm?*";
P_HTM[2162]="*Sattakkhattuparamassa, kolaṅkolassa, ekabījissa, sakadāgāmissa, yo ca diṭṭheva dhamme arahā—**The one who has seven rebirths at most, the one who goes from family to family, the one-seeder, the once returner, and the one who is perfected in the present life.*";
P_HTM[2163]="*imesaṃ pañcannaṃ idha niṭṭhā.**These five conclude their path in this realm.*";
P_HTM[2164]="*Katamesaṃ pañcannaṃ idha vihāya niṭṭhā?**Which five conclude their path after leaving this realm behind?*";
P_HTM[2165]="*Antarāparinibbāyissa, upahaccaparinibbāyissa, asaṅkhāraparinibbāyissa, sasaṅkhāraparinibbāyissa, uddhaṃsotassa akaniṭṭhagāmino—**The one who is extinguished between one life and the next, the one who is extinguished upon landing, the one who is extinguished without extra effort, the one who is extinguished with extra effort, and the one who heads upstream, going to the Akaniṭṭha realm.*";
P_HTM[2166]="*imesaṃ pañcannaṃ idha vihāya niṭṭhā.**These five conclude their path after leaving this realm behind.*";
P_HTM[2167]="*Ye keci, bhikkhave, mayi niṭṭhaṃ gatā, sabbe te diṭṭhisampannā.**All those who have come to a conclusion about me are accomplished in view.*";
P_HTM[2168]="*Tesaṃ diṭṭhisampannānaṃ imesaṃ pañcannaṃ idha niṭṭhā, imesaṃ pañcannaṃ idha vihāya niṭṭhā”ti.**Of those who are accomplished in view, these five conclude their path in this realm, and these five conclude their path after leaving this realm behind.”*";
P_HTM[2169]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2170]="*4. Aveccappasannasuttaṃ**Experiential Confidence*";
P_HTM[2171]="*“Ye keci, bhikkhave, mayi aveccappasannā, sabbe te sotāpannā.**“Mendicants, all those who have experiential confidence in me have entered the stream.*";
P_HTM[2172]="*Tesaṃ sotāpannānaṃ pañcannaṃ idha niṭṭhā, pañcannaṃ idha vihāya niṭṭhā.**Of those who have entered the stream, five conclude their path in this realm, and five conclude their path after leaving this realm behind.*";
P_HTM[2173]="*Katamesaṃ pañcannaṃ idha niṭṭhā?**Which five conclude their path in this realm?*";
P_HTM[2174]="*Sattakkhattuparamassa, kolaṅkolassa, ekabījissa, sakadāgāmissa, yo ca diṭṭheva dhamme arahā—**The one who has seven rebirths at most, the one who goes from family to family, the one-seeder, the once returner, and the one who is perfected in the present life.*";
P_HTM[2175]="*imesaṃ pañcannaṃ idha niṭṭhā.**These five conclude their path in this realm.*";
P_HTM[2176]="*Katamesaṃ pañcannaṃ idha vihāya niṭṭhā?**Which five conclude their path after leaving this realm behind?*";
P_HTM[2177]="*Antarāparinibbāyissa, upahaccaparinibbāyissa, asaṅkhāraparinibbāyissa, sasaṅkhāraparinibbāyissa, uddhaṃsotassa akaniṭṭhagāmino—**The one who is extinguished between one life and the next, the one who is extinguished upon landing, the one who is extinguished without extra effort, the one who is extinguished with extra effort, and the one who heads upstream, going to the Akaniṭṭha realm.*";
P_HTM[2178]="*imesaṃ pañcannaṃ idha vihāya niṭṭhā.**These five conclude their path after leaving this realm behind.*";
P_HTM[2179]="*Ye keci, bhikkhave, mayi aveccappasannā sabbe te sotāpannā.**All those who have experiential confidence in me have entered the stream.*";
P_HTM[2180]="*Tesaṃ sotāpannānaṃ imesaṃ pañcannaṃ idha niṭṭhā, imesaṃ pañcannaṃ idha vihāya niṭṭhā”ti.**Of those who have entered the stream, these five conclude their path in this realm, and these five conclude their path after leaving this realm behind.”*";
P_HTM[2181]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2182]="*5. Paṭhamasukhasuttaṃ**Happiness (1st)*";
P_HTM[2183]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā sāriputto magadhesu viharati nālakagāmake.**At one time Venerable Sāriputta was staying in the land of the Magadhans near the little village of Nālaka.*";
P_HTM[2184]="*Atha kho sāmaṇḍakāni paribbājako yenāyasmā sāriputto tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā sāriputtena saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then the wanderer Sāmaṇḍakāni went up to Venerable Sāriputta and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[2185]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho sāmaṇḍakāni paribbājako āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, Sāmaṇḍakāni sat down to one side, and said to Sāriputta:*";
P_HTM[2186]="*“Kiṃ nu kho, āvuso sāriputta, sukhaṃ, kiṃ dukkhan”ti?**“Reverend Sāriputta, what is happiness and what is suffering?”*";
P_HTM[2187]="*“Abhinibbatti kho, āvuso, dukkhā, anabhinibbatti sukhā.**“Rebirth is suffering, reverend, no rebirth is happiness.*";
P_HTM[2188]="*Abhinibbattiyā, āvuso, sati idaṃ dukkhaṃ pāṭikaṅkhaṃ—**When there is rebirth, you can expect this kind of suffering.*";
P_HTM[2189]="*sītaṃ uṇhaṃ jighacchā pipāsā uccāro passāvo aggisamphasso daṇḍasamphasso satthasamphasso ñātīpi mittāpi saṅgamma samāgamma rosenti.**Cold, heat, hunger, thirst, defecation, and urination. Contact with fire, clubs, and knives. And relatives and friends get together and annoy you.*";
P_HTM[2190]="*Abhinibbattiyā, āvuso, sati idaṃ dukkhaṃ pāṭikaṅkhaṃ.**When there is rebirth, this is the kind of suffering you can expect.*";
P_HTM[2191]="*Anabhinibbattiyā, āvuso, sati idaṃ sukhaṃ pāṭikaṅkhaṃ—**When there is no rebirth, you can expect this kind of happiness.*";
P_HTM[2192]="*na sītaṃ na uṇhaṃ na jighacchā na pipāsā na uccāro na passāvo na aggisamphasso na daṇḍasamphasso na satthasamphasso ñātīpi mittāpi saṅgamma samāgamma na rosenti.**No cold, heat, hunger, thirst, defecation, or urination. No contact with fire, clubs, or knives. And relatives and friends don’t get together and annoy you.*";
P_HTM[2193]="*Anabhinibbattiyā, āvuso, sati idaṃ sukhaṃ pāṭikaṅkhan”ti.**When there is no rebirth, this is the kind of happiness you can expect.”*";
P_HTM[2194]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2195]="*6. Dutiyasukhasuttaṃ**Happiness (2nd)*";
P_HTM[2196]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā sāriputto magadhesu viharati nālakagāmake.**At one time Venerable Sāriputta was staying in the land of the Magadhans near the little village of Nālaka.*";
P_HTM[2197]="*Atha kho sāmaṇḍakāni paribbājako yenāyasmā sāriputto tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā sāriputtena saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then the wanderer Sāmaṇḍakāni went up to Venerable Sāriputta and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[2198]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho sāmaṇḍakāni paribbājako āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, Sāmaṇḍakāni sat down to one side and said to Sāriputta:*";
P_HTM[2199]="*“Kiṃ nu kho, āvuso, sāriputta, imasmiṃ dhammavinaye sukhaṃ, kiṃ dukkhan”ti?**“Reverend Sāriputta, in this teaching and training, what is happiness and what is suffering?”*";
P_HTM[2200]="*“Anabhirati kho, āvuso, imasmiṃ dhammavinaye dukkhā, abhirati sukhā.**“Reverend, in this teaching and training dissatisfaction is suffering and satisfaction is happiness.*";
P_HTM[2201]="*Anabhiratiyā, āvuso, sati idaṃ dukkhaṃ pāṭikaṅkhaṃ—**When you’re dissatisfied, you can expect this kind of suffering.*";
P_HTM[2202]="*gacchantopi sukhaṃ sātaṃ nādhigacchati,**You find no happiness or pleasure while walking …*";
P_HTM[2203]="*ṭhitopi …**standing …*";
P_HTM[2204]="*nisinnopi …**sitting …*";
P_HTM[2205]="*sayānopi …**or lying down …*";
P_HTM[2206]="*gāmagatopi …**or when in a village …*";
P_HTM[2207]="*araññagatopi …**a wilderness …*";
P_HTM[2208]="*rukkhamūlagatopi …**at the root of a tree …*";
P_HTM[2209]="*suññāgāragatopi …**an empty hut …*";
P_HTM[2210]="*abbhokāsagatopi …**the open air …*";
P_HTM[2211]="*bhikkhumajjhagatopi sukhaṃ sātaṃ nādhigacchati.**or when among the mendicants.*";
P_HTM[2212]="*Anabhiratiyā, āvuso, sati idaṃ dukkhaṃ pāṭikaṅkhaṃ.**When you’re dissatisfied, this is the kind of suffering you can expect.*";
P_HTM[2213]="*Abhiratiyā, āvuso, sati idaṃ sukhaṃ pāṭikaṅkhaṃ—**When you’re satisfied, you can expect this kind of happiness.*";
P_HTM[2214]="*gacchantopi sukhaṃ sātaṃ adhigacchati,**You find happiness or pleasure while walking …*";
P_HTM[2215]="*ṭhitopi …**standing …*";
P_HTM[2216]="*nisinnopi …**sitting …*";
P_HTM[2217]="*sayānopi …**or lying down …*";
P_HTM[2218]="*gāmagatopi …**or when in a village …*";
P_HTM[2219]="*araññagatopi …**a wilderness …*";
P_HTM[2220]="*rukkhamūlagatopi …**at the root of a tree …*";
P_HTM[2221]="*suññāgāragatopi …**an empty hut …*";
P_HTM[2222]="*abbhokāsagatopi …**the open air …*";
P_HTM[2223]="*bhikkhumajjhagatopi sukhaṃ sātaṃ adhigacchati.**or when among the mendicants.*";
P_HTM[2224]="*Abhiratiyā, āvuso, sati idaṃ sukhaṃ pāṭikaṅkhan”ti.**When you’re satisfied, this is the kind of happiness you can expect.”*";
P_HTM[2225]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2226]="*7. Paṭhamanaḷakapānasuttaṃ**At Naḷakapāna (1st)*";
P_HTM[2227]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā kosalesu cārikaṃ caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ yena naḷakapānaṃ nāma kosalānaṃ nigamo tadavasari.**At one time the Buddha was wandering in the land of the Kosalans together with a large Saṅgha of mendicants when he arrived at a town of the Kosalans named Naḷakapāna.*";
P_HTM[2228]="*Tatra sudaṃ bhagavā naḷakapāne viharati palāsavane.**There the Buddha stayed near Naḷakapāna in the parrot tree grove.*";
P_HTM[2229]="*Tena kho pana samayena bhagavā tadahuposathe bhikkhusaṅghaparivuto nisinno hoti.**Now, at that time it was the sabbath, and the Buddha was sitting surrounded by the Saṅgha of monks.*";
P_HTM[2230]="*Atha kho bhagavā bahudeva rattiṃ bhikkhūnaṃ dhammiyā kathāya sandassetvā samādapetvā samuttejetvā sampahaṃsetvā tuṇhībhūtaṃ tuṇhībhūtaṃ bhikkhusaṅghaṃ anuviloketvā āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ āmantesi:**The Buddha spent most of the night educating, encouraging, firing up, and inspiring the mendicants with a Dhamma talk. Then he looked around the Saṅgha of monks, who were so very silent. He addressed Venerable Sāriputta:*";
P_HTM[2231]="*“Vigatathinamiddho kho, sāriputta, bhikkhusaṃgho.**“Sāriputta, the Saṅgha of mendicants is rid of dullness and drowsiness.*";
P_HTM[2232]="*Paṭibhātu taṃ, sāriputta, bhikkhūnaṃ dhammī kathā.**Give them some Dhamma talk as you feel inspired.*";
P_HTM[2233]="*Piṭṭhi me āgilāyati;**My back is sore,*";
P_HTM[2234]="*tamahaṃ āyamissāmī”ti.**I’ll stretch it.”*";
P_HTM[2235]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā sāriputto bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Sāriputta replied.*";
P_HTM[2236]="*Atha kho bhagavā catugguṇaṃ saṅghāṭiṃ paññāpetvā dakkhiṇena passena sīhaseyyaṃ kappesi pāde pādaṃ accādhāya sato sampajāno uṭṭhānasaññaṃ manasi karitvā.**And then the Buddha spread out his outer robe folded in four and laid down in the lion’s posture—on the right side, placing one foot on top of the other—mindful and aware, and focused on the time of getting up.*";
P_HTM[2237]="*Tatra kho āyasmā sāriputto bhikkhū āmantesi:**There Sāriputta addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[2238]="*“āvuso bhikkhave”ti.**“Reverends, mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[2239]="*“Āvuso”ti kho te bhikkhū āyasmato sāriputtassa paccassosuṃ.**“Reverend,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[2240]="*Āyasmā sāriputto etadavoca:**Sāriputta said this:*";
P_HTM[2241]="*“Yassa kassaci, āvuso, saddhā natthi kusalesu dhammesu, hirī natthi …**“Reverends, whoever has no faith, conscience, prudence, energy, and wisdom when it comes to skillful qualities*";
P_HTM[2242]="*ottappaṃ natthi …* **";
P_HTM[2243]="*vīriyaṃ natthi …* **";
P_HTM[2244]="*paññā natthi kusalesu dhammesu, tassa yā ratti vā divaso vā āgacchati, hāniyeva pāṭikaṅkhā kusalesu dhammesu no vuddhi.**can expect decline, not growth, in skillful qualities, whether by day or by night.*";
P_HTM[2245]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso, kāḷapakkhe candassa yā ratti vā divaso vā āgacchati, hāyateva vaṇṇena hāyati maṇḍalena hāyati ābhāya hāyati ārohapariṇāhena;**It’s like the moon in the waning fortnight. Whether by day or by night, its beauty, roundness, light, and diameter and circumference only decline.*";
P_HTM[2246]="*evamevaṃ kho, āvuso, yassa kassaci saddhā natthi kusalesu dhammesu, hirī natthi …**In the same way, whoever has no faith, conscience, prudence, energy, and wisdom when it comes to skillful qualities*";
P_HTM[2247]="*ottappaṃ natthi …* **";
P_HTM[2248]="*vīriyaṃ natthi …* **";
P_HTM[2249]="*paññā natthi kusalesu dhammesu, tassa yā ratti vā divaso vā āgacchati, hāniyeva pāṭikaṅkhā kusalesu dhammesu no vuddhi.**can expect decline, not growth, in skillful qualities, whether by day or by night.*";
P_HTM[2250]="*‘Assaddho purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, parihānametaṃ;**A faithless individual is in decline.*";
P_HTM[2251]="*‘ahiriko purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, parihānametaṃ;**An individual with no conscience is in decline.*";
P_HTM[2252]="*‘anottappī purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, parihānametaṃ;**An imprudent individual is in decline.*";
P_HTM[2253]="*‘kusīto purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, parihānametaṃ;**A lazy individual is in decline.*";
P_HTM[2254]="*‘duppañño purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, parihānametaṃ;**A witless individual is in decline.*";
P_HTM[2255]="*‘kodhano purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, parihānametaṃ;**An irritable individual is in decline.*";
P_HTM[2256]="*‘upanāhī purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, parihānametaṃ;**A hostile individual is in decline.*";
P_HTM[2257]="*‘pāpiccho purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, parihānametaṃ;**An individual with bad desires is in decline.*";
P_HTM[2258]="*‘pāpamitto purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, parihānametaṃ;**An individual with bad friends is in decline.*";
P_HTM[2259]="*‘micchādiṭṭhiko purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, parihānametaṃ.**An individual with wrong view is in decline.*";
P_HTM[2260]="*Yassa kassaci, āvuso, saddhā atthi kusalesu dhammesu, hirī atthi …**Whoever has faith, conscience, prudence, energy, and wisdom when it comes to skillful qualities*";
P_HTM[2261]="*ottappaṃ atthi …* **";
P_HTM[2262]="*paññā atthi kusalesu dhammesu, tassa yā ratti vā divaso vā āgacchati, vuddhiyeva pāṭikaṅkhā kusalesu dhammesu no parihāni.**can expect growth, not decline, in skillful qualities, whether by day or by night.*";
P_HTM[2263]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso, juṇhapakkhe candassa yā ratti vā divaso vā āgacchati, vaḍḍhateva vaṇṇena vaḍḍhati maṇḍalena vaḍḍhati ābhāya vaḍḍhati ārohapariṇāhena;**It’s like the moon in the waxing fortnight. Whether by day or by night, its beauty, roundness, light, and diameter and circumference only grow.*";
P_HTM[2264]="*evamevaṃ kho, āvuso, yassa kassaci saddhā atthi kusalesu dhammesu, hirī atthi …**In the same way, whoever has faith, conscience, prudence, energy, and wisdom when it comes to skillful qualities*";
P_HTM[2265]="*ottappaṃ atthi …* **";
P_HTM[2266]="*vīriyaṃ atthi …* **";
P_HTM[2267]="*paññā atthi kusalesu dhammesu, tassa yā ratti vā divaso vā āgacchati, vuddhiyeva pāṭikaṅkhā kusalesu dhammesu no parihāni.**can expect growth, not decline, in skillful qualities, whether by day or by night.*";
P_HTM[2268]="*‘Saddho purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, aparihānametaṃ;**A faithful individual doesn’t decline.*";
P_HTM[2269]="*‘hirīmā purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, aparihānametaṃ;**An individual with a conscience doesn’t decline.*";
P_HTM[2270]="*‘ottappī purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, aparihānametaṃ;**A prudent individual doesn’t decline.*";
P_HTM[2271]="*‘āraddhavīriyo purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, aparihānametaṃ;**An energetic individual doesn’t decline.*";
P_HTM[2272]="*‘paññavā purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, aparihānametaṃ;**A wise individual doesn’t decline.*";
P_HTM[2273]="*‘akkodhano purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, aparihānametaṃ;**A loving individual doesn’t decline.*";
P_HTM[2274]="*‘anupanāhī purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, aparihānametaṃ;**A kind individual doesn’t decline.*";
P_HTM[2275]="*‘appiccho purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, aparihānametaṃ;**An individual with few desires doesn’t decline.*";
P_HTM[2276]="*‘kalyāṇamitto purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, aparihānametaṃ;**An individual with good friends doesn’t decline.*";
P_HTM[2277]="*‘sammādiṭṭhiko purisapuggalo’ti, āvuso, aparihānametan”ti.**An individual with right view doesn’t decline.”*";
P_HTM[2278]="*Atha kho bhagavā paccuṭṭhāya āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha got up and said to Venerable Sāriputta:*";
P_HTM[2279]="*“sādhu sādhu, sāriputta.**“Good, good, Sāriputta!*";
P_HTM[2280]="*Yassa kassaci, sāriputta, saddhā natthi kusalesu dhammesu, hirī natthi …**Whoever has no faith, conscience, prudence, energy, and wisdom when it comes to skillful qualities*";
P_HTM[2281]="*ottappaṃ natthi …* **";
P_HTM[2282]="*vīriyaṃ natthi …* **";
P_HTM[2283]="*paññā natthi kusalesu dhammesu, tassa yā ratti vā divaso vā āgacchati, hāniyeva pāṭikaṅkhā kusalesu dhammesu no vuddhi.**can expect decline, not growth, in skillful qualities, whether by day or by night.*";
P_HTM[2284]="*Seyyathāpi, sāriputta, kāḷapakkhe candassa yā ratti vā divaso vā āgacchati, hāyateva vaṇṇena hāyati maṇḍalena hāyati ābhāya hāyati ārohapariṇāhena;**It’s like the moon in the waning fortnight. Whether by day or by night, its beauty, roundness, light, and diameter and circumference only decline.*";
